{"title_page": "John Inverdale", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = John Inverdale\n|image         = John Inverdale - Aegon Eastbourne (35678389225).jpg\n|image_size    = 200px\n|caption       = Inverdale in 2017\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1957|9|27|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Plymouth]], [[Devon]], [[England]], [[UK]]\n|death_date    =\n|death_place   = \n|nationality   = English\n|other_names   =\n|education     = [[Clifton College]], [[Cardiff Metropolitan University]], [[University of Southampton]]\n|occupation    = Television and radio presenter\n|employer      = [[BBC Sport]], [[ITV Sport]]\n|title         =\n|spouse        = Jackie Inverdale\n|partner       =\n|children      = 2\n|website       =\n|footnotes     =\n|birthname     = John Inverdale\n|religion      =\n}}\n\n'''John Inverdale''' (born 27 September 1957) is an English broadcaster who works for both the [[BBC]] and [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]].\n\nDuring his radio career, he has presented coverage of many major sporting events including the [[Olympic Games]], [[Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]], the [[Grand National]] and the [[FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|title=John Inverdale Biography|url=http://www.speakerscorner.co.uk/speaker/john-inverdale|work=Speakers Corner|accessdate=13 July 2013}}</ref> He was the main television presenter of ''[[Today at Wimbledon]]'' until 2014 and has hosted television coverage of sports programmes including ''[[Rugby Special]]'' and ''[[Grandstand (TV series)|Grandstand]]''. He has presented ITV's coverage of the [[Rugby World Cup]] and the [[French Open]].\n\nSince 2013, Inverdale has been embroiled in several broadcasting [[#Controversy|controversies]], which have prompted criticism as well as articles written in his defence. He earns \u00a3200,000 - \u00a3249,999 annually as a BBC sports presenter and contributor.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-40653861</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nInverdale was born in [[Plymouth]], [[Devon]], the son of a [[Royal Navy]] [[dental surgeon]], [[Captain (naval)|Captain]] John Inverdale, who played [[rugby union]] for [[Devonport Services R.F.C.|Devonport Services]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.navyrugbyunion.co.uk/news/rnru-inter-command-competition-inverdale-trophy-preview|title=RNRU INTER COMMAND COMPETITION - INVERDALE TROPHY - PREVIEW : Royal Navy Rugby Union - Official Site|website=www.navyrugbyunion.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Inverdale was educated at [[Clifton College]] in [[Bristol]] and at the [[University of Southampton]], graduating with a history degree in 1979. He was the editor of the student newspaper ''Wessex News'' (now ''[[Wessex Scene]]'') and captained the university's [[tennis]] team for two years.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sale|first1=Jonathan|title=Passed/Failed: An education in the life of John Inverdale, sports broadcaster|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/passedfailed-an-education-in-the-life-of-john-inverdale-sports-broadcaster-880942.html|work=The Independent|date=30 July 2008}}</ref>\n\nAfter gaining a post-graduate [[journalism]] qualification at [[University of Wales Institute, Cardiff|University of Wales Institute]], [[Cardiff]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/2008/11/11/tv-presenter-inverdale-signs-up-to-save-the-vulcan-pub-91466-22223277/ |title=TV presenter Inverdale signs up to save the Vulcan pub |publisher=Media Wales |work=Wales Online |date=11 November 2008 |accessdate=11 November 2008}}</ref> he began his career with two years at the ''[[Lincolnshire Echo]]'', and then joined [[BBC Radio Lincolnshire]] in 1982.\n\n==Broadcasting career==\n\n===Radio===\nInverdale began to work on the BBC's national radio stations in 1985, firstly on [[BBC Radio 2|Radio 2]]'s sports unit where he presented the final edition of ''Sport on 2'' in August 1990,<ref>{{cite web|url = http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/50decb81644e4b0d9a7da5af278292e3|title = BBC Genome Project|accessdate = 15 March 2019|work = Sport on 2}}</ref> then between 1990 and 1994 at [[BBC Radio 5 (former)|Radio 5]], where he presented the flagship sports programme ''[[5 Live Sport|Sport on 5]]''. In 1994 he became one of the main regular presenters on the relaunched [[BBC Radio 5 Live]]. He presented the drivetime show ''John Inverdale Nationwide'' until 1997, for which he was named [[Sony Radio Academy Awards|Sony Broadcaster of the Year]] in 1997. At 5 Live, he hosted the topical show, ''Any Sporting Questions'', a variation on [[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]]'s ''[[Any Questions]]'', and similarly toured the UK each week. In 2008 he broadcast for 5 Live from the Olympic Games in China. Along with [[Steve Redgrave|Sir Steve Redgrave]] he appeared at [[Shunyi Olympic Rowing-Canoeing Park|Shunyi Rowing Lake]] for the [[2008 Summer Olympics|Olympics]] in [[Beijing]].\n\nInverdale headed 5 Live's coverage of the [[Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]], [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] and [[Commonwealth Games]], [[FIFA World Cup|football]] and [[Rugby Union World Cup|rugby union World Cups]], [[World Athletics Championships]], [[Ryder Cup]], [[the Open Championship|Open Championship]], [[London Marathon]] and [[Cheltenham Festival]].\n\nHe has hosted the station's coverage of [[BBC Sports Personality of the Year]] and occasionally guest presented on Radio 2.\n\nInverdale left 5 Live in March 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://radiotoday.co.uk/2019/03/john-inverdale-to-leave-bbc-radio-5-live-after-25-years/|title = John Inverdale to leave BBC Radio 5 Live after 25 years|date = 15 March 2019|publisher = Radio Today|accessdate = 15 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 Inverdale provided radio commentary to Japan 2019 [[Rugby World Cup]] matches via the official audio commentary available through the [[TuneIn radio]] platform.\n\n===Television===\nInverdale has also worked regularly for [[BBC Television]]. He became the BBC's main Rugby Union anchor in the 2006 [[Six Nations Championship]]s following the departure of [[Steve Rider]] to [[ITV Sport]]. He led ITV's Rugby World Cup coverage in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/presscentre/press-releases/itv-announces-rugby-world-cup-2015-line|title=ITV announces Rugby World Cup 2015 line-up|accessdate=18 June 2017}}</ref> He hosted BBC One's sports chat show, ''On Side'' between 1997\u20132001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/tv_and_radio/on_side/default.stm|title=BBC SPORT - ON SIDE|website=news.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=18 June 2017}}</ref> He presents the BBC's World Cup and Olympic Rowing coverage alongside [[Sir Steve Redgrave]]. In October 2012, he filmed several episodes of Channel 4 show ''[[Countdown (game show)|Countdown]]''. Inverdale has hosted [[ITV Sport|ITV]]'s live [[French Open]] coverage from [[Stade Roland Garros|Roland Garros]] since 2012.<ref>[http://www.itv.com/presscentre/press-releases/itv-sport-announces-french-open-line ITV Sport announces French Open Line-Up], ITV Press Release, 14 May 2014</ref>\n\nFrom 2000\u20132014 he presented ''[[Today at Wimbledon]]'', [[BBC Two]]'s nightly tennis highlights, until the format changed in 2015. This was mainly due to the 2013 Marion Bartoli controversy which led the BBC to drop Inverdale from the show. However, the new version ''Wimbledon 2Day'' hosted by [[Clare Balding]] was ridiculed by the public. Such was the unpopularity of ''Wimbledon 2Day'', a Twitter campaign called \"bring back John Inverdale\" attracted thousands of supporters, with Inverdale claiming that he had \"never been so popular.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ward|first1=Victoria|title=John Inverdale declares he has 'never been so popular' as backlash grows over BBC's revamped Wimbledon highlights|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/11715114/John-Inverdale-declares-he-has-never-been-so-popular-as-backlash-grows-over-BBCs-revamped-Wimbledon-highlights.html|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=21 December 2016|date=3 July 2015}}</ref> The unpopular highlights show was ditched in 2016 and rebranded its original title, ''Today at Wimbledon''. Inverdale is now a member of the main commentary team.\n\nHe appeared as himself in five episodes of 2016 BBC Three comedy ''[[Witless (TV series)|Witless]]'' as the presenter of 'Witpro', a spoof video series about witness protection.\n\n==Controversy==\nOwing to his involvement in multiple broadcasting controversies, Inverdale has been dubbed as \"gaffe-prone\".<ref name=\"gaffe\"/>\n\n===Marion Bartoli===\nOn 6 July 2013, the day of the [[2013 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|Wimbledon Ladies Final]], during a pre-match discussion on [[BBC Radio 5 Live|5 Live]] with commentator [[Lindsay Davenport]], Inverdale said of finalist and eventual winner [[Marion Bartoli]]: \"I just wonder if her dad, because he has obviously been the most influential person in her life, I just wonder if her dad did say to her when she was 12, 13, 14 maybe, 'Listen, you are never going to be, you know, a [[Physical attractiveness|looker]]. You are never going to be somebody like a [[Maria Sharapova|Sharapova]], you're never going to be 5ft 11, you're never going to be somebody with long legs, so you have to compensate for that. You are going to have to be the most dogged, determined fighter that anyone has ever seen on the tennis court if you are going to make it', and she kind of is.\"<ref name=bbc>{{cite news|title=John Inverdale's Bartoli remark prompts Miller letter|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-23352708|accessdate=26 August 2013|newspaper=BBC|date=18 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nInverdale's words prompted criticism on Twitter and other social media, with some alleging they had complained of his \"sexist and patronising\" view of women's tennis in the past.<ref name=\"Duffin\">Patrick Sawer and Claire Duffin [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/tennis/wimbledon/10164511/Wimbledon-2013-BBC-apologise-for-John-Inverdales-Bartoli-not-a-looker-comment.html \"Wimbledon 2013: BBC apologise for John Inverdale's 'Bartoli not a looker\u2019 comment\"], telegraph.co.uk, 6 July 2013</ref>\n\nBartoli was yet to hear a recording of the incident<ref name=radiotimes-2014/> when asked about it at a press conference the following day. She responded: \"It doesn't matter, honestly. I am not blonde, yes. That is a fact. Have I dreamt about having a model contract? No. I'm sorry. But have I dreamed about winning Wimbledon? Absolutely, yes. And to share this moment with my dad was absolutely amazing and I am so proud of it.\"<ref name=ocarrell-2013>{{cite news|last=O'Carrell|first=Lisa|title=John Inverdale's Marion Bartoli comments 'wrong', says BBC news chief|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2013/jul/09/john-inverdale-marion-bartoli-bbc|accessdate=16 July 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=9 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nInverdale himself apologised on air the next day for his \"ham-fisted comments\",<ref name=bbc-2/> saying that he had \"understandably caused something of a furore\"<ref name=bbc/> and that he had apologised to Bartoli by letter.<ref name=bbc-2>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-23214821 \"John Inverdale 'has written to Marion Bartoli over remark'\"], BBC News, 7 July 2013</ref> He also spoke to her at the Champions' Dinner that evening.<ref name=radiotimes-2014/> A BBC spokesman said: \"We accept that this remark was insensitive and for that we apologise.\"<ref name=\"Duffin\"/>\n\nBBC Director of News [[James Harding (journalist)|James Harding]] was asked at a Women in Journalism event the following week whether Inverdale ought to be sacked.<ref name=ocarrell-2013/> Harding said: \"I think he said the wrong thing ... You have got to own your mistakes and apologise for them. I do think it's important that an apology too is an important thing and if you are talking about sacking someone, [you have to ask] is it proportionate. As a licence fee payer I think it was wrong.\"<ref name=ocarrell-2013/> In the initial days the BBC received 674 complaints<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/wimbledon-2013-bbc-receives-674-complaints-over-john-inverdales-sexist-marion-bartoli-comments-8695665.html BBC receives 674 complaints over John Inverdale's 'sexist' Marion Bartoli comments], The Independent, 8 July 2013</ref> \u2013 the number rose as the story gained wider coverage.<ref>[http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/416328/John-Inverdale-s-sexist-complaints-hit-1-250 John Inverdale\u2019s \u2018sexist\u2019 complaints hit 1,250], Sunday Express, 21 July 2013</ref>\n\nJournalist [[Jan Moir]] supported Inverdale, writing: \"The presenter was trying to say, I believe, that Marion Bartoli would never be the kind of sponsorship-bagging, classically beautiful glamazon who would make millions from even a mediocre tennis career, one that had never involved winning a grand slam. For her, the glory would lie in the majesty of her sporting triumph, not in glossy magazine deals selling tights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/debate/article-2369805/JAN-MOIR-Forget-Beeb-sexist-pigs-Commons.html|title=Forget the Beeb, what about the sexist pigs at the Commons?|last=Moir|first=Jan|authorlink=Jan Moir|date=19 July 2013|website=[[Daily Mail]]|access-date=27 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport|Culture Secretary]] [[Maria Miller]] wrote to BBC director general [[Tony Hall, Baron Hall of Birkenhead|Lord Hall]], expressing concern and asking about \"any further action that is likely to be taken\".<ref name=bbc/> In his reply, Hall wrote, \"I agree that the comments made by John during the build-up to the women's final were totally unacceptable and fell well beneath the standards we expect of our presenters.\" Hall added that BBC executives told Inverdale that \"an incident of this nature must never happen again\".<ref name=bbc/> Racehorse trainer [[Charlie Brooks (racehorse trainer)|Charlie Brooks]] defended Inverdale as a \"brilliant broadcaster\" who \"must not be hounded out of the BBC by Maria Miller\". He asserted: \"The [[Horse racing|[horse] racing]] industry should take this opportunity to embrace and support Inverdale. God only knows how many fans he has created with his enthusiasm and in-depth knowledge.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/horseracing/10207608/John-Inverdale-must-not-be-hounded-out-of-the-BBC-by-Maria-Miller-for-comments-about-Marion-Bartoli.html|title=John Inverdale must not be hounded out of the BBC by Maria Miller for comments about Marion Bartoli|last=Brooks|first=Charlie|authorlink=Charlie Brooks (racehorse trainer)|date=28 July 2013|website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=28 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn a joint interview with Bartoli the following year, as promotion for [[ITV Sport]]'s [[2014 French Open]] coverage, Inverdale said he believed Miller's intervention, ten days after the original incident, was likely politically motivated and part of an anti-BBC agenda. Bartoli said: \"I'd known John a long time, and I knew what he was trying to say. At the end of the day I am a tennis player, I know I'm not 6ft tall, I'm not the same long, lean shape as Maria Sharapova, but the beauty of tennis is that anyone can win, tall or short. Something the press took to be negative to me was a positive... In my mind it was never really a story.\"<ref name=\"radiotimes-2014\">[http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-05-25/marion-bartoli-and-john-inverdale-put-aside-last-years-gaffe-to-present-itvs-french-open-coverage \"Marion Bartoli and John Inverdale put aside last year's gaffe to present ITV's French Open coverage\"], Radio Times, 25 May 2014</ref>\n\n===2016 Summer Olympics===\nInverdale received \"intense criticism\" while presenting the [[BBC]]'s coverage of the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]].<ref name=\"bagchi\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/olympics/2016/08/15/why-does-everyone-hate-john-inverdale/|title=Why does everyone hate John Inverdale?|accessdate=18 June 2017}}</ref> He and co-host, Olympic rower [[Steve Redgrave]], were seen to have \"clashed\" multiple times on television, with Redgrave allegedly being afforded little opportunity to speak. The talkative Inverdale called Redgrave [[Oddjob]], the silent Bond villain as a reference to Redgrave's quiet personality. This led to negative social media commentary of Inverdale. Redgrave was observed directing jibes toward Inverdale, shaking a wet umbrella over his head, and even walking off the set. The BBC denied any hostility between the two.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/olympics/2016/08/13/sir-steve-redgrave-and-john-inverdale-in-on-air-spat-during-bbc/|title=Sir Steve Redgrave and John Inverdale in another on-air spat during BBC coverage of Rio Olympics|last=Graham|first=Chris|date=13 August 2016|website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=20 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the men's tennis gold medal final, Inverdale congratulated [[Andy Murray]] on being the first tennis player to win two gold medals; although Murray is the first player to lift two singles golds, [[Serena Williams|Serena]] and [[Venus Williams]] had previously won four golds each between singles and doubles tennis. Inverdale's comment was criticised as sexist and also brought the 2013 Marion Bartoli controversy back to the fore on social media. The BBC stated that the comment was \"a simple error\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/rio-2016-john-inverdale-andy-murray-sexism-row-tennis-olympic-gold-medals-a7191986.html|title=John Inverdale sparks everyday sexism row with claim Andy Murray is first tennis player to win two Olympic golds|last=Blair|first=Olivia|date=15 August 2016|website=[[The Independent]]|access-date=20 August 2016}}</ref> Also following the incident, ''[[The Daily Telegraph|Telegraph]]'' journalist Rob Bagchi wrote a piece titled \"Why does everyone hate John Inverdale?\", in which he defended Inverdale and suggested that critics were enjoying \"the vicarious thrill in a sustained pile-on\".<ref name=\"bagchi\"/> The article was shared on [[Twitter]] by broadcaster [[Jeremy Vine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/theJeremyVine/status/766571489382588416|title=2:44 AM - 19 Aug 2016|last=Vine|first=Jeremy|authorlink=Jeremy Vine|date=19 August 2016|website=Jeremy Vine on Twitter|publisher=[[Twitter]]|access-date=27 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nInverdale experienced further censure when he was accused of \"ignoring\" British heavyweight boxer [[Anthony Joshua]] during an interview.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/olympics/2016/08/18/bbcs-john-inverdale-accused-of-ignoring-anthony-joshua/|title=BBC's John Inverdale accused of 'ignoring' Anthony Joshua during 'disrespectful' interview|last=Davis|first=Callum|date=18 August 2016|website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=20 August 2016}}</ref> Some defended Inverdale, saying he was attempting to catch the eye of French boxer [[Sarah Ourahmoune]], whom they had been speaking of; she eventually joined them to talk.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/rio-2016-john-inverdale-anthony-joshua-bbc-interview-boxing-rude-a7199686.html|title=Rio 2016: John Inverdale accused of being 'monumentally rude' to Anthony Joshua|last=Worley|first=Will|date=19 August 2016|website=[[The Independent]]|access-date=24 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn the final day of the Olympics coverage, Inverdale was criticised again during a boxing broadcast when he interrupted Joshua to speak about the victorious French boxer [[Tony Yoka]], and claimed that Yoka and his partner may have become the first engaged or married couple to both win gold medals at the same Olympics, in spite of British cyclists [[Laura Kenny|Laura Trott]] and her fianc\u00e9 [[Jason Kenny]] both having won multiple golds just days earlier, and married couple [[Kate Richardson-Walsh]] and [[Helen Richardson-Walsh]] having both won gold medals in the women's hockey just two days prior.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/john-inverdale-boxing-engaged-married-couple-trott-kenny-richardson-walsh_uk_57ba09d5e4b042aee74c303c|title=Did John Inverdale Make A 'Golden Couple' Gaffe?|date=21 August 2016|accessdate=18 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe day after this final Rio 2016 controversy for Inverdale, Mark Davies of ''[[The Spectator]]'' penned an article titled \"In defence of John Inverdale\", in which he wrote that the broadcaster had been subjected to a large volume of \"totally unwarranted\" censure. Davies felt it was \"clear\" what Inverdale meant during the Murray and Yoka incidents, and was doing \"what all broadcast interviewers do\" during the Joshua episode by looking for future interviewees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/08/defence-john-inverdale/|title=In defence of John Inverdale|last=Davies|first=Mark|date=22 August 2016|website=[[The Spectator]]|access-date=27 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Other===\nDuring a 2014 [[BBC One]] broadcast, Inverdale said that England \u2013 rather than Great Britain \u2013 would play the United States of America in that year's [[2014 Davis Cup|Davis Cup]]; he apologised later in the programme. The comment nevertheless sparked complaints from viewers who found it to be \"inaccurate and biased\". The BBC called it an \"unintentional slip\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/13144024.BBC_defend__unintentional__Inverdale_gaffe_after_presenter_says_England_rather_than_GB_playing_US_in_Davis_Cup/|title=BBC defend 'unintentional' Inverdale gaffe after presenter says England rather than GB playing US in Davis Cup|date=4 February 2014|website=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|access-date=11 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[BBC Radio 5 Live]]'s coverage of the 2015 [[Cheltenham Festival]], Inverdale said \"rose-cunted\" on air, in reference to [[glasses]]. He swiftly apologised, attributing his language to a \"[[Speech error|slip of the tongue]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/mar/10/john-inverdale-x-rated-comment-cheltenham-festival|title=John Inverdale apologises for X-rated comment on Cheltenham coverage|last=Riach|first=James|date=10 March 2015|website=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=20 August 2016}}</ref> Ben Rumsby in ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' called Inverdale's mistake \"a genuinely unfortunate mangling of the words 'coloured' and 'tinted'\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/horseracing/cheltenham-festival/11461850/Cheltenham-2015-John-Inverdale-apologises-for-making-x-rated-comment-on-air.html|title=Cheltenham 2015: John Inverdale apologises for making x-rated comment on air|last=Rumsby|first=Ben|date=10 March 2015|website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=24 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2016 Wimbledon Championships]], Inverdale commented that tennis player [[Nick Kyrgios]] \"lumbered off like a character from ''[[The Jungle Book]]''\", which led to allegations of racism on social media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/john-inverdale-andy-murray-bbc-rio-2016-controversial-moments-marion-bartoli-nick-kyrgios-a7194186.html|title=John Inverdale: The BBC Rio 2016 broadcaster's most controversial moments|last=Ramgobin|first=Ryan|date=16 August 2016|website=[[The Independent]]|access-date=20 August 2016}}</ref> The BBC declined to comment on the incident, beyond describing the number of complaints received as \"small\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/mediamonkeyblog/2016/jul/11/bbcs-john-inverdale-likens-wimbledon-tennis-star-to-jungle-book-character|title=BBC's John Inverdale likens Wimbledon tennis star to Jungle Book character|date=11 July 2016|website=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=28 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and personal life==\nInverdale received a [[Doctor of Letters]] honorary degree from the [[University of Southampton]] in July 2001. He was awarded an honorary fellowship to the [[University of Wales Institute, Cardiff]] (UWIC) in November 2009.{{Citation needed|date=June 2013}}\n\nInverdale lives in [[Branston, Lincolnshire]] with his wife and two daughters.<ref>[http://lincolnshiresports.com/events/sportsawards2012/john-inverdale/ Lincolnshire Sports Awards 2012 \u2013 Our Presenter John Inverdale]. Lincolnshiresports.com. Retrieved on 27 March 2013.</ref> He made national news in 2005 when his face appeared in many newspapers showing the scars he received whilst playing rugby union for [[Esher RFC|Esher]].<ref>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/john-inverdale-exclusive-rugby-thug-569393 John Inverdale Exclusive: Rugby thug stamped on my head] Mirror.co.uk, 16 December 2005</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyunion/2370093/Player-cited-over-Inverdale-stamping.html Player cited over Inverdale 'stamping'] The Telegraph, 21 December 2005</ref> He is a fan of both [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] and [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] football clubs.<ref>[http://observer.guardian.co.uk/osm/story/0,,727814,00.html Quick-fire round: John Inverdale | Sport | The Observer]. Observer.guardian.co.uk (10 February 2011). Retrieved on 27 March 2013.</ref>\n\nIn 2005 Inverdale became a patron of charity [[Cardiac Risk in the Young]].\n\nHe has publicly stated his love for the band [[Starship (band)|Starship]], and in particular their 1985 song '[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K1b8AhIsSYQ We Built This City On Rock And Roll]'<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06309jx|title=BBC Radio 2 - Sounds of the 70s with Johnnie Walker, John Inverdale|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"gaffe\">The following outlets have labelled Inverdale as \"gaffe-prone\":\n\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/tennis/andy-murray/andy-murray-corrects-gaffe-by-bbc-presenter-john-inverdale-1-4203763|title=Andy Murray corrects gaffe by BBC presenter John Inverdale|website=[[The Scotsman]]|accessdate=18 June 2017}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/john-inverdale-sexism-row-kate-middleton-duchess-of-cambridge-doesnt-understand-rugby-laws-england-a7638341.html|title=Inverdale in fresh sexism row after suggesting Kate doesn't know rugby laws|date=19 March 2017|website=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=18 June 2017}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/olympics/2016/08/17/team-gb-has-barely-put-a-foot-wrong-at-rio-2016--but-the-bbc-jus/|title=Team GB has barely put a foot wrong at Rio 2016 \u2013 but the BBC just keeps on stumbling|website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=18 June 2017}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.eurosport.co.uk/tennis/rio/2016/olympics-rio-2016-andy-murray-gives-williams-sisters-credit-in-john-inverdale-interview_sto5723582/story.shtml|title=Olympics Rio 2016: Andy Murray corrects John Inverdale over gender error in interview|date=15 August 2016|publisher=[[Eurosport]]|accessdate=18 June 2017}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/03/10/jeremy-clarkson-suspended-john-inverdale_n_6840456.html|title=The BBC Just Had The Worst Afternoon Ever...|date=10 March 2015|website=[[HuffPost|HuffPost UK]]|accessdate=18 June 2017}}\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/olympics/83202764/Rio-Olympics-2016-Andy-Murray-puts-BBC-presenter-John-Inverdale-right\n|title=Rio Olympics 2016: Andy Murray puts BBC presenter John Inverdale right|date=16 August 2016|work=[[Stuff.co.nz]]|accessdate=18 June 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|John Inverdale}}\n\n* {{IMDb name|id=0409471|name=John Inverdale }}\n* [http://www.radiowaves.co.uk/story/66093 John Inverdale \u2013 BBC and Canoeing Commentator!] Radio Waves, 31 May 2009 \u2013 Students interview John Inverdale\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Inverdale, John}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Southampton]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Cardiff Metropolitan University]]\n[[Category:BBC Radio 5 Live presenters]]\n[[Category:BBC sports presenters and reporters]]\n[[Category:English radio personalities]]\n[[Category:English sports broadcasters]]\n[[Category:English male journalists]]\n[[Category:English television presenters]]\n[[Category:Golf writers and broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Clifton College]]\n[[Category:People from Plymouth]]\n[[Category:Tennis commentators]]\n[[Category:English male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:People from North Kesteven District]]\n[[Category:Devonport Services R.F.C. players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = John Inverdale\n|image         = John Inverdale - Aegon Eastbourne (35678389225).jpg\n|image_size    = 200px\n|caption       = Inverdale in 2017\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1957|9|27|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Plymouth]], [[Devon]], [[England]], [[UK]]\n|death_date    =\n|death_place   = \n|nationality   = English\n|other_names   =\n|education     = [[Clifton College]], [[Cardiff Metropolitan University]], [[University of Southampton]]\n|occupation    = Television and radio presenter\n|employer      = [[BBC Sport]], [[ITV Sport]]\n|title         =\n|spouse        = Jackie Inverdale\n|partner       =\n|children      = 2\n|website       =\n|footnotes     =\n|birthname     = John Inverdale\n|religion      =\n}}\n\n'''John Inverdale''' (born 27 September 1957) is an English broadcaster who works for both the [[BBC]] and [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]].\n\nDuring his radio career, he has presented coverage of many major sporting events including the [[Olympic Games]], [[Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]], the [[Grand National]] and the [[FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|title=John Inverdale Biography|url=http://www.speakerscorner.co.uk/speaker/john-inverdale|work=Speakers Corner|accessdate=13 July 2013}}</ref> He was the main television presenter of ''[[Today at Wimbledon]]'' until 2014 and has hosted television coverage of sports programmes including ''[[Rugby Special]]'' and ''[[Grandstand (TV series)|Grandstand]]''. He has presented ITV's coverage of the [[Rugby World Cup]] and the [[French Open]].\n\nSince 2013, Inverdale has been embroiled in several broadcasting [[#Controversy|controversies]], which have prompted criticism as well as articles written in his defence. He earns \u00a3200,000 - \u00a3249,999 annually as a BBC sports presenter and contributor.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-40653861</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nInverdale was born in [[Plymouth]], [[Devon]], the son of a [[Royal Navy]] [[dental surgeon]], [[Captain (naval)|Captain]] John Inverdale, who played [[rugby union]] for [[Devonport Services R.F.C.|Devonport Services]].{{citation needed|date=July 2015}} Inverdale was educated at [[Clifton College]] in [[Bristol]] and at the [[University of Southampton]], graduating with a history degree in 1979. He was the editor of the student newspaper ''Wessex News'' (now ''[[Wessex Scene]]'') and captained the university's [[tennis]] team for two years.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sale|first1=Jonathan|title=Passed/Failed: An education in the life of John Inverdale, sports broadcaster|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/passedfailed-an-education-in-the-life-of-john-inverdale-sports-broadcaster-880942.html|work=The Independent|date=30 July 2008}}</ref>\n\nAfter gaining a post-graduate [[journalism]] qualification at [[University of Wales Institute, Cardiff|University of Wales Institute]], [[Cardiff]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/2008/11/11/tv-presenter-inverdale-signs-up-to-save-the-vulcan-pub-91466-22223277/ |title=TV presenter Inverdale signs up to save the Vulcan pub |publisher=Media Wales |work=Wales Online |date=11 November 2008 |accessdate=11 November 2008}}</ref> he began his career with two years at the ''[[Lincolnshire Echo]]'', and then joined [[BBC Radio Lincolnshire]] in 1982.\n\n==Broadcasting career==\n\n===Radio===\nInverdale began to work on the BBC's national radio stations in 1985, firstly on [[BBC Radio 2|Radio 2]]'s sports unit where he presented the final edition of ''Sport on 2'' in August 1990,<ref>{{cite web|url = http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/50decb81644e4b0d9a7da5af278292e3|title = BBC Genome Project|accessdate = 15 March 2019|work = Sport on 2}}</ref> then between 1990 and 1994 at [[BBC Radio 5 (former)|Radio 5]], where he presented the flagship sports programme ''[[5 Live Sport|Sport on 5]]''. In 1994 he became one of the main regular presenters on the relaunched [[BBC Radio 5 Live]]. He presented the drivetime show ''John Inverdale Nationwide'' until 1997, for which he was named [[Sony Radio Academy Awards|Sony Broadcaster of the Year]] in 1997. At 5 Live, he hosted the topical show, ''Any Sporting Questions'', a variation on [[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]]'s ''[[Any Questions]]'', and similarly toured the UK each week. In 2008 he broadcast for 5 Live from the Olympic Games in China. Along with [[Steve Redgrave|Sir Steve Redgrave]] he appeared at [[Shunyi Olympic Rowing-Canoeing Park|Shunyi Rowing Lake]] for the [[2008 Summer Olympics|Olympics]] in [[Beijing]].\n\nInverdale headed 5 Live's coverage of the [[Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]], [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] and [[Commonwealth Games]], [[FIFA World Cup|football]] and [[Rugby Union World Cup|rugby union World Cups]], [[World Athletics Championships]], [[Ryder Cup]], [[the Open Championship|Open Championship]], [[London Marathon]] and [[Cheltenham Festival]].\n\nHe has hosted the station's coverage of [[BBC Sports Personality of the Year]] and occasionally guest presented on Radio 2.\n\nInverdale left 5 Live in March 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://radiotoday.co.uk/2019/03/john-inverdale-to-leave-bbc-radio-5-live-after-25-years/|title = John Inverdale to leave BBC Radio 5 Live after 25 years|date = 15 March 2019|publisher = Radio Today|accessdate = 15 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 Inverdale provided radio commentary to Japan 2019 [[Rugby World Cup]] matches via the official audio commentary available through the [[TuneIn radio]] platform.\n\n===Television===\nInverdale has also worked regularly for [[BBC Television]]. He became the BBC's main Rugby Union anchor in the 2006 [[Six Nations Championship]]s following the departure of [[Steve Rider]] to [[ITV Sport]]. He led ITV's Rugby World Cup coverage in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/presscentre/press-releases/itv-announces-rugby-world-cup-2015-line|title=ITV announces Rugby World Cup 2015 line-up|accessdate=18 June 2017}}</ref> He hosted BBC One's sports chat show, ''On Side'' between 1997\u20132001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/tv_and_radio/on_side/default.stm|title=BBC SPORT - ON SIDE|website=news.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=18 June 2017}}</ref> He presents the BBC's World Cup and Olympic Rowing coverage alongside [[Sir Steve Redgrave]]. In October 2012, he filmed several episodes of Channel 4 show ''[[Countdown (game show)|Countdown]]''. Inverdale has hosted [[ITV Sport|ITV]]'s live [[French Open]] coverage from [[Stade Roland Garros|Roland Garros]] since 2012.<ref>[http://www.itv.com/presscentre/press-releases/itv-sport-announces-french-open-line ITV Sport announces French Open Line-Up], ITV Press Release, 14 May 2014</ref>\n\nFrom 2000\u20132014 he presented ''[[Today at Wimbledon]]'', [[BBC Two]]'s nightly tennis highlights, until the format changed in 2015. This was mainly due to the 2013 Marion Bartoli controversy which led the BBC to drop Inverdale from the show. However, the new version ''Wimbledon 2Day'' hosted by [[Clare Balding]] was ridiculed by the public. Such was the unpopularity of ''Wimbledon 2Day'', a Twitter campaign called \"bring back John Inverdale\" attracted thousands of supporters, with Inverdale claiming that he had \"never been so popular.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ward|first1=Victoria|title=John Inverdale declares he has 'never been so popular' as backlash grows over BBC's revamped Wimbledon highlights|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/11715114/John-Inverdale-declares-he-has-never-been-so-popular-as-backlash-grows-over-BBCs-revamped-Wimbledon-highlights.html|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=21 December 2016|date=3 July 2015}}</ref> The unpopular highlights show was ditched in 2016 and rebranded its original title, ''Today at Wimbledon''. Inverdale is now a member of the main commentary team.\n\nHe appeared as himself in five episodes of 2016 BBC Three comedy ''[[Witless (TV series)|Witless]]'' as the presenter of 'Witpro', a spoof video series about witness protection.\n\n==Controversy==\nOwing to his involvement in multiple broadcasting controversies, Inverdale has been dubbed as \"gaffe-prone\".<ref name=\"gaffe\"/>\n\n===Marion Bartoli===\nOn 6 July 2013, the day of the [[2013 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|Wimbledon Ladies Final]], during a pre-match discussion on [[BBC Radio 5 Live|5 Live]] with commentator [[Lindsay Davenport]], Inverdale said of finalist and eventual winner [[Marion Bartoli]]: \"I just wonder if her dad, because he has obviously been the most influential person in her life, I just wonder if her dad did say to her when she was 12, 13, 14 maybe, 'Listen, you are never going to be, you know, a [[Physical attractiveness|looker]]. You are never going to be somebody like a [[Maria Sharapova|Sharapova]], you're never going to be 5ft 11, you're never going to be somebody with long legs, so you have to compensate for that. You are going to have to be the most dogged, determined fighter that anyone has ever seen on the tennis court if you are going to make it', and she kind of is.\"<ref name=bbc>{{cite news|title=John Inverdale's Bartoli remark prompts Miller letter|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-23352708|accessdate=26 August 2013|newspaper=BBC|date=18 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nInverdale's words prompted criticism on Twitter and other social media, with some alleging they had complained of his \"sexist and patronising\" view of women's tennis in the past.<ref name=\"Duffin\">Patrick Sawer and Claire Duffin [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/tennis/wimbledon/10164511/Wimbledon-2013-BBC-apologise-for-John-Inverdales-Bartoli-not-a-looker-comment.html \"Wimbledon 2013: BBC apologise for John Inverdale's 'Bartoli not a looker\u2019 comment\"], telegraph.co.uk, 6 July 2013</ref>\n\nBartoli was yet to hear a recording of the incident<ref name=radiotimes-2014/> when asked about it at a press conference the following day. She responded: \"It doesn't matter, honestly. I am not blonde, yes. That is a fact. Have I dreamt about having a model contract? No. I'm sorry. But have I dreamed about winning Wimbledon? Absolutely, yes. And to share this moment with my dad was absolutely amazing and I am so proud of it.\"<ref name=ocarrell-2013>{{cite news|last=O'Carrell|first=Lisa|title=John Inverdale's Marion Bartoli comments 'wrong', says BBC news chief|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2013/jul/09/john-inverdale-marion-bartoli-bbc|accessdate=16 July 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=9 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nInverdale himself apologised on air the next day for his \"ham-fisted comments\",<ref name=bbc-2/> saying that he had \"understandably caused something of a furore\"<ref name=bbc/> and that he had apologised to Bartoli by letter.<ref name=bbc-2>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-23214821 \"John Inverdale 'has written to Marion Bartoli over remark'\"], BBC News, 7 July 2013</ref> He also spoke to her at the Champions' Dinner that evening.<ref name=radiotimes-2014/> A BBC spokesman said: \"We accept that this remark was insensitive and for that we apologise.\"<ref name=\"Duffin\"/>\n\nBBC Director of News [[James Harding (journalist)|James Harding]] was asked at a Women in Journalism event the following week whether Inverdale ought to be sacked.<ref name=ocarrell-2013/> Harding said: \"I think he said the wrong thing ... You have got to own your mistakes and apologise for them. I do think it's important that an apology too is an important thing and if you are talking about sacking someone, [you have to ask] is it proportionate. As a licence fee payer I think it was wrong.\"<ref name=ocarrell-2013/> In the initial days the BBC received 674 complaints<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/wimbledon-2013-bbc-receives-674-complaints-over-john-inverdales-sexist-marion-bartoli-comments-8695665.html BBC receives 674 complaints over John Inverdale's 'sexist' Marion Bartoli comments], The Independent, 8 July 2013</ref> \u2013 the number rose as the story gained wider coverage.<ref>[http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/416328/John-Inverdale-s-sexist-complaints-hit-1-250 John Inverdale\u2019s \u2018sexist\u2019 complaints hit 1,250], Sunday Express, 21 July 2013</ref>\n\nJournalist [[Jan Moir]] supported Inverdale, writing: \"The presenter was trying to say, I believe, that Marion Bartoli would never be the kind of sponsorship-bagging, classically beautiful glamazon who would make millions from even a mediocre tennis career, one that had never involved winning a grand slam. For her, the glory would lie in the majesty of her sporting triumph, not in glossy magazine deals selling tights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/debate/article-2369805/JAN-MOIR-Forget-Beeb-sexist-pigs-Commons.html|title=Forget the Beeb, what about the sexist pigs at the Commons?|last=Moir|first=Jan|authorlink=Jan Moir|date=19 July 2013|website=[[Daily Mail]]|access-date=27 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport|Culture Secretary]] [[Maria Miller]] wrote to BBC director general [[Tony Hall, Baron Hall of Birkenhead|Lord Hall]], expressing concern and asking about \"any further action that is likely to be taken\".<ref name=bbc/> In his reply, Hall wrote, \"I agree that the comments made by John during the build-up to the women's final were totally unacceptable and fell well beneath the standards we expect of our presenters.\" Hall added that BBC executives told Inverdale that \"an incident of this nature must never happen again\".<ref name=bbc/> Racehorse trainer [[Charlie Brooks (racehorse trainer)|Charlie Brooks]] defended Inverdale as a \"brilliant broadcaster\" who \"must not be hounded out of the BBC by Maria Miller\". He asserted: \"The [[Horse racing|[horse] racing]] industry should take this opportunity to embrace and support Inverdale. God only knows how many fans he has created with his enthusiasm and in-depth knowledge.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/horseracing/10207608/John-Inverdale-must-not-be-hounded-out-of-the-BBC-by-Maria-Miller-for-comments-about-Marion-Bartoli.html|title=John Inverdale must not be hounded out of the BBC by Maria Miller for comments about Marion Bartoli|last=Brooks|first=Charlie|authorlink=Charlie Brooks (racehorse trainer)|date=28 July 2013|website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=28 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn a joint interview with Bartoli the following year, as promotion for [[ITV Sport]]'s [[2014 French Open]] coverage, Inverdale said he believed Miller's intervention, ten days after the original incident, was likely politically motivated and part of an anti-BBC agenda. Bartoli said: \"I'd known John a long time, and I knew what he was trying to say. At the end of the day I am a tennis player, I know I'm not 6ft tall, I'm not the same long, lean shape as Maria Sharapova, but the beauty of tennis is that anyone can win, tall or short. Something the press took to be negative to me was a positive... In my mind it was never really a story.\"<ref name=\"radiotimes-2014\">[http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-05-25/marion-bartoli-and-john-inverdale-put-aside-last-years-gaffe-to-present-itvs-french-open-coverage \"Marion Bartoli and John Inverdale put aside last year's gaffe to present ITV's French Open coverage\"], Radio Times, 25 May 2014</ref>\n\n===2016 Summer Olympics===\nInverdale received \"intense criticism\" while presenting the [[BBC]]'s coverage of the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]].<ref name=\"bagchi\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/olympics/2016/08/15/why-does-everyone-hate-john-inverdale/|title=Why does everyone hate John Inverdale?|accessdate=18 June 2017}}</ref> He and co-host, Olympic rower [[Steve Redgrave]], were seen to have \"clashed\" multiple times on television, with Redgrave allegedly being afforded little opportunity to speak. The talkative Inverdale called Redgrave [[Oddjob]], the silent Bond villain as a reference to Redgrave's quiet personality. This led to negative social media commentary of Inverdale. Redgrave was observed directing jibes toward Inverdale, shaking a wet umbrella over his head, and even walking off the set. The BBC denied any hostility between the two.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/olympics/2016/08/13/sir-steve-redgrave-and-john-inverdale-in-on-air-spat-during-bbc/|title=Sir Steve Redgrave and John Inverdale in another on-air spat during BBC coverage of Rio Olympics|last=Graham|first=Chris|date=13 August 2016|website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=20 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the men's tennis gold medal final, Inverdale congratulated [[Andy Murray]] on being the first tennis player to win two gold medals; although Murray is the first player to lift two singles golds, [[Serena Williams|Serena]] and [[Venus Williams]] had previously won four golds each between singles and doubles tennis. Inverdale's comment was criticised as sexist and also brought the 2013 Marion Bartoli controversy back to the fore on social media. The BBC stated that the comment was \"a simple error\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/rio-2016-john-inverdale-andy-murray-sexism-row-tennis-olympic-gold-medals-a7191986.html|title=John Inverdale sparks everyday sexism row with claim Andy Murray is first tennis player to win two Olympic golds|last=Blair|first=Olivia|date=15 August 2016|website=[[The Independent]]|access-date=20 August 2016}}</ref> Also following the incident, ''[[The Daily Telegraph|Telegraph]]'' journalist Rob Bagchi wrote a piece titled \"Why does everyone hate John Inverdale?\", in which he defended Inverdale and suggested that critics were enjoying \"the vicarious thrill in a sustained pile-on\".<ref name=\"bagchi\"/> The article was shared on [[Twitter]] by broadcaster [[Jeremy Vine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/theJeremyVine/status/766571489382588416|title=2:44 AM - 19 Aug 2016|last=Vine|first=Jeremy|authorlink=Jeremy Vine|date=19 August 2016|website=Jeremy Vine on Twitter|publisher=[[Twitter]]|access-date=27 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nInverdale experienced further censure when he was accused of \"ignoring\" British heavyweight boxer [[Anthony Joshua]] during an interview.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/olympics/2016/08/18/bbcs-john-inverdale-accused-of-ignoring-anthony-joshua/|title=BBC's John Inverdale accused of 'ignoring' Anthony Joshua during 'disrespectful' interview|last=Davis|first=Callum|date=18 August 2016|website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=20 August 2016}}</ref> Some defended Inverdale, saying he was attempting to catch the eye of French boxer [[Sarah Ourahmoune]], whom they had been speaking of; she eventually joined them to talk.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/rio-2016-john-inverdale-anthony-joshua-bbc-interview-boxing-rude-a7199686.html|title=Rio 2016: John Inverdale accused of being 'monumentally rude' to Anthony Joshua|last=Worley|first=Will|date=19 August 2016|website=[[The Independent]]|access-date=24 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn the final day of the Olympics coverage, Inverdale was criticised again during a boxing broadcast when he interrupted Joshua to speak about the victorious French boxer [[Tony Yoka]], and claimed that Yoka and his partner may have become the first engaged or married couple to both win gold medals at the same Olympics, in spite of British cyclists [[Laura Kenny|Laura Trott]] and her fianc\u00e9 [[Jason Kenny]] both having won multiple golds just days earlier, and married couple [[Kate Richardson-Walsh]] and [[Helen Richardson-Walsh]] having both won gold medals in the women's hockey just two days prior.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/john-inverdale-boxing-engaged-married-couple-trott-kenny-richardson-walsh_uk_57ba09d5e4b042aee74c303c|title=Did John Inverdale Make A 'Golden Couple' Gaffe?|date=21 August 2016|accessdate=18 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe day after this final Rio 2016 controversy for Inverdale, Mark Davies of ''[[The Spectator]]'' penned an article titled \"In defence of John Inverdale\", in which he wrote that the broadcaster had been subjected to a large volume of \"totally unwarranted\" censure. Davies felt it was \"clear\" what Inverdale meant during the Murray and Yoka incidents, and was doing \"what all broadcast interviewers do\" during the Joshua episode by looking for future interviewees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/08/defence-john-inverdale/|title=In defence of John Inverdale|last=Davies|first=Mark|date=22 August 2016|website=[[The Spectator]]|access-date=27 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Other===\nDuring a 2014 [[BBC One]] broadcast, Inverdale said that England \u2013 rather than Great Britain \u2013 would play the United States of America in that year's [[2014 Davis Cup|Davis Cup]]; he apologised later in the programme. The comment nevertheless sparked complaints from viewers who found it to be \"inaccurate and biased\". The BBC called it an \"unintentional slip\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/13144024.BBC_defend__unintentional__Inverdale_gaffe_after_presenter_says_England_rather_than_GB_playing_US_in_Davis_Cup/|title=BBC defend 'unintentional' Inverdale gaffe after presenter says England rather than GB playing US in Davis Cup|date=4 February 2014|website=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|access-date=11 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[BBC Radio 5 Live]]'s coverage of the 2015 [[Cheltenham Festival]], Inverdale said \"rose-cunted\" on air, in reference to [[glasses]]. He swiftly apologised, attributing his language to a \"[[Speech error|slip of the tongue]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/mar/10/john-inverdale-x-rated-comment-cheltenham-festival|title=John Inverdale apologises for X-rated comment on Cheltenham coverage|last=Riach|first=James|date=10 March 2015|website=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=20 August 2016}}</ref> Ben Rumsby in ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' called Inverdale's mistake \"a genuinely unfortunate mangling of the words 'coloured' and 'tinted'\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/horseracing/cheltenham-festival/11461850/Cheltenham-2015-John-Inverdale-apologises-for-making-x-rated-comment-on-air.html|title=Cheltenham 2015: John Inverdale apologises for making x-rated comment on air|last=Rumsby|first=Ben|date=10 March 2015|website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=24 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2016 Wimbledon Championships]], Inverdale commented that tennis player [[Nick Kyrgios]] \"lumbered off like a character from ''[[The Jungle Book]]''\", which led to allegations of racism on social media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/john-inverdale-andy-murray-bbc-rio-2016-controversial-moments-marion-bartoli-nick-kyrgios-a7194186.html|title=John Inverdale: The BBC Rio 2016 broadcaster's most controversial moments|last=Ramgobin|first=Ryan|date=16 August 2016|website=[[The Independent]]|access-date=20 August 2016}}</ref> The BBC declined to comment on the incident, beyond describing the number of complaints received as \"small\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/mediamonkeyblog/2016/jul/11/bbcs-john-inverdale-likens-wimbledon-tennis-star-to-jungle-book-character|title=BBC's John Inverdale likens Wimbledon tennis star to Jungle Book character|date=11 July 2016|website=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=28 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and personal life==\nInverdale received a [[Doctor of Letters]] honorary degree from the [[University of Southampton]] in July 2001. He was awarded an honorary fellowship to the [[University of Wales Institute, Cardiff]] (UWIC) in November 2009.{{Citation needed|date=June 2013}}\n\nInverdale lives in [[Branston, Lincolnshire]] with his wife and two daughters.<ref>[http://lincolnshiresports.com/events/sportsawards2012/john-inverdale/ Lincolnshire Sports Awards 2012 \u2013 Our Presenter John Inverdale]. Lincolnshiresports.com. Retrieved on 27 March 2013.</ref> He made national news in 2005 when his face appeared in many newspapers showing the scars he received whilst playing rugby union for [[Esher RFC|Esher]].<ref>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/john-inverdale-exclusive-rugby-thug-569393 John Inverdale Exclusive: Rugby thug stamped on my head] Mirror.co.uk, 16 December 2005</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyunion/2370093/Player-cited-over-Inverdale-stamping.html Player cited over Inverdale 'stamping'] The Telegraph, 21 December 2005</ref> He is a fan of both [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] and [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] football clubs.<ref>[http://observer.guardian.co.uk/osm/story/0,,727814,00.html Quick-fire round: John Inverdale | Sport | The Observer]. Observer.guardian.co.uk (10 February 2011). Retrieved on 27 March 2013.</ref>\n\nIn 2005 Inverdale became a patron of charity [[Cardiac Risk in the Young]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"gaffe\">The following outlets have labelled Inverdale as \"gaffe-prone\":\n\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/tennis/andy-murray/andy-murray-corrects-gaffe-by-bbc-presenter-john-inverdale-1-4203763|title=Andy Murray corrects gaffe by BBC presenter John Inverdale|website=[[The Scotsman]]|accessdate=18 June 2017}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/john-inverdale-sexism-row-kate-middleton-duchess-of-cambridge-doesnt-understand-rugby-laws-england-a7638341.html|title=Inverdale in fresh sexism row after suggesting Kate doesn't know rugby laws|date=19 March 2017|website=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=18 June 2017}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/olympics/2016/08/17/team-gb-has-barely-put-a-foot-wrong-at-rio-2016--but-the-bbc-jus/|title=Team GB has barely put a foot wrong at Rio 2016 \u2013 but the BBC just keeps on stumbling|website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=18 June 2017}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.eurosport.co.uk/tennis/rio/2016/olympics-rio-2016-andy-murray-gives-williams-sisters-credit-in-john-inverdale-interview_sto5723582/story.shtml|title=Olympics Rio 2016: Andy Murray corrects John Inverdale over gender error in interview|date=15 August 2016|publisher=[[Eurosport]]|accessdate=18 June 2017}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/03/10/jeremy-clarkson-suspended-john-inverdale_n_6840456.html|title=The BBC Just Had The Worst Afternoon Ever...|date=10 March 2015|website=[[HuffPost|HuffPost UK]]|accessdate=18 June 2017}}\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/olympics/83202764/Rio-Olympics-2016-Andy-Murray-puts-BBC-presenter-John-Inverdale-right\n|title=Rio Olympics 2016: Andy Murray puts BBC presenter John Inverdale right|date=16 August 2016|work=[[Stuff.co.nz]]|accessdate=18 June 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|John Inverdale}}\n\n* {{IMDb name|id=0409471|name=John Inverdale }}\n* [http://www.radiowaves.co.uk/story/66093 John Inverdale \u2013 BBC and Canoeing Commentator!] Radio Waves, 31 May 2009 \u2013 Students interview John Inverdale\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Inverdale, John}}