{"title_page": "Crosstalk", "text_new": "{{other uses|Crosstalk (disambiguation)}}\n{{distinguish|Spill (audio)}}\nIn [[electronics]], '''crosstalk''' is any phenomenon by which a [[signal]] transmitted on one [[Electronic circuit|circuit]] or [[Communication channel|channel]] of a [[transmission system]] creates an undesired effect in another circuit or channel. Crosstalk is usually caused by undesired [[capacitive coupling|capacitive]], [[inductive coupling|inductive]], or [[conductive coupling]] from one circuit or channel to another.\n\nCrosstalk is a significant issue in [[structured cabling]], [[audio electronics]], [[integrated circuit design]], [[wireless communication]] and other [[communications system]]s.\n\n==Mechanisms==\n===Electromagnetic field interference===\nEvery electrical signal is associated with a varying field, whether electrical, magnetic or travelling. Where these fields overlap, they interfere with each other's signal. For example if two wires next to each other carry different signals, the currents in them will create magnetic fields which will induce a smaller signal in the neighbouring wire.\n\n===Common impedance coupling===\nIn electrical circuits sharing a common signal return path, electrical impedance in the return path creates common impedance coupling between the signals, resulting in crosstalk.<ref>[http://learnemc.com/common-impedance-coupling LearnEMC Web Site: Common-Impedance Coupling]</ref><ref>K.-H. Gonschorek and R. Vick: Electromagnetic Compatibility for Device Design and System Integration, Springer, Berlin Heidelberg, 2009, isbn 978-3-642-03289-9, page 90</ref>\n\n==In cabling==\nIn structured cabling, crosstalk refers to [[electromagnetic interference]] from one unshielded [[twisted pair]] to another twisted pair, normally running in parallel. Signals traveling through adjacent pairs of wire create magnetic fields which interact with each other, inducing interference in the neighboring pair. The pair causing the interference is called the \u201cdisturbing pair\u201d, while the pair experiencing the interference is the \u201cdisturbed pair\u201d.\n\n;Near end crosstalk (NEXT):  NEXT is a measure of the ability of a cable to reject crosstalk, so the higher the NEXT value, the greater the rejection of crosstalk at the local connection. It is referred to as Near End because the interference between the two signals in the cable is measured at the same end of the cable as the interfering transmitter. The NEXT value for a given cable type is generally expressed in decibels per feet or decibels per 1000 feet and varies with the frequency of transmission. General specifications for cabling (such as CAT 5) usually include the minimum NEXT values.<ref name=\"lanshack\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lanshack.com/cat5e-tutorial.aspx |title=Category 5 / 5E & Cat 6 Cabling Tutorial and FAQ's |publisher=lanshack.com |accessdate=2013-01-05 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117171629/http://www.lanshack.com/cat5e-tutorial.aspx |archivedate=2013-01-17 }}</ref>\n\n;{{Anchor|PSNEXT}}Power sum near end crosstalk (PSNEXT)\n:PSNEXT is a NEXT measurement which includes the sum of crosstalk contributions from all adjacent pairs as an algebraic sum of the NEXT of the three wire pairs as they affect the fourth pair in a four-pair cable (e.g., Category 6 cable).<ref name=\"lanshack\"/> The Superior Modular Products White paper<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.superiormod.com/smp/pages/support/White%20Paper%20-%20RJ21X.pdf |title=Component Level PowerSum Compliance and RJ21X Connectivity Solutions (Superior Modular Products White paper) |accessdate=2008-09-13 |format=PDF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060716043452/http://www.superiormod.com/smp/pages/support/White%20Paper%20-%20RJ21X.pdf |archivedate=July 16, 2006 }}</ref> states that the testing process for PSNEXT consists of measuring all pair-to-pair crosstalk combinations and then summing all of the values for each pair. The specification was developed to directly address the effect of transmissions on multiple adjacent pairs on the pair being tested and is relevant to all connecting hardware and associated communications cables.\n\n:Cabling bandwidths in excess of 100&nbsp;MHz ([[Category 5 cable]] bandwidth) make consideration of PSNEXT more important as [[Gigabit Ethernet]] through [[Cat-6]] uses all four wire pairs simultaneously and bidirectionally. The additional wire pair usage and growing bandwidth increases the need to keep NEXT in check.\n\n;Far end crosstalk (FEXT): FEXT measures the interference between two pairs of a cable measured at the far end of the cable with respect to the interfering transmitter.<ref name=\"lanshack\"/>\n\n;Equal level far end crosstalk (ELFEXT): ELFEXT measures the FEXT with attenuation compensation.<ref name=\"lanshack\"/>\n\n;{{visible anchor|Alien crosstalk}} (AXT): AXT is interference caused by other cables routed close to the cable of interest as opposed to signals contained in the same cable.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.comnews.com/features/2009_february/0209_web3_eliminating.aspx |title=Eliminating alien crosstalk |publisher=Communications News |date=February 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100209073156/http://www.comnews.com/features/2009_february/0209_web3_eliminating.aspx |archivedate=2010-02-09 }}</ref>\n\n==In audio==\n[[File:IBA Crosstalk weighting curve.svg|400px|right]]\n\nIn [[stereo]] audio reproduction, crosstalk can refer to signal leaking across from one program channel to another, reducing channel separation and [[stereo imaging]]. Crosstalk between channels in mixing consoles, and between studio feeds is a much more noticeable problem, as these are likely to be carrying very different programmes or material.\n\nCrosstalk is an electrical effect and can be quantified with a crosstalk measurement. Crosstalk measurements are made on audio systems to determine the amount of signal leaking across from one channel to another. The [[Independent Broadcasting Authority]] published a [[weighting curve]] for use in crosstalk measurement that gives due emphasis to the subjective audibility of different frequencies. In the absence of any international standards, this is still in use despite the demise of the IBA.{{cn|date=December 2017}}\n\nGood crosstalk performance for a stereo system is not difficult to achieve in today's [[digital audio]] systems, though it was hard to keep below the desired figure of -30&nbsp;dB{{cn|date=December 2017}} or so on [[vinyl record]]ings and [[FM radio]].\n\n==Other examples==\nIn [[telecommunication]] or [[telephony]], crosstalk is often distinguishable as pieces of speech or [[in-band signaling]] tones leaking from other people's connections.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.its.bldrdoc.gov/fs-1037/dir-009/_1340.htm |work=Federal Standard 1037C glossary |title=crosstalk (XT) |access-date=2018-03-26}}</ref> If the connection is analog, [[twisted pair]] cabling can often be used to reduce crosstalk. Alternatively, the signals can be converted to digital form, which is typically less susceptible to crosstalk.\n\nIn [[wireless communication]], crosstalk is often denoted [[co-channel interference]], and is related to [[adjacent-channel interference]].{{Clarify|date=February 2009}}\n\nIn [[integrated circuit design]], crosstalk normally refers to a signal affecting another nearby signal. Usually the coupling is capacitive, and to the nearest neighbor, but other forms of coupling and effects on signal further away are sometimes important, especially in analog designs. See [[signal integrity]] for tools used to measure and prevent this problem, and [[substrate coupling]] for a discussion of crosstalk conveyed through the [[integrated circuit]] substrate. There are a wide variety of repair solutions, with increased spacing, wire re-ordering, and shielding being the most common.\n\nIn full-field optical coherence [[tomography]], \"crosstalk\" refers to the phenomenon that due to highly scattering objects, multiple scattered photons reach the image plane and generate coherent signal after traveling a pathlength that matches that of the sample depth within a coherence length.\n\nIn [[3D display|stereoscopic 3D displays]], \"crosstalk\" refers to the incomplete isolation of the left and right image channels so that one leaks or bleeds into the other - like a double exposure, which produces a [[Ghosting (television)|ghosting]] effect.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Attenuation-to-crosstalk ratio]]\n*[[Audio system measurements]]\n*[[Co-channel interference]] (CCI)\n*[[Print-through]]\n*[[Signal integrity]]\n*[[Signal-to-interference ratio]] (SIR or ''S''/''I''), also known as [[carrier-to-interference ratio]] (CIR or ''C''/''I'')\n*[[Substrate coupling]]\n*[[Unger model]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{FS1037C MS188}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wiktionary|crosstalk}}\n*[http://download.intel.com/education/highered/signal/ELCT762/class19_Crosstalk_overview.ppt Educational slideshow on capacitive and inductive crosstalk]\n*[https://www.webcitation.org/62gSRsABm?url=http://www.ieee.li/pdf/viewgraphs/minimizing_crosstalk_wiring_cabling.pdf Minimizing Crosstalk in Wiring and Cabling]\n\n[[Category:Electrical phenomena]]\n[[Category:Electrical parameters]]\n[[Category:Electromagnetic compatibility]]\n[[Category:Audio amplifier specifications]]\n[[Category:Telecommunication theory]]\n[[Category:Audio engineering]]\n[[Category:Broadcast engineering]]\n[[Category:Sound measurements]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|Crosstalk (disambiguation)}}\n{{distinguish|Spill (audio)}}\nIn [[electronics]], '''crosstalk''' is any phenomenon by which a [[signal]] transmitted on one [[Electronic circuit|circuit]] or [[Communication channel|channel]] of a [[transmission system]] creates an undesired effect in another circuit or channel. Crosstalk is usually caused by undesired [[capacitive coupling|capacitive]], [[inductive coupling|inductive]], or [[conductive coupling]] from one circuit or channel to another.\n\nCrosstalk is a significant issue in [[structured cabling]], [[audio electronics]], [[integrated circuit design]], [[wireless communication]] and other [[communications system]]s.\n\n==Mechanisms==\n===Electromagnetic field interference===\nEvery electrical signal is associated with a varying fields, whether electrical, magnetic or travelling. Where these fields overlap, they interfere with each other's signal. For example if two wires next to each other carry different signals, the currents in them will create magnetic fields which will induce a smaller signal in the neighbouring wire.\n\n===Common impedance coupling===\nIn electrical circuits sharing a common signal return path, electrical impedance in the return path creates common impedance coupling between the signals, resulting in crosstalk.<ref>[http://learnemc.com/common-impedance-coupling LearnEMC Web Site: Common-Impedance Coupling]</ref><ref>K.-H. Gonschorek and R. Vick: Electromagnetic Compatibility for Device Design and System Integration, Springer, Berlin Heidelberg, 2009, isbn 978-3-642-03289-9, page 90</ref>\n\n==In cabling==\nIn structured cabling, crosstalk refers to [[electromagnetic interference]] from one unshielded [[twisted pair]] to another twisted pair, normally running in parallel. Signals traveling through adjacent pairs of wire create magnetic fields which interact with each other, inducing interference in the neighboring pair. The pair causing the interference is called the \u201cdisturbing pair\u201d, while the pair experiencing the interference is the \u201cdisturbed pair\u201d.\n\n;Near end crosstalk (NEXT):  NEXT is a measure of the ability of a cable to reject crosstalk, so the higher the NEXT value, the greater the rejection of crosstalk at the local connection. It is referred to as Near End because the interference between the two signals in the cable is measured at the same end of the cable as the interfering transmitter. The NEXT value for a given cable type is generally expressed in decibels per feet or decibels per 1000 feet and varies with the frequency of transmission. General specifications for cabling (such as CAT 5) usually include the minimum NEXT values.<ref name=\"lanshack\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lanshack.com/cat5e-tutorial.aspx |title=Category 5 / 5E & Cat 6 Cabling Tutorial and FAQ's |publisher=lanshack.com |accessdate=2013-01-05 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117171629/http://www.lanshack.com/cat5e-tutorial.aspx |archivedate=2013-01-17 }}</ref>\n\n;{{Anchor|PSNEXT}}Power sum near end crosstalk (PSNEXT)\n:PSNEXT is a NEXT measurement which includes the sum of crosstalk contributions from all adjacent pairs as an algebraic sum of the NEXT of the three wire pairs as they affect the fourth pair in a four-pair cable (e.g., Category 6 cable).<ref name=\"lanshack\"/> The Superior Modular Products White paper<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.superiormod.com/smp/pages/support/White%20Paper%20-%20RJ21X.pdf |title=Component Level PowerSum Compliance and RJ21X Connectivity Solutions (Superior Modular Products White paper) |accessdate=2008-09-13 |format=PDF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060716043452/http://www.superiormod.com/smp/pages/support/White%20Paper%20-%20RJ21X.pdf |archivedate=July 16, 2006 }}</ref> states that the testing process for PSNEXT consists of measuring all pair-to-pair crosstalk combinations and then summing all of the values for each pair. The specification was developed to directly address the effect of transmissions on multiple adjacent pairs on the pair being tested and is relevant to all connecting hardware and associated communications cables.\n\n:Cabling bandwidths in excess of 100&nbsp;MHz ([[Category 5 cable]] bandwidth) make consideration of PSNEXT more important as [[Gigabit Ethernet]] through [[Cat-6]] uses all four wire pairs simultaneously and bidirectionally. The additional wire pair usage and growing bandwidth increases the need to keep NEXT in check.\n\n;Far end crosstalk (FEXT): FEXT measures the interference between two pairs of a cable measured at the far end of the cable with respect to the interfering transmitter.<ref name=\"lanshack\"/>\n\n;Equal level far end crosstalk (ELFEXT): ELFEXT measures the FEXT with attenuation compensation.<ref name=\"lanshack\"/>\n\n;{{visible anchor|Alien crosstalk}} (AXT): AXT is interference caused by other cables routed close to the cable of interest as opposed to signals contained in the same cable.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.comnews.com/features/2009_february/0209_web3_eliminating.aspx |title=Eliminating alien crosstalk |publisher=Communications News |date=February 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100209073156/http://www.comnews.com/features/2009_february/0209_web3_eliminating.aspx |archivedate=2010-02-09 }}</ref>\n\n==In audio==\n[[File:IBA Crosstalk weighting curve.svg|400px|right]]\n\nIn [[stereo]] audio reproduction, crosstalk can refer to signal leaking across from one program channel to another, reducing channel separation and [[stereo imaging]]. Crosstalk between channels in mixing consoles, and between studio feeds is a much more noticeable problem, as these are likely to be carrying very different programmes or material.\n\nCrosstalk is an electrical effect and can be quantified with a crosstalk measurement. Crosstalk measurements are made on audio systems to determine the amount of signal leaking across from one channel to another. The [[Independent Broadcasting Authority]] published a [[weighting curve]] for use in crosstalk measurement that gives due emphasis to the subjective audibility of different frequencies. In the absence of any international standards, this is still in use despite the demise of the IBA.{{cn|date=December 2017}}\n\nGood crosstalk performance for a stereo system is not difficult to achieve in today's [[digital audio]] systems, though it was hard to keep below the desired figure of -30&nbsp;dB{{cn|date=December 2017}} or so on [[vinyl record]]ings and [[FM radio]].\n\n==Other examples==\nIn [[telecommunication]] or [[telephony]], crosstalk is often distinguishable as pieces of speech or [[in-band signaling]] tones leaking from other people's connections.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.its.bldrdoc.gov/fs-1037/dir-009/_1340.htm |work=Federal Standard 1037C glossary |title=crosstalk (XT) |access-date=2018-03-26}}</ref> If the connection is analog, [[twisted pair]] cabling can often be used to reduce crosstalk. Alternatively, the signals can be converted to digital form, which is typically less susceptible to crosstalk.\n\nIn [[wireless communication]], crosstalk is often denoted [[co-channel interference]], and is related to [[adjacent-channel interference]].{{Clarify|date=February 2009}}\n\nIn [[integrated circuit design]], crosstalk normally refers to a signal affecting another nearby signal. Usually the coupling is capacitive, and to the nearest neighbor, but other forms of coupling and effects on signal further away are sometimes important, especially in analog designs. See [[signal integrity]] for tools used to measure and prevent this problem, and [[substrate coupling]] for a discussion of crosstalk conveyed through the [[integrated circuit]] substrate. There are a wide variety of repair solutions, with increased spacing, wire re-ordering, and shielding being the most common.\n\nIn full-field optical coherence [[tomography]], \"crosstalk\" refers to the phenomenon that due to highly scattering objects, multiple scattered photons reach the image plane and generate coherent signal after traveling a pathlength that matches that of the sample depth within a coherence length.\n\nIn [[3D display|stereoscopic 3D displays]], \"crosstalk\" refers to the incomplete isolation of the left and right image channels so that one leaks or bleeds into the other - like a double exposure, which produces a [[Ghosting (television)|ghosting]] effect.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Attenuation-to-crosstalk ratio]]\n*[[Audio system measurements]]\n*[[Co-channel interference]] (CCI)\n*[[Print-through]]\n*[[Signal integrity]]\n*[[Signal-to-interference ratio]] (SIR or ''S''/''I''), also known as [[carrier-to-interference ratio]] (CIR or ''C''/''I'')\n*[[Substrate coupling]]\n*[[Unger model]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{FS1037C MS188}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wiktionary|crosstalk}}\n*[http://download.intel.com/education/highered/signal/ELCT762/class19_Crosstalk_overview.ppt Educational slideshow on capacitive and inductive crosstalk]\n*[https://www.webcitation.org/62gSRsABm?url=http://www.ieee.li/pdf/viewgraphs/minimizing_crosstalk_wiring_cabling.pdf Minimizing Crosstalk in Wiring and Cabling]\n\n[[Category:Electrical phenomena]]\n[[Category:Electrical parameters]]\n[[Category:Electromagnetic compatibility]]\n[[Category:Audio amplifier specifications]]\n[[Category:Telecommunication theory]]\n[[Category:Audio engineering]]\n[[Category:Broadcast engineering]]\n[[Category:Sound measurements]]\n", "name_user": "GingerBreadmanCandyCane", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eElectromagnetic field interference:removed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crosstalk"}
{"title_page": "Steven Spielberg", "text_new": "{{redirect|Spielberg}}\n{{pp-semi|small=yes}}\n{{Use American English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|American film director and screenwriter}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Steven Spielberg\n| image              = Steven Spielberg by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption            = Spielberg in 2017\n| birth_name         = Steven Allan Spielberg\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1946|12|18}}\n| birth_place        = [[Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]], U.S.\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| education     = [[Saratoga High School (California)|Saratoga High School]]\n| alma_mater         = [[California State University, Long Beach]]\n| occupation         = Film producer, film director, screenwriter\n| years_active       = 1959\u2013present\n| networth           = US$3.6 billion (2019)<ref name=\"forbes1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/steven-spielberg/|title=Steven Spielberg|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=December 9, 2016}}</ref>\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Amy Irving]]|1985|1989|end=divorced}}<br />{{marriage|[[Kate Capshaw]]|1991}}\n| children           = 7 (including [[Sasha Spielberg|Sasha]] and [[Jessica Capshaw]])\n| mother             = Leah Posner\n| father             = [[Arnold Spielberg]]\n| relations          = [[Anne Spielberg]] (sister)\n| signature          = Steven Spielberg Signature.svg\n}}\n'''Steven Allan Spielberg''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|p|i\u02d0|l|b|\u025cr|\u0261}}; born December 18, 1946) is an American filmmaker. He is considered one of the founding pioneers of the [[New Hollywood]] era and one of the most popular directors and producers in film history.<ref>{{citation|title=The Cinema of Steven Spielberg: Empire of Light|author=Morris, Nigel|publisher=Wallflower Press|date=2007}}</ref> Spielberg started in Hollywood directing television and several minor theatrical releases. He became a household name as the director of ''[[Jaws (film)|Jaws]]'' (1975), which was critically and commercially successful and is considered the first [[Blockbuster (entertainment)|summer blockbuster]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Higgins|first1=Bill|title='Jaws': Revisiting Hollywood's First Summer Blockbuster|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jaws-steven-spielberg-box-office-309339|accessdate=July 10, 2016|date=April 7, 2012|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref> His subsequent releases focused typically on science fiction/adventure films such as ''[[Close Encounters of the Third Kind]]'' (1977), ''[[Raiders of the Lost Ark]]'' (1981), ''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]'' (1982), and ''[[Jurassic Park (film)|Jurassic Park]]'' (1993), which became archetypes of modern Hollywood [[Escapism|escapist]] filmmaking.<ref>{{cite news|date=May 27, 2016|title=Steven Spielberg to Harvard grads: Be the movie heroes of real life|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/steven-spielberg-to-harvard-grads-be-the-movie-heroes-of-real-life/articleshow/52463599.cms|work=The Economic Times}}</ref>\n\nSpielberg transitioned into addressing serious issues in his later work with ''[[The Color Purple (film)|The Color Purple]]'' (1985), ''[[Empire of the Sun (film)|Empire of the Sun]]'' (1987), ''[[Schindler's List]]'' (1993), ''[[Amistad (film)|Amistad]]'' (1997), and ''[[Saving Private Ryan]]'' (1998). He has largely adhered to this practice during the 21st century, with ''[[Munich (film)|Munich]]'' (2005), ''[[Lincoln (film)|Lincoln]]'' (2012), ''[[Bridge of Spies (film)|Bridge of Spies]]'' (2015), and ''[[The Post (film)|The Post]]'' (2017).\n\nHe co-founded [[Amblin Entertainment]] and [[DreamWorks Pictures]], where he has also served as a producer or executive producer for several successful film trilogies, tetralogies and more including the ''[[Gremlins]]'', ''[[Back to the Future (franchise)|Back to the Future]]'', ''[[Men in Black (film series)|Men in Black]]'', and the ''[[Transformers (film series)|Transformers]]'' series. He later transitioned into producing several video games.\n\nSpielberg is one of the American film industry's most critically successful filmmakers, with praise for his directing talent and versatility,<ref>{{cite web|author1=Seitz, Matt Zoller|author2=Arikan, Ali|author3=Bramble, Serena|title=MAGIC AND LIGHT: THE FILMS OF STEVEN SPIELBERG: Chapter 1: Introduction|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2011/12/magic-and-light-the-films-of-steven-spielberg-chapter-1-introduction-132598/|website=[[IndieWire]]|date=December 15, 2011|author1-link=Matt Zoller Seitz}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=Dargis, Manohla|author2-link=A. O. Scott|author2=Scott, A. O.|title=The 25 Best Films of the 21st Century So Far.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/06/09/movies/the-25-best-films-of-the-21st-century.html|newspaper=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|accessdate=October 2, 2018|date=June 9, 2017|author1-link=Manohla Dargis}}</ref> and he has won the [[Academy Award for Best Director]] twice. Some of his movies are also among the highest-grossing films, while his total work makes him the [[List of highest-grossing directors|highest-grossing film director in history]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-milestone-steven-spielberg-is-first-member-10b-directors-club-1103623|title=Box-Office Milestone: Steven Spielberg Is First Member of $10B Directors' Club|last=McClintock|first=Pamela|date=April 17, 2018|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=April 18, 2018}}</ref> His net worth is estimated to be more than $3 billion.<ref name=\"forbes1\" />\n\n==Early life==\nSpielberg was born on December 18, 1946 in [[Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]].<ref name=McBride /><ref>{{cite news|author=Post 50|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/12/18/steven-spielberg-10-birthday-facts_n_2317744.html|title=Steven Spielberg: 10 Little Known Facts About The Director On His Birthday|work=HuffPost|date = December 18, 2012|accessdate=February 26, 2019}}</ref> His mother, Leah (n\u00e9e Posner, later Adler; January 12, 1920 \u2013 February 21, 2017),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fredbernstein.com/info/spielberg_mom.shtml|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130323023020/http://fredbernstein.com/info/spielberg_mom.shtml|title=Fred A. Bernstein|publisher=Fredbernstein.com|archivedate= March 23, 2013|accessdate=May 25, 2012}}</ref> was a restaurateur and concert pianist, and his father, [[Arnold Spielberg]] (born 1917), was an electrical engineer involved in the development of computers.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|title = Steven Spielberg Biography (1947?\u2013)|url = http://www.filmreference.com/film/85/Steven-Spielberg.html|publisher = filmreference.com|accessdate =January 15, 2008}}</ref> His family was [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox Jewish]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Zoe|last=Heller|title=FILM / The Real Thing: Steven Spielberg, fueller of fantasies, wizard|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/film-the-real-thing-steven-spielberg-fueller-of-fantasies-wizard-of-wonder-is-making-a-film-about-2324669.html|work=[[The Independent]]|date=May 22, 1993|accessdate=May 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Tom|last=Shales|title=THE MAN AT THE TOP OF 'SCHINDLER'S LIST'|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1993/12/15/the-man-at-the-top-of-schindlers-list/22c1c36c-b62e-408c-8c4e-a06963bbb049/?tid=ss_tw|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=December 15, 1993|accessdate=May 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=DbqATVZHvkQC&pg=PA35|title=Steven Spielberg: A Biography|publisher=Da Capo Press|year= 1999|isbn=978-0-306-80900-2}}</ref> Spielberg's paternal grandparents were [[History of the Jews in Russia|Jewish Russian]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://birth-records.mooseroots.com/l/1321764/Arnold-Meyer-Spielberg|title=Arnold Meyer Spielberg (b. 1917)|website=birth-records.mooseroots.com|accessdate=January 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Sara Debbie|last=Gutfreund|title=Steven Spielberg's Jewish Roots|url=http://www.aish.com/jw/s/Steven-Spielbergs-Jewish-Roots.html|work=The Jewish Website - aish.com|date=January 28, 2017|accessdate=May 11, 2018}}</ref> immigrants who settled in Cincinnati in the 1900s; his grandmother was from [[Sudylkiv]], while his grandfather was from [[Kamianets-Podilskyi]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://oralhistory.rutgers.edu/interviewees/30-interview-html-text/146-spielberg-arnold| title=Interview:Spielberg, Arnold| publisher=[[Rutgers University]]| date=May 12, 2006| accessdate=October 25, 2015| author=Illingworth, Shaun}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/hollywood/article/a_close_encounter_with_steven_spielbergs_dad_20120613| title=A close encounter with Steven Spielberg's dad| work=[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles]]| date=June 13, 2012| accessdate=October 25, 2015| author=Tugend, Tom}}</ref> In 1950, his family moved to [[Haddon Township, New Jersey]], when his father took a job with RCA. Three years later, the family moved to [[Phoenix, Arizona]].<ref>{{cite web|first=David|last=Denby|title=Steven Spielberg at Seventy|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/01/16/steven-spielberg-at-seventy|work=[[The New Yorker]]|date=January 16, 2017|accessdate=May 11, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Fischer />{{rp|548}} Spielberg attended Hebrew school from 1953 to 1957, in classes taught by Rabbi [[Albert L. Lewis]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=DbqATVZHvkQC&pg=PA42|title=Steven Spielberg: A Biography|publisher=Da Capo Press|year= 1999|isbn=978-0-306-80900-2}}</ref>\n\nAs a child, Spielberg faced difficulty reconciling being an Orthodox Jew with the perception of him by other children he played with. \"It isn't something I enjoy admitting,\" he once said, \"but when I was seven, eight, nine years old, God forgive me, I was embarrassed because we were Orthodox Jews. I was embarrassed by the outward perception of my parents' Jewish practices. I was never really ashamed to be Jewish, but I was uneasy at times.\"<ref>{{cite web|first=Slovie|last=Jungreis-Wolff|title=Steven Spielberg, E.T. and Growing Up Jewish|url=http://www.aish.com/f/p/Steven-Spielberg-ET-and-Growing-Up-Jewish.html|work=The Jewish Website - aish.com|date=August 22, 2015|accessdate=May 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Steven Spielberg: 'We Can't Just Sit Back and Hope'|publisher=Parade Magazine|date=March 27, 1994|url=http://www.parade.com/articles/editions/1994/edition_03-27-1994/steven-spielberg-we-cant-just-sit-back-and-hope.html|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202024010/https://parade.com/articles/editions/1994/edition_03-27-1994/steven-spielberg-we-cant-just-sit-back-and-hope.html|archivedate=February 2, 2016}}</ref> Spielberg also said he suffered from acts of [[anti-Semitic]] prejudice and bullying: \"In high school, I got smacked and kicked around. Two bloody noses. It was horrible.\"<ref name=faces>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/packages/html/movies/bestpictures/schindler-ar1.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|first=Bernard|last=Weinraub|date=December 12, 1993|title=Steven Spielberg Faces the Holocaust}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|first=Noah|last=Isenberg|title=The Making of Steven Spielberg|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/139708/making-steven-spielberg|journal=[[The New Republic]]|date=January 9, 2017|accessdate=May 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=J.D.|last=Reed|title=Steven Spielberg|url=http://people.com/archive/steven-spielberg/|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=March 15, 1999|accessdate=May 11, 2018}}</ref> At age 12, he made his first home movie: a train wreck involving his toy [[Lionel Corporation|Lionel]] trains.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Sanello|first1=Frank|title=Spielberg: The Man, the Movies, the Mythology|date=2002|publisher=Taylor Trade Publications|page=14|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A6hmQbfOeTAC&pg=PA14#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=April 21, 2015|isbn=9780878331482}}</ref> Throughout his early teens, and after entering high school, Spielberg continued to make amateur, 8&nbsp;mm, \"adventure\" films.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Jackson|first1=Kathi|title=Steven Spielberg: A Biography|date=2007|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|page=5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SwkUdUXRA_kC&pg=PA5#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=April 21, 2015|isbn=9780313337963}}</ref>\n\nIn 1958, he became a [[Scouts BSA (Boy Scouts of America)|Boy Scout]] and fulfilled a requirement for the [[Merit badge (Boy Scouts of America)|photography merit badge]] by making a nine-minute, 8&nbsp;mm film entitled ''The Last Gunfight''.<ref>{{cite web| title = Steven Spielberg Sighted in Arizona|url = http://doney.net/aroundaz/celebrity/spielberg_stephen.htm| accessdate =November 19, 2007}}</ref> Years later, Spielberg recalled to a magazine interviewer, \"My dad's still-camera was broken, so I asked the scoutmaster if I could tell a story with my father's movie camera. He said yes, and I got an idea to do a Western. I made it and got my merit badge. That was how it all started.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Nickelodeon Magazine Interviews Steven Spielberg|work=[[Nickelodeon Magazine]]|url=http://www.nick.com/shows/nick_mag/lookInside/index.jhtml?pagenum=8|accessdate=July 29, 2008}}</ref>\nAt age 13, while living in Phoenix, Spielberg won a prize for a 40-minute, war film he titled ''Escape to Nowhere'', using a cast composed of other high school friends. That motivated him to make 15 more amateur, 8&nbsp;mm films.<ref name=Fischer />{{rp|548}}\n\nSome of the films he cited as early influences that he grew up watching include the ''[[Godzilla (franchise)|Godzilla]]'' [[kaiju]] film ''[[Godzilla, King of the Monsters!|King of the Monsters]]'' (1956), which he called \"the most masterful of all the dinosaur movies because it made you believe it was really happening\",<ref>{{cite book |last=Ryfle |first=Steve |title=Japan's Favorite Mon-Star: The Unauthorized Biography of the Big G |year=1998 |publisher=ECW Press |isbn=9781550223484 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/japansfavoritemo0000ryfl/page/15 15\u201317] |url=https://archive.org/details/japansfavoritemo0000ryfl/page/15 }}</ref> as well as titles such as ''[[Captains Courageous]]'' (1937), ''[[Pinocchio (1940 film)|Pinocchio]]'' (1940), and particularly ''[[Lawrence of Arabia (film)|Lawrence of Arabia]]'' (1962), which he cited as \"the film that set me on my journey\".<ref>{{cite web |title=10 great films that inspired Steven Spielberg |url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/news-opinion/news-bfi/lists/10-great-films-inspired-steven-spielberg |website=[[British Film Institute]] |date=January 23, 2018 |accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref> In 1963, at age 16, Spielberg wrote and directed his first independent film, a 140-minute science fiction adventure called ''[[Firelight (1964 film)|Firelight]]'', which would later inspire ''Close Encounters''. The film was made for $500, most of which came from his father, and was shown in a local cinema for one evening, which earned back its cost.<ref>From Inside the Actor's Studio with James Lipton interviewing Steven Spielberg.</ref>\n\nAfter attending [[Arcadia High School (Phoenix, Arizona)|Arcadia High School]] in Phoenix for three years, his family later moved to [[Saratoga, California]] where he attended and graduated from [[Saratoga High School (California)|Saratoga High School]] in 1965. He attained the rank of [[Eagle Scout (Boy Scouts of America)|Eagle Scout]]. His parents divorced while he was still in school,<ref name=\"weisman\">{{cite web|last1=Weisman|first1=Aly|title=Meet Steven Spielberg's Parents In This Revealing '60 Minutes' Profile|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/meet-steven-spielbergs-parents-in-this-revealing-60-minutes-profile-2012-10|accessdate=September 29, 2016|website=Business Insider|date=October 22, 2012}}</ref> and, soon after, he graduated. Spielberg moved to [[Los Angeles]], staying initially with his father. His long-term goal was to become a film director. His three sisters and mother remained in Saratoga. In Los Angeles, he applied to the [[University of Southern California]]'s film school but was turned down because of his \"C\" grade average.<ref name=Fischer>Fischer, Dennis. ''Science Fiction Film Directors, 1895\u20131998'', McFarland & Co. (2000)</ref>{{rp|548}} He then applied and was admitted to [[California State University, Long Beach]] where he became a brother of [[Theta Chi Fraternity]].<ref>[http://www.thetachi.org/about/notable-theta-chis/ \"Notable Theta Chis\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418075922/http://www.thetachi.org/about/notable-theta-chis/|date=April 18, 2015 }}, Theta Chi Fraternity alumni</ref> Spielberg attended [[Brookdale Community College]] for his undergrad.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RVdwDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA329|title=The Most Important People of the 20th Century (Part-II): Artists & Entertainers|last=Thakur|first=Pradeep|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=9780557943777|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWhile still a student, he was offered a small, unpaid, intern job at [[Universal Studios]] with the editing department.<ref name=USCtrustee>{{cite web|url=http://www.usc.edu/about/administration/trustees/|title=Board of Trustees \u2013 About USC|work=usc.edu|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726020808/http://www.usc.edu/about/administration/trustees/|archivedate=July 26, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.calstate.edu/Newsline/Archive/01-02/020514-LB.shtml|title=CSU Newsline \u2013 Steven Spielberg To Graduate from California State University, Long Beach With Bachelor's Degree in Film and Electronic Arts|publisher=Calstate.edu|date=May 14, 2002|accessdate=March 2, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100309122336/https://www.calstate.edu/Newsline/Archive/01-02/020514-LB.shtml|archivedate=March 9, 2010}}</ref> He was later given the opportunity to make a short film for theatrical release, the 26-minute, 35&nbsp;mm ''[[Amblin']]'', which he wrote and directed. Studio vice president [[Sidney Sheinberg]] was impressed by the film, which had won a number of awards, and offered Spielberg a seven-year directing contract. It made him the youngest director ever to be signed for a long-term deal with a major Hollywood studio.<ref name=Fischer />{{rp|548}} He subsequently dropped out of college to begin professionally directing TV productions with Universal.<ref>{{cite news| url =https://articles.latimes.com/2002/may/31/local/me-graduate31|title= Spielberg to Add B.A. to His Resume|author= Stephanie Chavez|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date =May 31, 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url = https://www.nytimes.com/times-insider/2014/06/26/first-glimpses-spielberg-and-snow-white/?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0|title=1969: Spielberg and Snow White|author=Mark Bulik|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date = June 26, 2014}}</ref> Spielberg later returned to [[California State University, Long Beach]] and completed his BA degree in Film and Electronic Arts in 2002.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/3579578/Spielberg-why-I-went-back-to-college.html|title=Spielberg: why I went back to college|first=John|last=Hiscock|date=June 30, 2002|accessdate=December 1, 2017|website=Telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===1970s===\nHis first professional TV job came when he was hired to direct one of the segments for the 1969 pilot episode of ''[[Night Gallery (film)|Night Gallery]]'', written by [[Rod Serling]] and starring [[Joan Crawford]].<ref>{{Cite news| url =https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0064725/|title= Night Gallery|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate = July 21, 2014}}</ref> Crawford, however, was \"speechless, and then horrified\" at the thought of a twenty-one-year-old newcomer directing her, one of Hollywood's leading stars. \"Why was this happening to me?\" she asked the producer.<ref name=Chandler>Chandler, Charlotte. ''Not the Girl Next Door: Joan Crawford, a Personal Biography'', Hal Leonard Corp. (2008) p. 261</ref> Her attitude changed after they began working on her scenes:\n\n{{quote|When I began to work with Steven, I understood everything. It was immediately obvious to me, and probably everyone else, that here was a young genius. I thought maybe more experience was important, but then I thought of all of those experienced directors who didn't have Steven's intuitive inspiration and who just kept repeating the same old routine performances. ''That'' was called \"experience.\" I knew then that Steven Spielberg had a brilliant future ahead of him. Hollywood doesn't always recognize talent, but Steven's was not going to be overlooked. I told him so in a note I wrote him. I wrote to Rod Serling, too. I was so grateful that he had approved Steven as the director. I told him he had been totally right.<ref name=Chandler />}}\n\nShe and Spielberg were reportedly close friends until her death. The episode is unusual in his body of work, in that the camerawork is more highly stylized than his later, more \"mature\" films. After this, and an episode of ''[[Marcus Welby, M.D.]]'', Spielberg got his first feature-length assignment: an episode of ''[[The Name of the Game (TV series)|The Name of the Game]]'' called \"[[L.A. 2017]]\". This futuristic science fiction episode impressed Universal Studios and they signed him to a short contract. He did another segment on ''Night Gallery'' and did some work for shows such as ''[[Owen Marshall: Counselor at Law]]'' and ''The Psychiatrist'', before landing the first series episode of ''[[Columbo (TV series)|Columbo]]'' (previous episodes were actually TV films).\n\nBased on the strength of his work, Universal signed Spielberg to do four TV films. The first was a [[Richard Matheson]] adaptation called ''[[Duel (1971 film)|Duel]]''. The film is about a psychotic [[Peterbilt 281]] [[tanker truck]] driver who chases the terrified driver ([[Dennis Weaver]]) of a small [[Plymouth Valiant]] and tries to run him off the road. Special praise of this film by the influential British critic [[Dilys Powell]] was highly significant to Spielberg's career. Another TV film (''[[Something Evil]]'') was made and released to capitalize on the popularity of ''[[The Exorcist (film)|The Exorcist]]'', then a major best-selling book which had not yet been released as a film. He fulfilled his contract by directing the TV film-length pilot of a show called ''Savage'', starring [[Martin Landau]]. Spielberg's debut full-length feature film was ''[[The Sugarland Express]]'', about a married couple who are chased by police as the couple tries to regain custody of their baby. Spielberg's cinematography for the police chase was praised by reviewers, and ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' stated that \"a major new director is on the horizon.\"<ref name=McBride />{{rp|223}} However, the film fared poorly at the box office and received a limited release.\n\nStudio producers [[Richard D. Zanuck]] and [[David Brown (producer)|David Brown]] offered Spielberg the director's chair for ''[[Jaws (film)|Jaws]]'', a thriller-horror film based on the [[Peter Benchley]] novel [[Jaws (novel)|about an enormous killer shark]]. Spielberg has often referred to the gruelling shoot as his professional crucible. Despite the film's ultimate, enormous success, it was nearly shut down due to delays and budget over-runs. But Spielberg persevered and finished the film. It was an enormous hit, winning three Academy Awards (for editing, original score and sound) and grossing more than $470&nbsp;million worldwide at the box office. It also set the domestic record for box office gross, leading to what the press described as \"Jawsmania.\"<ref name=McBride />{{rp|248}} ''Jaws'' made Spielberg a household name and one of America's youngest multi-millionaires, allowing him a great deal of autonomy for his future projects.<ref name=McBride />{{rp|250}} It was nominated for Best Picture and featured Spielberg's first of three collaborations with actor [[Richard Dreyfuss]].\n\nRejecting offers to direct ''[[Jaws 2]]'',<ref>{{cite book|last=Baxter|first=John|year=1997|title=Steven Spielberg: The Unauthorised Biography|location=London|publisher=Harper Collins|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780006384441/page/145 145]|isbn=978-0-00-638444-1|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780006384441/page/145}}</ref> ''[[King Kong (1976 film)|King Kong]]'' and ''[[Superman (1978 film)|Superman]]'', Spielberg and actor Richard Dreyfuss re-convened to work on a film about [[Unidentified flying object|UFOs]], which became ''[[Close Encounters of the Third Kind]]'' (1977). One of the rare films both written and directed by Spielberg, ''Close Encounters'' was a critical and box office hit, giving Spielberg his first Best Director nomination from the Academy as well as earning six other [[Academy Awards]] nominations. It won Oscars in two categories (Cinematography, [[Vilmos Zsigmond]], and a Special Achievement Award for Sound Effects Editing, Frank E. Warner). This second blockbuster helped to secure Spielberg's rise. His next film, ''[[1941 (film)|1941]]'', a big-budgeted World War&nbsp;II farce, was not nearly as successful and though it grossed over $92.4&nbsp;million worldwide (and did make a small profit for co-producing studios Columbia and Universal) it was seen as a disappointment, mainly with the critics.<ref>[https://www.the-numbers.com/movies/1979/01941.php \"1941, Box Office Information.\"] ''The Numbers'', September 27, 2012.</ref>\n\nSpielberg then revisited his ''Close Encounters'' project and, with financial backing from Columbia Pictures, released ''Close Encounters: The Special Edition'' in 1980. For this, Spielberg fixed some of the flaws he thought impeded the original 1977 version of the film and also, at the behest of Columbia, and as a condition of Spielberg revising the film, shot additional footage showing the audience the interior of the mothership seen at the end of the film (a decision Spielberg would later regret as he felt the interior of the mothership should have remained a mystery). Nevertheless, the re-release was a moderate success, while the 2001 DVD release of the film restored the original ending.\n\n===1980s===\nNext, Spielberg teamed with ''[[Star Wars]]'' creator and friend [[George Lucas]] on an action adventure film, ''[[Raiders of the Lost Ark]]'', the first of the [[Indiana Jones]] films. The archaeologist and adventurer hero Indiana Jones was played by [[Harrison Ford]] (whom Lucas had previously cast in his ''[[Star Wars]]'' films as [[Han Solo]]). The film was considered an homage to the cliffhanger serials of the [[Golden Age of Hollywood]]. It became the biggest film at the box office in 1981, and the recipient of numerous Oscar nominations including Best Director (Spielberg's second nomination) and Best Picture (the second Spielberg film to be nominated for Best Picture). ''Raiders'' is still considered a landmark example of the action-adventure genre. The film also led to Ford's casting in [[Ridley Scott]]'s ''[[Blade Runner]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Blade Runner|url=http://www.gradesaver.com/blade-runner/wikipedia/casting-and-characters/|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110820185400/https://www.gradesaver.com/blade-runner/wikipedia/casting-and-characters/|archivedate=August 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\nA year later, Spielberg returned to the science fiction genre with ''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]''. It was the story of a young boy and the alien he befriends, who was accidentally left behind by his companions and is attempting to return home. ''E.T.'' went on to become the top-grossing film of all time. It was also nominated for nine Academy Awards including Best Picture and Best Director, winning 4 of them.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/oct/21/et-spielberg-fantasy|title=ET: The Extra-Terrestrial: No 7 best sci-fi and fantasy film of all time|last=Wise|first=Damon|date=October 21, 2010|work=The Guardian|access-date=October 18, 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\nBetween 1982 and 1985, Spielberg produced three high-grossing films: ''[[Poltergeist (1982 film)|Poltergeist]]'' (for which he also co-wrote the screenplay), a big-screen adaptation of ''[[Twilight Zone: The Movie|The Twilight Zone]]'' (for which he directed the segment \"Kick The Can\"),<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.mtv.com/movies/news/articles/1556111/story.jhtml|title= Rewind: Major-Studio flicks that belong in the Grind House|first = Karl|last = Heitmueller|date = April 3, 2007|accessdate =January 2, 2009|publisher = MTV|quote = Ultimate A-lister Steven Spielberg co-produced this big-budget adaptation of Rod Serling's classic '60s TV show....}}</ref> and ''[[The Goonies]]'' (Spielberg, executive producer, also wrote the story on which the screenplay was based).<ref>{{cite journal|title = This way to the children's crusade|first = Richard|last = Corliss|date = January 7, 1985|accessdate =January 2, 2009|quote = he wrote the story and served as an executive producer of The Goonies....|url= http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,959559,00.html|journal = [[Time (magazine)|Time]]}}</ref> Spielberg appeared in a cameo on [[Cyndi Lauper]]'s music video for the movie's theme song, \"[[The Goonies 'R' Good Enough]]\".<ref>{{youtube|LxLhytQ67fs|Cyndi Lauper \u2013 The Goonies 'R' Good Enough}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Steven Spielberg with Chandran Rutnam in Sri Lanka.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|right|Steven Spielberg and [[Chandran Rutnam]] on a location in Sri Lanka during the filming of ''[[Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom]]''.]]\nHis next directorial feature was the ''Raiders'' prequel ''[[Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom]]''. Teaming up once again with Lucas and Ford, the film was plagued with uncertainty for the material and script. This film and the Spielberg-produced ''[[Gremlins]]'' led to the creation of the [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system|PG-13 rating]] due to the high level of violence in films targeted at younger audiences. In spite of this, ''Temple of Doom'' is rated PG by the MPAA, even though it is the darkest and, possibly, most violent Indy film. Nonetheless, the film was still a huge blockbuster hit in 1984. It was on this project that Spielberg also met his future wife, actress [[Kate Capshaw]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biography.com/articles/Steven-Spielberg-9490621|title=Steven Spielberg Biography|publisher=Biography.com|date=December 18, 1947|accessdate=January 31, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514201106/https://www.biography.com/articles/Steven-Spielberg-9490621|archivedate=May 14, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, Spielberg released ''[[The Color Purple (film)|The Color Purple]],'' an adaptation of [[Alice Walker]]'s [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning [[The Color Purple|novel of the same name]], about a generation of empowered African-American women during depression-era America. Starring [[Whoopi Goldberg]] and future talk-show superstar [[Oprah Winfrey]], the film was a box office smash and critics hailed Spielberg's successful foray into the dramatic genre. [[Roger Ebert]] proclaimed it the best film of the year and later entered it into his Great Films archive. The film received eleven [[Academy Award]] nominations, including two for Goldberg and Winfrey. However, Spielberg did not get a Best Director nomination.\n\nIn 1987, as China began opening to Western capital investment, Spielberg shot the first American film in Shanghai since the 1930s, an adaptation of [[J. G. Ballard]]'s autobiographical novel ''[[Empire of the Sun (film)|Empire of the Sun]]'', starring [[John Malkovich]] and a young [[Christian Bale]]. The film garnered much praise from critics and was nominated for several Oscars, but did not yield substantial box office revenues. Reviewer [[Andrew Sarris]] called it the best film of the year and later included it among the best films of the decade.<ref>{{cite web| title = Andrew Sarris' Top 10 lists 1958\u20132005| url = http://alumnus.caltech.edu/~ejohnson/critics/sarris.html#y1977| accessdate = October 21, 2006| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20010210193008/http://alumnus.caltech.edu/~ejohnson/critics/sarris.html#y1977| archive-date = February 10, 2001| url-status=dead| df = mdy-all}}</ref> Spielberg was also a co-producer of the 1987 film ''[[Batteries Not Included|*batteries not included]]''.\n\nAfter two forays into more serious dramatic films, Spielberg then directed the third Indiana Jones film, 1989's ''[[Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade]]''. Once again teaming up with Lucas and Ford, Spielberg also cast actor [[Sean Connery]] in a supporting role as Indy's father. The film earned generally positive reviews and was another box office success, becoming the highest-grossing film worldwide that year; its total box office receipts even topped those of Tim Burton's much-anticipated film ''[[Batman (1989 film)|Batman]]'', which had been the bigger hit domestically. Also in 1989, he re-united with actor [[Richard Dreyfuss]] for the romantic comedy-drama ''[[Always (1989 film)|Always]]'', about a daredevil pilot who extinguishes forest fires. Spielberg's first romantic film, ''Always'' was only a moderate success and had mixed reviews.\n\n===1990s===\n[[File:Steven Spielberg in 1990.jpg|thumb|left|Spielberg in March 1990]]\nIn 1991, Spielberg directed ''[[Hook (film)|Hook]]'', about a middle-aged [[Peter Pan]], played by [[Robin Williams]], who returns to [[Neverland]]. Despite innumerable rewrites and creative changes coupled with mixed reviews, the film proved popular with audiences, making over $300&nbsp;million worldwide (from a $70&nbsp;million budget).\n\nIn 1993, Spielberg returned to the adventure genre with the film version of [[Michael Crichton]]'s novel ''[[Jurassic Park (film)|Jurassic Park]]'', about a theme park with genetically engineered dinosaurs. With revolutionary special effects provided by friend [[George Lucas]]'s [[Industrial Light & Magic]] company, the film would eventually become the highest-grossing film of all time (at the worldwide box office) with $914.7&nbsp;million. This would be the third time that one of Spielberg's films became the highest-grossing film ever.\n\nSpielberg's next film, ''[[Schindler's List]]'', was based on the true story of [[Oskar Schindler]], a man who risked his life to save 1,100 Jews from the Holocaust.<ref>The screenplay, adapted from [[Thomas Keneally]]'s novel, was originally in the hands of fellow director [[Martin Scorsese]], but Spielberg negotiated with Scorsese to trade scripts. (At the time, Spielberg held the script for a remake of ''[[Cape Fear (1962 film)|Cape Fear]]''.)</ref> ''Schindler's List'' earned Spielberg his first [[Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]] (it also won [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]]). With the film a huge success at the box office, Spielberg used the profits to set up the [[Shoah Foundation]], a non-profit organization that archives filmed testimony of Holocaust survivors. In 1997, the [[American Film Institute]] listed it among the 10 Greatest American Films ever Made (#9) which moved up to (#8) when the list was remade in 2007.\n\nIn 1994, Spielberg took a hiatus from directing to spend more time with his family and build his new studio, [[DreamWorks Pictures|DreamWorks]],<ref>{{cite magazine|author = Army Archered|title = Spielberg to take break after completing 'List'|magazine = Variety|date = June 17, 1993|url = https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117862199.html?categoryid=2&cs=1&query=dark+AND+angel|accessdate = February 11, 2007|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071011203554/http://variety.com/article/VR1117862199.html?categoryid=2&cs=1&query=dark+AND+angel|archive-date = October 11, 2007|url-status = dead}}</ref> with partners [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]] and [[David Geffen]]. In 1996, he directed the sequel to 1993's ''Jurassic Park'' with ''[[The Lost World: Jurassic Park]]'', which generated over $618&nbsp;million worldwide despite mixed reviews, and was the second biggest film of 1997 behind [[James Cameron]]'s ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]'' (which topped the original ''Jurassic Park'' to become the new recordholder for box office receipts).\n[[File:Steven Spielberg - GianAngelo Pistoia 1.jpg|thumb|right|Spielberg receiving the [[Golden Lion]] by Italian filmmaker [[Gillo Pontecorvo]] at the [[50th Venice International Film Festival]], 1993]]\n\nHis next film, ''[[Amistad (film)|Amistad]]'', was based on a true story (like ''Schindler's List''), specifically about an African slave rebellion. Despite decent reviews from critics, it did not do well at the box office. Spielberg released ''Amistad'' under DreamWorks Pictures,<ref>(formed with former [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] animation exec [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]] and media mogul [[David Geffen]], providing the other letters in the company name)</ref> which has produced all of his films from ''Amistad'' onwards with the exception of ''[[Indiana Jones and the Kingdom of the Crystal Skull]]'', ''[[The Adventures of Tintin (film)|The Adventures of Tintin]]'' and ''[[Ready Player One (film)|Ready Player One]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Masters|first1=Kim|title=Steven Spielberg on DreamWorks' Past, Amblin's Present and His Own Future|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/steven-spielberg-dreamworks-past-amblins-902544|accessdate=July 11, 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=June 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHis 1998 theatrical release was the World War II film ''[[Saving Private Ryan]]'', about a group of U.S. soldiers led by Capt. Miller ([[Tom Hanks]]) sent to bring home a [[paratrooper]] whose three older brothers were killed in the same twenty-four hours, June 5\u20136, of the Normandy landing. The film was a huge box office success, grossing over $481&nbsp;million worldwide and was the biggest film of the year at the North American box office (worldwide it made second place after Michael Bay's ''[[Armageddon (1998 film)|Armageddon]]''). Spielberg won his second Academy Award for his direction. The film's graphic, realistic depiction of combat violence influenced later war films such as ''[[Black Hawk Down (film)|Black Hawk Down]]'' and ''[[Enemy at the Gates]]''. The film was also the first major hit for DreamWorks, which co-produced the film with [[Paramount Pictures]] (as such, it was Spielberg's first release from the latter that was not part of the ''Indiana Jones'' series). Later, Spielberg and [[Tom Hanks]] produced a [[Band of Brothers (TV miniseries)|TV mini-series]] based on [[Stephen Ambrose]]'s book ''[[Band of Brothers (book)|Band of Brothers]]''. The ten-part [[HBO]] mini-series follows Easy Company of the [[101st Airborne Division]]'s 506th Parachute Infantry Regiment. The series won a number of awards at the [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globes]] and the [[Emmy Award|Emmys]].\n\n===2000s===\nIn 2001, Spielberg filmed fellow director and friend [[Stanley Kubrick]]'s final project, ''[[A.I. Artificial Intelligence]]'' which Kubrick was unable to begin during his lifetime. A futuristic film about a humanoid [[android (robot)|android]] longing for love, ''A.I.'' featured groundbreaking visual effects and a multi-layered, allegorical storyline, adapted by Spielberg himself. Though the film's reception in the US was relatively muted, it performed better overseas for a worldwide total box office gross of $236&nbsp;million.\n\nSpielberg and actor [[Tom Cruise]] collaborated for the first time for the futuristic [[neo-noir]] ''[[Minority Report (film)|Minority Report]]'', based upon [[The Minority Report|the science fiction short story]] written by [[Philip K. Dick]] about a Washington D.C. police captain in the year 2054 who has been foreseen to murder a man he has not yet met. The film received strong reviews with the review tallying website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] giving it a 92% approval rating, reporting that 206 out of the 225 reviews they tallied were positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/minority_report/|title=Minority Report|last=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|website=|accessdate=April 10, 2018}}</ref> The film earned over $358&nbsp;million worldwide. [[Roger Ebert]], who named it the best film of 2002, praised its breathtaking vision of the future as well as for the way Spielberg blended [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] with live-action.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20020621/REVIEWS/206210304/1023|title=Minority Report|last=Ebert|first=Roger|date=June 21, 2002|work=Chicago Sun-Times|accessdate=April 10, 2018|authorlink=Roger Ebert}}</ref>\n\nSpielberg's 2002 film ''[[Catch Me If You Can]]'' is about the daring adventures of a youthful con artist (played by [[Leonardo DiCaprio]]). It earned [[Christopher Walken]] an Academy Award nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]. The film is known for [[John Williams]]'s score and its unique [[title sequence]]. It was a hit both commercially<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=catchmeifyoucan.htm| title=Box office collection of Catch Me If You Can| accessdate=November 19, 2012}}</ref> and critically.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/catch_me_if_you_can/|title=Reviews of Catch Me If You Can|website=|accessdate=April 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSpielberg collaborated again with Tom Hanks along with [[Catherine Zeta-Jones]] and [[Stanley Tucci]] in 2004's ''[[The Terminal]]'', a warm-hearted comedy about a man of Eastern European descent who is stranded in an airport. It received mixed reviews but performed relatively well at the box office. In 2005, ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' magazine ranked Spielberg number one on a list of the greatest film directors of all time.\n\nAlso in 2005, Spielberg directed a modern adaptation of ''[[War of the Worlds (2005 film)|War of the Worlds]]'' (a co-production of Paramount and DreamWorks), based on the H. G. Wells book of the same name (Spielberg had been a huge fan of the book and the original 1953 film). It starred Tom Cruise and [[Dakota Fanning]], and, as with past Spielberg films, [[Industrial Light & Magic]] (ILM) provided the [[visual effects]]. Unlike ''E.T.'' and ''Close Encounters of the Third Kind'', which depicted friendly alien visitors, ''War of the Worlds'' featured violent invaders. The film was another huge box office smash, grossing over $591&nbsp;million worldwide.\n\nSpielberg's film ''[[Munich (film)|Munich]]'', about the events following the 1972 [[Munich Massacre]] of Israeli athletes at the Olympic Games, was his second film essaying Jewish relations in the world (the first being ''Schindler's List''). The film is based on ''[[Vengeance (Jonas book)|Vengeance]]'', a book by Canadian journalist [[George Jonas]]. It was previously adapted into the 1986 made-for-TV film ''[[Sword of Gideon]]''. The film received strong critical praise, but underperformed at the U.S. and world box-office; it remains one of Spielberg's most controversial films to date.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Yossi Melman and Steven Hartov|date=January 17, 2006|title=Munich: Fact and Fantasy|url=https://www.theguardian.com/comment/story/0,3604,1687815,00.html|publisher=The Guardian Unlimited|volume=|accessdate=April 10, 2018|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> ''Munich'' received five Academy Awards nominations, including Best Picture, Film Editing, Original Music Score (by John Williams), Best Adapted Screenplay, and Best Director for Spielberg. It was Spielberg's sixth Best Director nomination and fifth Best Picture nomination.\n\nIn June 2006, Steven Spielberg announced he would direct a [[Hard science fiction|scientifically accurate]] film about \"a group of explorers who travel through a worm hole and into another dimension\",<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117945326.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130205132901/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117945326.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 5, 2013|title=Space chase pic on Par launch pad|author=Michael Fleming|date=June 14, 2006|work=Variety|accessdate=April 10, 2018}}</ref> from a treatment by [[Kip Thorne]] and producer [[Lynda Obst]].<ref name=\"script\">{{cite news|author=Jay A. Fernandez|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/movies/la-et-scriptland28mar28,1,3123129.story?track=rss&ctrack=1&cset=true|title=Jonah Nolan turns science into a film script|work=Los Angeles Times|date=March 28, 2007|accessdate=March 28, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202012203/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/movies/la-et-scriptland28mar28%2C1%2C3123129.story?track=rss&ctrack=1&cset=true|archivedate=December 2, 2008}}</ref> In January 2007, screenwriter [[Jonathan Nolan]] met with them to discuss adapting Obst and Thorne's treatment into a narrative screenplay. The screenwriter suggested the addition of a \"time element\" to the treatment's basic idea, which was welcomed by Obst and Thorne.<ref name=\"script\" /> In March of that year, Paramount hired Nolan, as well as scientists from [[Caltech]], forming a workshop to adapt the treatment under the title ''[[Interstellar (film)|Interstellar]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117961655.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130205112431/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117961655.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 5, 2013|title=Nolan to write Spielberg film|author=Michael Fleming|date=March 22, 2007|work=Variety|accessdate=April 10, 2018}}</ref> The following July, Kip Thorne said there was a push by people for him to portray himself in the film.<ref>{{cite news| author=Leigh Dayton| url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,20867,22071820-30417,00.html| title=Warped in La La Land| work=The Australian| date=July 14, 2007| accessdate=July 20, 2007| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071110002631/http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,20867,22071820-30417,00.html| archive-date=November 10, 2007| url-status=dead| df=mdy-all}}</ref> Spielberg later abandoned ''Interstellar'', which was eventually directed by [[Christopher Nolan]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Child|first=Ben|title=Christopher Nolan's next film mission to go Interstellar|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/jan/10/christopher-nolan-next-film-interstellar|newspaper=The Guardian|date=January 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\nSpielberg directed ''[[Indiana Jones and the Kingdom of the Crystal Skull]]'', which wrapped filming in October 2007 and was released on May 22, 2008.<ref>{{Cite news|title = New Indy Adventure Begins Shooting|publisher = IndianaJones.com|date = June 18, 2007|url = http://www.indianajones.com/community/news/news20070618.html|accessdate =June 18, 2007|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070621003713/http://indianajones.com/community/news/news20070618.html|archivedate = June 21, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title = Spielberg, Ford and Lucas on Indy IV| work = Empire| date = August 21, 2006| url = https://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?NID=19382| accessdate =October 21, 2006}}</ref> This was his first film not to be released by DreamWorks since 1997. The film received generally positive reviews from critics,<ref>{{cite web|title=Indiana Jones and the Kingdom of the Crystal Skull (2008)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/indiana_jones_and_the_kingdom_of_the_crystal_skull/|accessdate=April 12, 2012}}</ref> and was financially successful, grossing $786&nbsp;million worldwide.\n\n===2010s===\n[[File:Steven Spielberg Masterclass Cin\u00e9math\u00e8que Fran\u00e7aise 2 cropped.jpg|thumb|left|Spielberg at his masterclass at the [[Cin\u00e9math\u00e8que Fran\u00e7aise]] in January 2012.]]\nIn early 2009, Spielberg shot the first film in a planned trilogy of [[motion capture]] films based on ''[[The Adventures of Tintin]]'', written by Belgian artist [[Herg\u00e9]],<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/23/books/23book.html \"The Man Behind Boy, Dog and Their Adventures\"] Book review by [[Charles McGrath (critic)|Charles McGrath]], ''The New York Times'', December 22, 2009 (December 23, 2009, p. C1 NY ed.). Book reviewed: ''Herg\u00e9: The Man Who Created Tintin'', by Pierre Assouline; translated by Charles Ruas, 276 pages. Oxford University Press. Retrieved December 24, 2009.</ref> with [[Peter Jackson]]. ''[[The Adventures of Tintin: The Secret of the Unicorn]]'', was not released until October 2011, due to the complexity of the computer animation involved. The world premiere took place on October 22, 2011 in [[Brussels]], Belgium.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tintin Has World Premiere in His Hometown|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=141619935|accessdate=October 22, 2011|newspaper=NPR|date=October 22, 2011|agency=Associated Press}}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The film was released in North American theaters on December 21, 2011, in [[Digital 3D]] and [[IMAX 3D|IMAX]].<ref name=\"reldates\">{{cite web|url=http://www.us.movie.tintin.com|title=The Adventures of Tintin Official Movie Site|publisher=Paramount Pictures|accessdate=October 13, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111013183713/http://www.us.movie.tintin.com/|archivedate=October 13, 2011 }}</ref> It received generally positive reviews from critics,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Adventures of Tintin (Rotten Tomatoes)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_adventures_of_tintin/|accessdate=April 12, 2012}}</ref> and grossed over $373&nbsp;million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Adventures of Tintin (Box office)|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=main&id=tintin.htm|accessdate=April 12, 2012}}</ref> ''The Adventures of Tintin'' won the award for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Animated Feature Film|Best Animated Feature Film]] at the [[69th Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Awards]] that year.<ref>{{cite web|title=2012 GOLDEN GLOBES Nominees and Winners \u2013 Complete List!|url=http://broadwayworld.com/article/2012-GOLDEN-GLOBES-Are-Tonight-BroadwayWorld-to-Update-Winners-LIVE-20120115|accessdate=April 15, 2012}}</ref> It is the first non-[[Pixar]] film to win the award since the category was first introduced.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tintin Takes Golden Globe|url=http://www.pixarportal.com/blog.php?id=tintin-takes-golden-globe|accessdate=April 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Adventures of Tintin (Trivia)|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0983193/trivia|accessdate=April 12, 2012}}</ref> Jackson has been announced to direct the second film.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wigler|first=Josh|title=Jackson To Direct 'Tintin' Sequel|url=http://splashpage.mtv.com/2011/10/26/peter-jackson-tintin-hobbit/|publisher=MTV|accessdate=October 26, 2011|date=October 26, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111028074216/http://splashpage.mtv.com/2011/10/26/peter-jackson-tintin-hobbit/|archivedate=October 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nSpielberg followed with ''[[War Horse (film)|War Horse]]'', shot in England in the summer of 2010.<ref>[http://www.thisisplymouth.co.uk/news/SPIELBERG-FILMS-DARTMOOR/article-2482773-detail/article.html \"Steven Spielberg starts filming War Horse on Dartmoor\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110425134559/http://www.thisisplymouth.co.uk/news/SPIELBERG-FILMS-DARTMOOR/article-2482773-detail/article.html|date=April 25, 2011 }} by Tristan Nichols, ''The Herald'' August 3, 2010</ref> It was released just four days after ''The Adventures of Tintin'', on December 25, 2011. The film, based on the [[War Horse (book)|novel]] of the same name written by [[Michael Morpurgo]] and published in 1982, follows the long friendship between a British boy and his horse Joey before and during World War I \u2013 the novel was also adapted into a hit [[War Horse (play)|play]] in London which is still running there, as well as on Broadway. Distributed by [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Walt Disney Studios]], with whom DreamWorks made a distribution deal in 2009, ''War Horse'' was the first of four consecutive Spielberg films released by Disney. ''War Horse'' received generally positive reviews from critics,<ref>{{cite web|title=War Horse (Rotten Tomatoes)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/war_horse/|accessdate=April 12, 2012}}</ref> and was nominated for six [[Academy Awards]], including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Nominees and Winners for the 84th Academy Awards|url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/84/nominees.html|work=oscars.org|accessdate=April 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSpielberg next directed the [[historical drama film]] ''[[Lincoln (film)|Lincoln]]'', starring [[Daniel Day-Lewis]] as United States President [[Abraham Lincoln]] and [[Sally Field]] as [[Mary Todd Lincoln]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2011/04/13/spielbergs-lincoln-gets-its-mary-todd-sally-field/|title=Steven Spielberg's 'Lincoln' gets its Mary Todd: Sally Field|last=Breznican|first=Anthony|date=April 13, 2011|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=October 22, 2019}}</ref> Based on [[Doris Kearns Goodwin]]'s bestseller ''[[Team of Rivals: The Political Genius of Abraham Lincoln]]'', the film covered the final four months of Lincoln's life. Written by [[Tony Kushner]], the film was shot in Richmond, Virginia, in late 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbc12.com/story/14601466/first-casting-calls-for-steven-spielberg-movie|title=First casting calls for Steven Spielberg movie|first=Ben|last=Garbarek|publisher=WWBT (Richmond)|date=May 9, 2011|accessdate=July 20, 2011}}</ref> and was released in the United States in November 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thisweekinthecivilwar.com/2011/10/05/spielberg-to-film-lincoln-scenes-in-richmond/|title=This Week in the Civil War|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140411133150/https://thisweekinthecivilwar.com/2011/10/05/spielberg-to-film-lincoln-scenes-in-richmond/|archivedate=April 11, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/daniel-day-lewis-lincoln-steven-spielberg/|title=Daniel Day-Lewis to Star in Steven Spielberg's 'Lincoln'|work=[[/Film]]|author=Fischer, Russ|date=November 19, 2010}}</ref> Upon release, ''Lincoln'' received widespread critical acclaim,<ref name=\"rt\">{{cite web|url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/lincoln_2011/|title=Lincoln|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]| accessdate=November 15, 2012 }}</ref> and was nominated for twelve [[Academy Awards]] (the most of any film that year) including Best Picture and Best Director for Spielberg.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nominees for the 85th Academy Awards|url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/85/nominees.html|work=oscars.org|accessdate=March 3, 2013}}</ref> It won the award for [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Best Production Design]] and Day-Lewis won the [[Academy Award for Best Actor]] for his portrayal of Lincoln, becoming the first three-time winner in that category as well as the first to win for a performance directed by Spielberg.\n\nIt was announced on May 2, 2013, that Spielberg would direct the film about the story of U.S. [[sniper]] [[Chris Kyle]], titled ''[[American Sniper]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Steven Spielberg, Bradley Cooper to team for 'American Sniper'|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-steven-spielberg-bradley-cooper-to-team-on-american-sniper-20130502,0,6075950.story|newspaper=LA Times|accessdate=May 3, 2013}}</ref> However, on August 5, 2013, it was announced that Spielberg had decided not to direct the film, which was instead directed by [[Clint Eastwood]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Kroll|first=Justin|title=Steven Spielberg, DreamWorks Part Ways With 'American Sniper'|url=https://variety.com/2013/film/news/steven-spielberg-american-sniper-1200566895/|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=August 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ready Player One Japan Premiere Red Carpet Steven Spielberg (40713131765) (cropped).jpg|thumb|Spielberg promoting ''[[Ready Player One (film)|Ready Player One]]'' (2018) in Japan.]]\nSpielberg directed 2015's ''[[Bridge of Spies (film)|Bridge of Spies]]'', a Cold War thriller based on the [[1960 U-2 incident]], and focusing on [[James B. Donovan]]'s negotiations with the Soviets for the release of pilot [[Gary Powers]] after his aircraft was shot down over Soviet territory. The film starred [[Tom Hanks]] as Donovan, as well as [[Mark Rylance]], [[Amy Ryan]], and [[Alan Alda]], with a script by the [[Coen brothers]].<ref name=June14dates>{{cite news|last1=Bahr|first1=Lindsey|title=Steven Spielberg's Cold War thriller and 'The BFG' snag release dates|url=https://ew.com/article/2014/06/16/steven-spielberg-cold-war-bfg/|accessdate=October 22, 2019|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|date=June 16, 2014}}</ref> The film was shot from September to December 2014 on location in New York City, Berlin and [[Wroclaw]], Poland (which doubled for East Berlin), and was released on October 16, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title=Tom Hanks-Steven Spielberg Cold War Thriller Set for Oct. 16, 2015|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/tom-hanks-steven-spielberg-cold-war-thriller-set-for-oct-16-2015-1201221269/|accessdate=June 6, 2014|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=June 16, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Amy Ryan, Alan Alda Join Tom Hanks in Steven Spielberg's Cold War Thriller|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/amy-ryan-alan-alda-join-tom-hanks-in-steven-spielbergs-cold-war-thriller-1201266172/|accessdate=July 21, 2014|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=July 21, 2014}}</ref> ''Bridge of Spies'' received positive reviews from critics, and was nominated for six Academy Awards, including Best Picture; Rylance won the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]], becoming the second actor to win for a performance directed by Spielberg.\n\nSpielberg's ''[[The BFG (2016 film)|The BFG]]'' is an adaptation of [[Roald Dahl]]'s celebrated [[The BFG|children's story]], starring newcomer [[Ruby Barnhill]], and Rylance as the titular Big Friendly Giant. DreamWorks bought the rights in 2010, originally intending [[John Madden (director)|John Madden]] to direct.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/apr/28/steven-spielberg-bfg-movie-roald-dahl|title=Steven Spielberg to tackle The BFG movie|author=Andrew Pulver|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=April 28, 2014}}</ref> The film was the last to be written by ''E.T.'' screenwriter [[Melissa Mathison]] before she died. It was co-produced and released by [[Walt Disney Pictures]], marking the first Disney-branded film to be directed by Spielberg. ''The BFG'' premiered out of competition at the [[Cannes Film Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/04/cannes-film-festival-2016-official-selection-lineup-full-list-1201736807/|title=Cannes Film Festival 2016 Lineup: 'The BFG', 'Nice Guys', Penn, Refn, Almod\u00f3var & More Confirmed; No Closing-Night Pic|first=Nancy Tartaglione,Ali|last=Jaafar|date=April 14, 2016|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=December 1, 2017}}</ref> on May 14, 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/press/programmation/?date=2016-05-14#|title=Programme|website=[[Cannes Film Festival|Festival de Cannes]]|accessdate=December 1, 2017}}</ref> and received a wide release in the US on July 1, 2016.<ref name=June14dates />\n\nSpielberg directed Tom Hanks and [[Meryl Streep]] in ''[[The Post (film)|The Post]]'', an account of ''[[The Washington Post]]'''s printing of the [[Pentagon Papers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/03/steven-spielberg-tom-hanks-meryl-streep-pentagon-papers-oscar-race-the-post-1202040913/|title=Spielberg, Hanks & Streep's Pentagon Papers Pic A Contender In Next Oscar Race|last=Fleming, Jr.|first=Mike|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 10, 2017|accessdate=March 30, 2017}}</ref> Production began in New York on May 30, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/Production-Underway-on-Spielbergs-THE-PAPERS-Starring-Meryl-Streep-Tom-Hanks-20170606|title=Production Underway on Spielberg's THE PAPERS, Starring Meryl Streep & Tom Hanks|website=Broadwayworld.com|accessdate=December 1, 2017}}</ref> The film began a limited release on December 22, 2017, with a wide release following on January 12, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/04/22/queen-bohemian-rhapsody-steven-spielberg-pentagon-papers-release-dates/|title=Steven Spielberg, Bryan Singer's Queen Film Land Awards Season Releases|website=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=December 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSpielberg directed the [[Ready Player One (film)|film adaptation]] of the popular sci-fi novel ''[[Ready Player One]]'', by [[Ernest Cline]]. The film stars [[Tye Sheridan]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/tye-sheridan-lands-lead-in-steven-spielbergs-ready-player-one-20160225|title=Tye Sheridan Lands Lead In Steven Spielberg's 'Ready Play \u2013 The Playlist|author=Kevin Jagernauth|date=February 25, 2016|work=The Playlist|accessdate=March 10, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306074739/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/tye-sheridan-lands-lead-in-steven-spielbergs-ready-player-one-20160225|archive-date=March 6, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Olivia Cooke]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/me-earl-the-dying-girl-bates-motel-star-olivia-cooke-wins-lead-in-steven-spielbergs-ready-player-one-20150911|title='Me, Earl & The Dying Girl' & 'Bates Motel' Star Olivia C \u2013 The Playlist|author=Oliver Lyttelton|date=September 11, 2015|work=The Playlist|access-date=September 11, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150914011858/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/me-earl-the-dying-girl-bates-motel-star-olivia-cooke-wins-lead-in-steven-spielbergs-ready-player-one-20150911|archive-date=September 14, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Ben Mendelsohn]], [[Simon Pegg]] and [[Mark Rylance]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=McNary|first=Dave|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/steven-spielberg-ready-player-one-mark-rylance-1201752474/|title=Mark Rylance Joins Steven Spielberg's 'Ready Player One'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=Variety Media, LLC|date=April 13, 2016|accessdate=July 4, 2016}}</ref> It began production in London in July 2016,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2016/06/26/bfg-steven-spielberg-mark-rylance/86164382/|title=New BFFs Spielberg, Rylance team up for 'The BFG' and big things beyond|access-date=July 4, 2016}}</ref> a year before ''The Post'', which was filmed, edited and released during the lengthy, effects-heavy post-production period for ''Ready Player One''. ''Ready Player One'' was originally slated to be released on December 15, 2017<ref>{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2015/08/steven-spielbergs-ready-player-one-december-15-2017-release-warner-bros-1201493651/|title=Steven Spielberg's 'Ready Player One' Slotted For December 2017|author=Mike Fleming Jr|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation|Penske Business Media, LLC]]|date=August 6, 2015|accessdate=March 10, 2018}}</ref> by [[Warner Bros.]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/03/ready-player-one-movie-steven-spielberg-ernest-cline-warner-bros-1201398299/|title=Steven Spielberg To Direct Sci-Fi Cult Favorite 'Ready Player One'; Back At Warner Bros.|author=Anita Busch|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 25, 2015}}</ref> but was pushed back to March 29, 2018, to avoid competition with ''[[Star Wars: The Last Jedi]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lang|first=Brent|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/ready-player-one-steven-spielberg-star-wars-1201701175/|title=Steven Spielberg's 'Ready Player One' Pushed Back to Avoid 'Star Wars: Episode VIII'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=Variety Media, LLC|date=February 9, 2016|accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref> It had its world premiere at the [[South by Southwest]] film festival, on March 11, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/spielbergs-ready-player-one-premiere-hit-with-technical-difficulties-1202723753/|title=Spielberg's 'Ready Player One' Premiere Hit With Technical Difficulties|first=Variety|last=Staff|date=March 12, 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nSpielberg is directing ''[[West Side Story (2020 film)|West Side Story]]'', a new film adaptation of the [[West Side Story|classic musical]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/03/fox-revives-west-side-story-for-steven-spielberg-as-town-ponders-stacey-snider-move-and-dreamworks-future/|title='West Side Story' Remake For Steven Spielberg In Works At Fox \u2013 Deadline|author=Mike Fleming Jr|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation|Penske Business Media, LLC]]|date=March 5, 2014}}</ref> [[Tony Kushner]] stated in July 2017 that he was adapting the show's book for Spielberg, though the musical score would remain unchanged, as would the late 1950s setting.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/tony-kushner-why-im-writing-a-play-about-donald-trump|title=Tony Kushner: Why I'm Writing a Play About Donald Trump|first=Tim|last=Teeman|date=July 19, 2017|accessdate=December 1, 2017|newspaper=The Daily Beast}}</ref> The film is set to be released by Disney on December 18, 2020.<ref>McPhee, Ryan (May 7, 2019).  [http://www.playbill.com/article/new-west-side-story-movie-sets-december-2020-release \"New West Side Story Movie Sets December 2020 Release.\"]  ''[[Playbill]]''.  Retrieved April 2, 2020.</ref>\n\n===Upcoming projects===\nDuring an interview with ''[[The Tech (newspaper)|The Tech]]'' in 2015, Spielberg described how he chooses the film projects he would work on:\n\n<blockquote>[Sometimes], a story speaks to me, even if it doesn't speak to any of my collaborators or any of my partners, who look at me and scratch their heads and say, 'Gee, are you sure you wanna get into that trench for a year and a half?' I love people challenging me that way because it's a real test about my own convictions and [whether] I can be the standing man of my own life and take a stand on a subject that may not be popular, but that I would be proud to add to the body of my work. That's pretty much the litmus test that gets me to say, 'Yeah, I'll direct that one.'<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wang|first1=Ray|title=The Tech talks to Steven Spielberg|url=https://thetech.com/2015/10/22/spielberginterview-v135-n28|website=[[The Tech (newspaper)|The Tech]]|publisher=The Tech|accessdate=March 10, 2018|date=October 22, 2015}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nSpielberg was scheduled to film his long-planned adaptation of [[David Kertzer]]'s ''The Kidnapping of [[Edgardo Mortara]]'' in early 2017, for release at the end of that year,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/04/steven-spielberg-the-kidnapping-of-edgardo-mortara-next-movie-mark-rylance-tony-kushner-1201735799/|title=Steven Spielberg Sets 'The Kidnapping Of Edgardo Mortara' Next; Tony Kushner Script, Mark Rylance Is Pope Pius IX|last=Jr|first=Mike Fleming|date=April 11, 2016|accessdate=July 4, 2016}}</ref> but production has been postponed. The book follows the true story of a young Jewish boy in 1858 Italy who was secretly baptized by a family servant and then kidnapped from his family by the Papal States, where he was raised and trained as a priest, causing international outrage and becoming a media sensation. It was first announced in 2014, with Kushner adapting the book for the screen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/steven-spielberg-tony-kushner-edgardo-mortara-1201157963/|title=Steven Spielberg Boards Religious Drama 'Edgardo Mortara' (Exclusive)|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=April 18, 2014|accessdate=July 4, 2016}}</ref> [[Mark Rylance]], in his fourth consecutive collaboration with Spielberg, was announced to star in the role of [[Pope Pius IX]]. [[Oscar Isaac]] was set to star as Mortara's father, but eventually dropped out.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/oscar-isaac-nazi-hunt-operation-finale/|title=Oscar Isaac Starring in Nazi Hunt Thriller Operation Finale|date=March 29, 2017|website=Screenrant.com|accessdate=December 1, 2017}}</ref> Spielberg had difficulty casting the title role, though he saw more than 2000 kids.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2018/01/steven-spielberg-indiana-jones-west-side-story-directing-vehicles-1202262857/|date=January 19, 2018|accessdate=January 25, 2018|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation|Penske Business Media, LLC]]|title=Steven Spielberg Eyes Indiana Jones & 'West Side Story' Atop Next Directing Vehicles|first=Mike|last=Fleming Jr.}}</ref>\n\nSpielberg is attached to direct an adaptation of American photojournalist [[Lynsey Addario]]'s memoir ''It's What I Do''. [[Jennifer Lawrence]] is attached to star in the lead role.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/steven-spielberg-jennifer-lawrence-lynsey-addario-movie/|title=Steven Spielberg to Direct Jennifer Lawrence in War Memoir Adaptation IT'S WHAT I DO|date=March 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, it was announced that Spielberg would direct a film adaptation of the ''[[Blackhawk (DC Comics)|Blackhawk]]'' comic book series. [[Warner Bros. Pictures]] will distribute the film, with [[David Koepp]] writing the script.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/movies/news/steven-spielberg-to-direct-film-adaptation-of-dc's-'blackhawk'/ar-AAvZA7O?ocid=spartanntp | title=Steven Spielberg to Direct Film Adaptation of DC's 'Blackhawk' }}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> During an interview in 1981 to promote ''Raiders of the Lost Ark'', Spielberg likened that film to the ''Blackhawk'' series.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sragow|first1=Michael|authorlink1=Michael Sragow|title=Inside 'Raiders of the Lost Ark'|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/features/raiders-of-the-lost-ark-19810625|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=April 22, 2018|date=June 25, 1981|quote=\"The one [Spielberg] feels ''Raiders'' is closest to is ''Blackhawk'' \u2013 the DC comic (and 1952 Sam Katzman serial)...\"}}</ref>\n\n====Projects on hold====\nIn 2009, Spielberg reportedly tried to obtain the screen rights to make a film based on [[Microsoft]]'s [[Halo (series)|''Halo'' series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2010/10/the_new_halo_video_game_is_a_h.html|title=The New Halo Game Is a Hit \u2013 So What's the Status of the Halo Movie?}}</ref> In September 2008, Steven Spielberg bought film rights for [[John Wyndham]]'s novel ''[[Chocky]]'' and is interested in directing it. He is also interested in making an adaptation of ''[[A Steady Rain]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=SDCC: Spielberg Interested in A Steady Rain Movie|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=80084|accessdate=July 21, 2011|publisher=ComingSoon|date=July 21, 2011}}</ref> ''[[Pirate Latitudes]]'',<ref>Spielberg to make pirates movie \u2013 Yahoo! Movies UK & Ireland {{cite web|url=http://uk.movies.yahoo.com/27082009/5/spielberg-pirates-movie-0.html|title=Yahoo Movies UK|accessdate=August 28, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090917051419/http://uk.movies.yahoo.com/27082009/5/spielberg-pirates-movie-0.html|archivedate=September 17, 2009 }}</ref> ''[[The 39 Clues]]'',<ref>{{cite news| author = Michael Fleming| title = Steven Spielberg follows '39 Clues'| work = Variety| date = June 24, 2008| url = https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117988019.html?categoryid=13&cs=1| accessdate = September 3, 2008| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081228030804/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117988019.html?categoryid=13&cs=1| archive-date = December 28, 2008| url-status = dead}}</ref> and a remake of ''[[When Worlds Collide (1951 film)|When Worlds Collide]]''.\n\nIn May 2009, Steven Spielberg bought the rights to the life story of [[Martin Luther King, Jr.]] Spielberg will be involved not only as producer but also as a director.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/5351278/Steven-Spielberg-to-direct-Martin-Luther-King-film.html \"Steven Spielberg to direct Martin Luther King film\"] ''Daily Telegraph'', May 19, 2009. Footnote format December 24, 2009.</ref> However, the purchase was made from the King estate, led by son [[Dexter King|Dexter]], while the two other surviving children, the [[Bernice Albertine King|Reverend Bernice]] and [[Martin Luther King III|Martin III]], immediately threatened to sue, not having given their approvals to the project.<ref>[http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/05/20/kings-children-may -sue-over-planned-biographical-film/ \"King's Children May Sue Over Planned Biographical Film\"] by Dave Itzkoff, ''[[The New York Times]]'' ArtsBeat blog, May 20, 2009. Retrieved December 24, 2009.</ref>\n\n===Production credits===\nSince the mid-1980s, Spielberg has increased his role as a film producer. He headed up the production team for several cartoons, including the Warner Bros. hits ''[[Tiny Toon Adventures]]'', ''[[Animaniacs]]'', ''[[Pinky and the Brain]]'', ''[[Toonsylvania]]'', and ''[[Freakazoid!]]'', for which he collaborated with [[Jean MacCurdy]] and [[Tom Ruegger]]. Due to his work on these series, in the official titles, most of them say, \"Steven Spielberg presents\" as well as making numerous cameos on the shows. Spielberg also produced the [[Don Bluth]] animated features, ''[[An American Tail]]'' and ''[[The Land Before Time]]'', which were released by [[Universal Studios]]. He also served as one of the executive producers of ''[[Who Framed Roger Rabbit]]'' and its three related shorts (''Tummy Trouble'', ''Roller Coaster Rabbit'', ''Trail Mix-Up''), which were all released by Disney, under both the [[Walt Disney Pictures]] and the [[Touchstone Pictures]] banners. He was furthermore, for a short time, the executive producer of the long-running medical drama ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]''. In 1989, he brought the concept of ''[[The Dig (video game)|The Dig]]'' to [[LucasArts]]. He contributed to the project from that time until 1995 when the game was released. He also collaborated with software publishers [[Knowledge Adventure]] on the multimedia game ''[[Steven Spielberg's Director's Chair]]'', which was released in 1996. Spielberg appears, as himself, in the game to direct the player. The Spielberg name provided branding for a [[Lego]] Moviemaker kit, the proceeds of which went to the Starbright Foundation.\n\n[[File:Steven Spielberg 1999.jpg|thumb|left|Spielberg speaking at the Pentagon on August 11, 1999 after receiving the Department of Defense Medal for Distinguished Public Service from Secretary of Defense [[William S. Cohen]]]]\n\nIn 1993, Spielberg acted as executive producer for the highly anticipated television series ''[[seaQuest DSV]]''; a science fiction series set \"in the near future\" starring [[Roy Scheider]] (who Spielberg had directed in ''Jaws'') and [[Jonathan Brandis]] that aired on [[NBC]]. While the first season was moderately successful, the second season did less well. Spielberg's name no longer appeared in the third season and the show was cancelled midway through it.\n\nSpielberg served as an uncredited executive producer on ''[[The Haunting (1999 film)|The Haunting]]'', ''[[The Prince of Egypt]]'', ''[[Just Like Heaven (film)|Just Like Heaven]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/386887.If_Only_It_Were_True|title=If Only It Were True by Marc Levy \u2013 Reviews, Discussion, Bookclubs, Lists|publisher=Goodreads.com|accessdate=May 25, 2012}}</ref> ''[[Shrek]]'', ''[[Road to Perdition]]'',<ref name=\"killer\">{{cite news|first=Jeff |last=Jensen|url=https://ew.com/article/2002/07/19/killer-instinct-6/|title= From the EW archives: Tom Hanks talks ''Road to Perdition''|work=Entertainment Weekly| date=July 19, 2002| accessdate=October 22, 2019}}</ref> and ''[[Evolution (2001 film)|Evolution]]''. He served as an executive producer for the 1997 film ''[[Men in Black (1997 film)|Men in Black]]'', and its sequels, ''[[Men in Black II]]'', ''[[Men in Black III]]'', and ''[[Men in Black: International]]''. In 2005, he served as a producer of ''[[Memoirs of a Geisha (film)|Memoirs of a Geisha]]'', an adaptation of the novel by [[Arthur Golden]], a film to which he was previously attached as director. In 2006, Spielberg co-executive produced with famed filmmaker [[Robert Zemeckis]] a CGI children's film called ''[[Monster House (film)|Monster House]]'', marking their eighth collaboration since 1990's ''[[Back to the Future Part III]]''. He also teamed with [[Clint Eastwood]] for the first time in their careers, co-producing Eastwood's ''[[Flags of Our Fathers (film)|Flags of Our Fathers]]'' and ''[[Letters from Iwo Jima]]'' with [[Robert Lorenz]] and Eastwood himself. He earned his twelfth Academy Award nomination for the latter film as it was nominated for Best Picture. Spielberg served as executive producer for ''[[Disturbia (film)|Disturbia]]'' and the ''[[Transformers (film)|Transformers]]'' live action film series with [[Hasbro]] CEO [[Brian Goldner]]. The films, including sequels ''[[Transformers: Revenge of the Fallen]]'', ''[[Transformers: Dark of the Moon]]'', ''[[Transformers: Age of Extinction]]'', and ''[[Transformers: The Last Knight]]'' were directed by [[Michael Bay]] and written by [[Roberto Orci]] and [[Alex Kurtzman]]. In 2011, he produced the [[J. J. Abrams]] science fiction thriller film ''[[Super 8 (2011 film)|Super 8]]'' for [[Paramount Pictures]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/20108|title=NEW 'Super 8' Teaser Details, Spielberg/Abrams Collaboration Confirmed!|publisher=Bloody-disgusting.com|accessdate=January 31, 2011|date=May 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOther major television series Spielberg produced were ''[[Band of Brothers (TV miniseries)|Band of Brothers]]'', ''[[Taken (TV miniseries)|Taken]]'' and ''[[The Pacific (miniseries)|The Pacific]]''. He was an executive producer on the critically acclaimed 2005 TV miniseries ''[[Into the West (TV miniseries)|Into the West]]'' which won two Emmy awards, including one for [[Geoff Zanelli]]'s score. For his 2010 miniseries ''[[The Pacific (miniseries)|The Pacific]]'' he teamed up once again with co-producer Tom Hanks, with [[Gary Goetzman]] also co-producing'. The miniseries is believed to have cost $250&nbsp;million and is a 10-part war miniseries centered on the battles in the Pacific Theater during World War II. Writer [[Bruce McKenna]], who penned several installments of (''[[Band of Brothers (TV miniseries)|Band of Brothers]]''), was the head writer.\n\nIn 2007, Steven Spielberg and [[Mark Burnett (executive producer)|Mark Burnett]] co-produced ''[[On the Lot]]'' a short-lived TV reality show about filmmaking. Despite this, he never gave up working on television. He currently serves as one of the executive producers on ''[[United States of Tara]]'', a show created by [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Academy Award]] [[Juno (film)|winner]] [[Diablo Cody]] which they developed together (Spielberg is uncredited as creator).\n\nIn 2011, Spielberg launched ''[[Falling Skies]]'', a science fiction television series, on the [[TNT (U.S. TV network)|TNT]] network. He developed the series with [[Robert Rodat]] and is credited as an executive producer. Spielberg is also producing the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] TV series ''[[Terra Nova (TV series)|Terra Nova]]''. ''Terra Nova'' begins in the year 2149 when all life on the planet Earth is threatened with extinction resulting in scientists opening a door that allows people to travel back 85&nbsp;million years to prehistoric times.<ref>{{cite news|last = Schneider|first = Michael|title = Spielberg takes development role in Fox TV projects|work = Variety|date = December 11, 2006|url = https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117955420.html|archive-url = https://archive.today/20120914135029/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117955420.html|url-status = dead|archive-date = September 14, 2012|accessdate = December 11, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2011/03/11/fox-pushes-back-terra-nova-to-fall/|title=Fox pushes back 'Terra Nova' to fall|first=James|last=Hibberd|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=March 11, 2011|accessdate=October 22, 2019}}</ref> Spielberg also produced ''[[The River (U.S. TV series)|The River]]'',<ref>{{cite news|title=ABC's 'The River' offers scary mystery|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/livefrom/post/2011/07/abcs-the-river-offers-scary-mystery/1|accessdate=July 22, 2011| work=USA Today|date=July 22, 2011}}</ref> ''[[Smash (U.S. TV series)|Smash]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title='Smash': It has Steven Spielberg, Katharine McPhee, Marilyn Monroe|url=http://blogs.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment_tv_tvblog/2011/05/smash-it-has-steven-spielberg-katharaine-mcphee-marilyn-monroe.html|accessdate=May 15, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520062315/https://blogs.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment_tv_tvblog/2011/05/smash-it-has-steven-spielberg-katharaine-mcphee-marilyn-monroe.html|archivedate=May 20, 2011}}</ref> ''[[Under the Dome (TV series)|Under the Dome]]'',<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/stephen-king-steven-spielberg-go-under-the-dome-20130619|title=Stephen King, Steven Spielberg Go 'Under the Dome'|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=December 1, 2017|date=June 19, 2013}}</ref> ''[[Extant (TV series)|Extant]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/voices/columns/extant-falling-skies-steven-spielberg-tv-aliens-1201557417/|title=Steven Spielberg's 'Extant' Only One of Many Alien TV Shows \u2013 Variety|author=Brian Lowry|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=Variety Media, LLC|date=August 6, 2015}}</ref> ''[[The Whispers (TV series)|The Whispers]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/reviews/the-whispers-review-steven-spielberg-series-abc-1201502034/|title='The Whispers' Review Steven Spielberg Series ABC \u2013 Variety|author=Brian Lowry|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=Variety Media, LLC|date=May 29, 2015}}</ref> a [[Minority Report (TV series)|TV adaptation]] of ''Minority Report'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/minority-report-fox-tv-show-tom-cruise-movie-1201596829/|title='Minority Report': Producers on Show Based on Tom Cruise Movie \u2013 Variety|author=Whitney Friedlander|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=Variety Media, LLC|date=September 21, 2015}}</ref> and ''[[Bull (2016 TV series)|Bull]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/03/glenn-gordon-caron-new-bull-showrunner-overall-deal-cbs-studios-1202047310/|title=Glenn Gordon Caron Tapped As New 'Bull' Showrunner Under CBS TV Studios Deal|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=March 20, 2017|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=December 1, 2017}}</ref> However, following sexual misconduct allegations against [[Michael Weatherly]], Amblin stopped producing the series, and Spielberg no longer served as an executive producer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/steven-spielbergs-amblin-tv-leaves-cbs-bull-harassment-scandal-1209256|title=Steven Spielberg's Amblin TV Leaves CBS' 'Bull' Over Harassment Scandal|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Rick|last=Porter|date=May 9, 2019|accessdate=May 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Spielberg and DreamWorks acquired the rights to produce [[Ghost in the Shell (2017 film)|a live-action film adaptation]] of the original ''[[Ghost in the Shell]]'' [[manga]]. [[Avi Arad]] and [[Steven Paul]] produced, [[Rupert Sanders]] directed, and [[Scarlett Johansson]] stars in the lead role of the film, which was released in 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117984029?refCatId=13|title=DreamWorks to make 'Ghost' in 3-D|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=November 9, 2011|first1=Tatiana|last1=Siegel|first2=Michael|last2=Fleming|date=April 14, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110818221658/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117984029?refCatId=13|archive-date=August 18, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|title=Scarlett Johansson Signs on to Star in DreamWorks' 'Ghost in the Shell' (EXCLUSIVE)|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/scarlett-johansson-signs-on-to-star-in-dreamworks-ghost-in-the-shell-exclusive-1201320788/|accessdate=January 5, 2015|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=January 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last= Bishop|first=Bryan|title=Live-action 'Ghost in the Shell' movie signs the director of 'Snow White and the Huntsman'|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/1/25/5343472/live-action-ghost-in-the-shell-movie-signs-the-director-of-snow-white|website=[[The Verge]]|accessdate=March 3, 2014|date=January 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, HBO confirmed that it was developing a third World War II miniseries based on the book ''Masters of the Air'' by [[Donald L. Miller]] with Spielberg and Tom Hanks to follow ''Band of Brothers'' and ''The Pacific''.<ref>[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/hbo-developing-third-wwii-miniseries-413632 HBO Developing Third WWII Miniseries with Tom Hanks, Steven Spielberg (Exclusive)] (The Hollywood Reporter)</ref> Few details have emerged about the project since, but ''[[NME]]'' reported in March 2017 that production was progressing under the working title ''[[Donald L. Miller#Masters of the Air|The Mighty Eighth]]''.<ref>[https://www.nme.com/news/tv/the-mighty-eighth-filming-spielberg-tom-hanks-1998119 Production progresses on reported Spielberg/Tom Hanks HBO miniseries 'The Mighty Eighth'] (NME)</ref>\n\nIn March 2013, Spielberg announced that he was \"developing a [[List of Stanley Kubrick's unrealized projects#Napoleon|Stanley Kubrick screenplay]] for a miniseries, not for a motion picture, about the life of [[Napoleon]].\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/steven-spielberg-developing-stanley-kubricks-425771|title=Steven Spielberg developing Stanley Kubrick|work=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> In May 2016, it was announced that [[Cary Fukunaga]] is in talks to direct the miniseries for [[HBO]], from a script by [[David Lenland]] based on extensive research materials accumulated by Kubrick over many years.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/cary-fukunaga-talks-direct-hbo-895382|title=Cary Fukunaga in Talks to Direct HBO Stanley Kubrick Mini 'Napoleon,' From Steven Spielberg|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=December 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSpielberg had planned to shoot a $200&nbsp;million adaptation of [[Daniel H. Wilson]]'s novel ''[[Robopocalypse]]'', adapted for the screen by [[Drew Goddard]].<ref name=\"Steven Spielberg Commits To Next Direct Robopocalypse\">{{cite web| url = https://www.deadline.com/2010/10/steven-spielberg-commits-to-direct-robopocalypse/| title = Steven Spielberg Commits To Next Direct 'Robopocalypse'| access-date=June 8, 2011| date = October 22, 2010}}</ref> The novel follows a global human war against a robot uprising about 15\u201320 years in the future.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/steven-spielberg-says-robopocalypse-will-be-set-15-20-years-in-the-future-center-on-man-vs-machine-war|title=Steven Spielberg Says 'Robopocalypse' Will Be Set 15\u201320 Years in the Future, Center on Man Vs. Machine War &#124; The Playlist|publisher=Blogs.indiewire.com|access-date=May 25, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504221640/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/steven-spielberg-says-robopocalypse-will-be-set-15-20-years-in-the-future-center-on-man-vs-machine-war|archive-date=May 4, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Like ''[[Lincoln (film)|Lincoln]]'', it was to be released by Disney in the United States and [[Fox Film Corporation|Fox]] overseas.<ref name=\"DreamWorks, Fox To Co-Finance Steven Spielberg's 'Robopocalypse'\">{{cite web| url = https://www.deadline.com/2011/09/disney-fox-to-co-finance-steven-spielbergs-robopocalypse/| title = DreamWorks, Fox To Co-Finance Steven Spielberg's 'Robopocalypse'| access-date=September 7, 2011| date = September 7, 2011}}</ref> It was set for release on April 25, 2014,<ref name=\"'X-Men: First Class' & 'Rise Of The Planet Of The Apes' Sequels Set For Summer 2014; 'Independence Day 3D' Hits July 3, 2013\">{{cite web| url = http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/x-men-first-class-rise-of-the-planet-of-the-apes-sequels-set-for-summer-2014-20120531| title = 'X-Men: First Class' & 'Rise Of The Planet Of The Apes' Sequels Set For Summer 2014; 'Independence Day 3D' Hits July 3, 2013| access-date = May 31, 2012| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130509160644/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/x-men-first-class-rise-of-the-planet-of-the-apes-sequels-set-for-summer-2014-20120531| archive-date = May 9, 2013| url-status=dead| df = mdy-all}}</ref> with [[Anne Hathaway]] and [[Chris Hemsworth]] set to star,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/steven-spielberg-indefinitely-postpones-robopocalypse-with-chris-hemsworth-anne-hathaway-20130109|title=Steven Spielberg Indefinitely Postpones 'Robopocalypse' W \u2013 The Playlist|author=Oliver Lyttelton|date=January 10, 2013|work=The Playlist|access-date=June 16, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130513130412/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/steven-spielberg-indefinitely-postpones-robopocalypse-with-chris-hemsworth-anne-hathaway-20130109|archive-date=May 13, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> but Spielberg postponed production indefinitely in January 2013, just before it was to begin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/steven-spielbergs-robopocalypse-postponed-indefinitely-410519|title=Steven Spielberg's 'Robopocalypse' Postponed Indefinitely \u2013 Hollywood Reporter|author=Kim Masters|work=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> In March 2018, it was announced that the film will now be directed by [[Michael Bay]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/03/michael-bay-robopocalypse-6-underground-directing-movies-1202315936/|title=Michael Bay Lining Up 'Robopocalypse' & '6 Underground' As Next Projects|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=March 7, 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nSpielberg will executive produce ''Cortes'', a historical mini-series written by [[Steven Zaillian]] about the Spanish conquest of the Aztec empire, and [[Hern\u00e1n Cort\u00e9s]]'s relationship with Aztec ruler [[Moctezuma II|Montezuma]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sexenio.com.mx/1fila/articulo.php?id=49392|title=Steven Spielberg grabar\u00e1 cinta sobre Moctezuma y Hern\u00e1n Cort\u00e9s {{!}} 1Fila|author=Sexenio.com.mx|accessdate=July 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610211708/http://www.sexenio.com.mx/1fila/articulo.php?id=49392|archive-date=June 10, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The script is based on an earlier one from 1965 by Oscar-winner [[Dalton Trumbo]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://screenrant.com/steven-spielberg-montezuma-cortes-movie-javier-bardem/|title=Steven Spielberg May Direct Montezuma-Cortes Film Starring Javier Bardem|work=[[Screen Rant]]|publisher=Valnet, Inc.|date=January 6, 2014|accessdate=July 4, 2016}}</ref> [[Javier Bardem]] will play the lead role of explorer Hern\u00e1n Cort\u00e9s. Spielberg was previously attached to direct the project as a feature film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/amazon-revives-dalton-trumbos-cortes-javier-bardem-star-mini-steven-spielberg-steven-zaillian-1097548|title=Amazon Revives Dalton Trumbo's 'Cortes': Javier Bardem to Star in Mini From Steven Spielberg, Steven Zaillian|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nSpielberg had originally planned to direct the untitled fifth installment in the [[Indiana Jones (franchise)|''Indiana Jones'' series]]. The film is set to star [[Harrison Ford]] and will be produced by [[Kathleen Kennedy (producer)|Kathleen Kennedy]] and [[Frank Marshall (producer)|Frank Marshall]]. In 2016 it was announced that it would be written by [[David Koepp]], who has written numerous other films for Spielberg, including the previous ''Indiana Jones'' film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/indiana-jones-5-writer-david-koepp-1201733969/|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=Variety Media, LLC|title='Indiana Jones 5' Taps Writer David Koepp, a Steven Spielberg Regular|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=March 18, 2016|accessdate=July 4, 2016}}</ref> It was originally set for release by Disney on July 19, 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/steven-spielberg-harrison-ford-team-up-for-indiana-jones-5-disney-sets-july-2019-release-1201720725/|title=Steven Spielberg & Harrison Ford Team Up For 'Indiana Jones 5'; Disney Sets July 2019 Release|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation|Penske Business Media, LLC]]|date=March 15, 2016|accessdate=July 4, 2016}}</ref> It was then announced that filming would begin in the UK in April 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theplaylist.net/spielberg-indy-5-20180319/|title=Spielberg Confirms 'Indy 5' Will Begin Production In April 2019|date=March 19, 2018|publisher=}}</ref> and the film was given a new release date of July 10, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starwars.com/news/star-wars-episode-ix-and-next-indiana-jones-get-release-dates|title=Star Wars: Episode IX and Next Indiana Jones Get Release Dates|website=Starwars.com|accessdate=December 1, 2017}}</ref> Filming was postponed again in June 2018, when [[Jonathan Kasdan]] was announced as the film's new writer.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/indiana-jones-5-release-date-spielberg-harrison-ford-1202861005/ | title='Indiana Jones 5' Will Miss 2020 Release Date (EXCLUSIVE)| date=June 28, 2018}}</ref> Soon after, a new release date of July 9, 2021 was announced.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/indiana-jones-5-release-date-pushed-again-2021-1125975 | title=Disney Pushes 'Indiana Jones 5' a Year to 2021, Dates 'Maleficent 2,' 'Jungle Cruise'}}</ref> In May 2019, it was reported that [[Dan Fogelman]] had been hired to write a new script, and that Kasdan's story, which focused on the [[Nazi gold train]], would not be used.<ref>https://comicbook.com/movies/2019/05/01/indiana-jones-5-new-writer-abandoned-plot-details-revealed/</ref> In February 2020, it was reported that, because he wanted to \"pass along Indy's whip to a new generation to bring their perspective to the story\", Spielberg will no longer direct the film, through he will remain involved in the project as a producer.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vary|first1=Adam B.|last2=Kroll|first2=Justin|last3=Lang|first3=Brent|title=Steven Spielberg Won't Direct 'Indiana Jones 5,' James Mangold in Talks to Replace (EXCLUSIVE)|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/steven-spielberg-indiana-jones-5-james-mangold-harrison-ford-1203515698|accessdate=February 26, 2020|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Onscreen appearances ===\nSpielberg had cameo roles in ''[[The Blues Brothers (film)|The Blues Brothers]]'', ''[[Gremlins]]'', ''[[Vanilla Sky]]'', and ''[[Austin Powers in Goldmember]]'', as well as small uncredited cameos in a handful of other films, such as a life-station worker in ''Jaws''. He also made numerous cameo roles in the Warner Bros. cartoons he produced, such as Animaniacs, and even made reference to some of his films. Spielberg voiced himself in the film ''[[Paul (film)|Paul]]'', and in one episode of ''[[Tiny Toon Adventures]]'' titled ''Buster and Babs Go Hawaiian''.\n\nIn 2017, Spielberg, along with fellow directors [[Francis Ford Coppola]], [[Guillermo del Toro]], [[Paul Greengrass]] and [[Lawrence Kasdan]] were featured in the [[Netflix]] documentary series ''[[Five Came Back (TV series)|Five Came Back]]'', which discussed the contributions of film directors [[Frank Capra]], [[John Ford]], [[John Huston]], [[George Stevens]] and [[William Wyler]] towards recording the events of [[World War II]]. Spielberg also served as an executive producer on the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/02/five-came-back-netflix-trailer-spielberg-coppola-del-toro-greengrass-kasdan-1202026705/|title='Netflix's 'Five Came Back' With Spielberg, Coppola, Del Toro, Greengrass & Kasdan Drops Trailer \u2013 Watch|first=Anita|last=Busch|date=February 28, 2017|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=December 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Involvement in video games ===\nApart from being an ardent gamer Spielberg has had a long history of involvement in video games.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/7260228.stm|title=Making games with Steven Spielberg|work=BBC News|date=February 23, 2008|accessdate=January 6, 2010|first=Darren|last=Waters}}</ref> He has been giving thanks to his games of his division [[DreamWorks Interactive]] as ''Someone's in the Kitchen'' with script written by [[Animaniacs]]' [[Paul Rugg]], ''[[Escape from HorrorLand|Goosebumps: Escape from HorrorLand]]'', ''[[The Neverhood]]'' (all in 1996), ''[[Skullmonkeys]]'', ''[[Dilbert's Desktop Games]]'', ''[[Goosebumps: Attack of the Mutant]]'' (all 1997), ''[[Boombots]]'' (1999), ''[[T'ai Fu: Wrath of the Tiger]]'' (1999), and ''[[Clive Barker's Undying]]'' (2001). In 2005 the director signed with [[Electronic Arts]] to collaborate on three games including an action game and an award-winning puzzle game for the [[Wii]] called ''[[Boom Blox]]'' (and its 2009 sequel: ''[[Boom Blox Bash Party]]'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/353191/spielbergs-boom-blox-revealed|title=Spielberg's Boom Blox Revealed|publisher=Kotaku.com|date=February 6, 2008|accessdate=January 31, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110623144325/https://kotaku.com/353191/spielbergs-boom-blox-revealed|archivedate=June 23, 2011}}</ref> Previously, he was involved in creating the scenario for the adventure game ''[[The Dig (video game)|The Dig]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adventureclassicgaming.com/index.php/site/features/265/|title=The Dig: in the deep of space, a curse is alive...|publisher=Adventure Classic Gaming|accessdate=January 31, 2011}}</ref> In 1996, Spielberg worked on and shot original footage for a movie-making simulation game called ''[[Steven Spielberg's Director's Chair]]''. He is the creator of the ''[[Medal of Honor (video game series)|Medal of Honor]]'' series by [[Electronic Arts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mobygames.com/game/windows/medal-of-honor-allied-assault/credits|title=Medal of Honor: Allied Assault (2002) Windows credits|publisher=MobyGames|accessdate=January 31, 2011}}</ref> He is credited in the special thanks section of the 1998 video game ''[[Jurassic Park: Trespasser|Trespasser]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=14402&tab=credits|title=Trespasser \u2013 Credits|publisher=allgame|accessdate=March 2, 2010}}</ref> In 2013, Spielberg has announced he is collaborating with [[343 Industries]] for a live-action TV show of ''[[Halo (series)|Halo]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Watercutter|first=Angela|url=https://www.wired.com/underwire/2013/05/steven-spielberg-halo-xbox/|title=Steven Spielberg Working on Live-Action Halo Series for Xbox &#124; Underwire|journal=Wired|date=March 28, 2013|accessdate=June 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Themes ==\n{{Original research|section|date=April 2011}}\nSpielberg's films often deal with several recurring themes. Most of his films deal with ordinary characters searching for or coming in contact with extraordinary beings or finding themselves in extraordinary circumstances. <!-- This is especially evident in the [[Indiana Jones]] series. : Archaeologist, adventurer and relic hunter is not really an \"ordinary character\"-->In an [[American Film Institute|AFI]] interview in August 2000 Spielberg commented on his interest in the possibility of extraterrestrial life and how it has influenced some of his films. Spielberg described himself as feeling like an alien during childhood,<ref name=\"McBride\">{{cite book| last = McBride| first = Joseph| title = Steven Spielberg| publisher = Faber and Faber|year=1997| isbn = 978-0-571-19177-2}}</ref> and his interest came from his father, a science fiction fan, and his opinion that aliens would not travel light years for conquest, but instead curiosity and sharing of knowledge.<ref>{{cite book| title = E.T. DVD Production Notes Booklet| publisher = Universal|year=2002}}</ref>\n\nA strong consistent [[theme (literature)|theme]] in his family-friendly work is a childlike sense of wonder and faith, as attested by works such as ''[[Close Encounters of the Third Kind]]'', ''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]'', ''[[Hook (film)|Hook]]'', ''[[A.I. Artificial Intelligence]]'' and ''[[The BFG (2016 film)|The BFG]]''. According to Warren Buckland,<ref>Directed by Steven Spielberg: Poetics of the Contemporary Hollywood Blockbuster</ref> these themes are portrayed through the use of low height camera tracking shots, which have become one of Spielberg's directing trademarks. In the cases when his films include children (''E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial'', ''[[Empire of the Sun (film)|Empire of the Sun]]'', ''[[Jurassic Park (film)|Jurassic Park]]'', etc.), this type of shot is more apparent, but it is also used in films like ''[[Munich (film)|Munich]]'', ''[[Saving Private Ryan]]'', ''[[The Terminal]]'', ''[[Minority Report (film)|Minority Report]]'', and ''[[Amistad (1997 film)|Amistad]]''. Each of his films feature this shot utilized by the director, and the water scenes in ''Jaws'' are filmed from the low-angle perspective of someone swimming. Another child oriented theme in Spielberg's films is that of loss of innocence and coming-of-age. In ''Empire of the Sun'', Jim, a well-groomed and spoiled English youth, loses his innocence as he suffers through World War II China. Similarly, in ''[[Catch Me If You Can]]'', Frank naively and foolishly believes that he can reclaim his shattered family if he accumulates enough money to support them.\n\nThe most persistent theme throughout his films is tension in parent-child relationships. Parents (often fathers) are reluctant, absent or ignorant. Peter Banning in ''Hook'' starts off in the beginning of the film as a reluctant married-to-his-work parent who through the course of the film regains the respect of his children. The absence of Elliott's father in ''E.T.'' is the most famous example of this theme. In ''[[Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade]]'', it is revealed that Indy has always had a very strained relationship with his father, who is a professor of medieval literature, as his father always seemed more interested in his work, specifically in his studies of the Holy Grail, than in his own son, although his father does not seem to realize or understand the negative effect that his aloof nature had on Indy (he even believes he was a good father in the sense that he taught his son \"self reliance,\" which is not how Indy saw it). Even [[Oskar Schindler]], from ''[[Schindler's List]]'', is reluctant to have a child with his wife. In ''[[The Color Purple (film)|The Color Purple]]'', the main character, Celie, has been impregnated by her father multiple times. ''[[Munich (film)|Munich]]'' depicts Avner as a man away from his wife and newborn daughter. There are exceptions; Brody in ''[[Jaws (film)|Jaws]]'' is a committed family man, while John Anderton in ''[[Minority Report (film)|Minority Report]]'' is a shattered man after the disappearance of his son. This theme is arguably the most autobiographical aspect of Spielberg's films, since Spielberg himself was affected by his parents' divorce as a child and by the absence of his father. Furthermore, to this theme, protagonists in his films often come from families with divorced parents, including ''E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial'' (protagonist Elliot's mother is divorced) and ''[[Catch Me If You Can]]'' (Frank Abagnale's mother and father split early on in the film). Little known also is Tim in ''[[Jurassic Park (film)|Jurassic Park]]'' (early in the film, another secondary character mentions Tim and Lex's parents' divorce). The family often shown divided is often resolved in the ending as well. Following this theme of reluctant fathers and father figures, Tim looks to Dr. Alan Grant as a father figure. Initially, Dr. Grant is reluctant to return those paternal feelings to Tim. However, by the end of the film, he has changed, and the kids even fall asleep with their heads on his shoulders.\n\nMost of his films are generally optimistic in nature. Though some critics accuse his films of being a little overly sentimental, Spielberg feels it is fine as long as it is disguised.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}} He is still a highly praised director as well as being credited as one of the most influential directors of all time. The influence comes from directors [[Frank Capra]] and [[John Ford]].<ref name=\"culture show\">{{cite video| title = The Culture Show| medium = TV|publisher=BBC|date = November 4, 2006}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n=== Marriages and children ===\nSpielberg met actress [[Amy Irving]] in 1976 at the suggestion of director [[Brian De Palma]], who knew he was looking for an actress to play in ''Close Encounters''. After meeting her, Spielberg told his co-producer [[Julia Phillips]], \"I met a real heartbreaker last night.\"<ref name=McBride />{{rp|293}} Although she was too young for the role, she and Spielberg began dating and she eventually moved into what she described as his \"bachelor funky\" house.<ref name=McBride />{{rp|294}} They lived together for four years, but the stresses of their professional careers took a toll on their relationship. Irving wanted to be certain that whatever success she attained as an actress would be her own: \"I don't want to be known as Steven's girlfriend,\" she said, and chose not to be in any of his films during those years.<ref name=McBride />{{rp|295}} As a result, they broke up in 1979, but remained close friends. Then in 1984 they renewed their romance, and in November 1985 they married, after the birth of their son, Max Samuel. But after 3 1/2 years of marriage, many of the same competing stresses of their careers caused them to divorce in 1989. They agreed to maintain homes near each other to facilitate the shared custody and parenting of their son.<ref name=McBride />{{rp|403}} Their divorce was recorded as the third most costly celebrity divorce in history.<ref>{{cite news|title = 'Most costly' celebrity divorces|work=BBC News|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/6552597.stm|date = April 13, 2007}}</ref>\n\nSpielberg subsequently developed a relationship with actress [[Kate Capshaw]], whom he met when he cast her in ''[[Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom]]''. They married on October 12, 1991. Capshaw is a [[Conversion to Judaism|convert]] to Judaism.<ref>{{cite news|first=Karen W.|last=Arenson|title=From 'Schindler's List,' a Jewish Mission|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/09/24/us/from-schindler-s-list-a-jewish-mission.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 24, 1995|accessdate=May 11, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Capshaw\">{{cite book|last =Pogrebin| first =Abigail| title =Stars of David: Prominent Jews Talk About Being Jewish| publisher =Bantam Dell Pub Group|date=October 2005| isbn =978-0-7679-1612-7| title-link =Stars of David: Prominent Jews Talk About Being Jewish}}</ref> They currently move among their four homes in [[Pacific Palisades, California]]; Quelle Farm, [[Georgica Pond]] in [[East Hampton (village), New York|East Hampton, New York]];<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/2002/09/19/0919feat_7.html \"Billionaires on vacation: No. 80: Steven Spielberg\"] by Christina Valhouli, ''Forbes'' magazine, September 19, 2002. Retrieved December 24, 2009.</ref> [[New York City]]; and [[Naples, Florida]].\n\nThere are seven children in the Spielberg-Capshaw family:\n*[[Jessica Capshaw]] (born August 9, 1976) \u2013 daughter from Kate Capshaw's previous marriage to Robert Capshaw\n*Max Samuel Spielberg (born June 13, 1985) \u2013 son from Spielberg's previous marriage to actress [[Amy Irving]]\n*Theo Spielberg (born August 21, 1988) \u2013 son adopted by Capshaw before her marriage to Spielberg, who later also adopted him<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.funtrivia.com/en/Celebrities/Spielberg-Steven-14300.html|title=Spielberg, Steven \u2013 Fun Facts, Answers, Factoids, Info, Information|publisher=Funtrivia.com|accessdate=March 2, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100309223135/http://www.funtrivia.com/en/Celebrities/Spielberg-Steven-14300.html|archivedate=March 9, 2010}}</ref>\n*[[Sasha Spielberg|Sasha Rebecca Spielberg]] (born May 14, 1990, Los Angeles)\n*Sawyer Avery Spielberg (born March 10, 1992, Los Angeles)<ref>{{cite web|first=Dana|last=Schuster|title=A stage for Spielberg's son|url=https://nypost.com/2012/09/07/a-stage-for-spielbergs-son/|work=[[New York Post]]|date=September 7, 2012|accessdate=May 11, 2018}}</ref>\n*Mikaela George (born February 28, 1996) \u2013 adopted with Kate Capshaw\n*Destry Allyn Spielberg (born December 1, 1996)\n\n=== Religion ===\nSpielberg grew up in a Jewish household and had a [[bar mitzvah]] ceremony in Phoenix when he turned 13.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dbs.bh.org.il/luminary/spielberg-steven|title=Heroes - Trailblazers of the Jewish People|website=Beit Hatfutsot|access-date=}}</ref> He grew away from Judaism during his high-school years, after his family moved to various cities and found themselves the only Jews in their new neighborhoods.<ref name=Pogrebin />{{rp|29}} Before those years, his family was involved in the synagogue and had many Jewish friends and nearby relatives.\n\nHe remembers his grandparents telling him about their life in Russia, where they were subjected to religious persecution, causing them to eventually flee to the United States. He was made aware of [[the Holocaust]] by his parents, who he says \"talked about it all the time, and so it was always on my mind.\"<ref name=Pogrebin />{{rp|30}} His father had lost between sixteen and twenty relatives during the Holocaust.<ref name=McBride />{{rp|21}}\n\nSpielberg \"rediscovered the honor of being a Jew,\" he says, before he made ''Schindler's List'', when he married Kate Capshaw.<ref name=Pogrebin>Pogrebin, Abigail. ''Stars of David'', Broadway Books, NY, (2005)</ref>{{rp|25}} Until then, having become a filmmaker, he only felt his connection to Judaism when he visited his parents. He says he made the film partly to create \"something that would confirm my Judaism to my family and myself.\"<ref name=Loshitzky>Loshitzky, Yosefa. ''Spielberg's Holocaust: Critical Perspectives on \"Schindler's List\",'' Indiana Univ. Press (1997) p. 162</ref>\n\n{{quote|Kate is Protestant and she insisted on converting to Judaism. She spent a year studying, did the \"[[mikveh]],\" the whole thing. She chose to do a full conversion ''before'' we were married in 1991, and she married me after becoming a Jew. I think ''that'', more than anything else, brought me back to Judaism.<ref name=Pogrebin />{{rp|25}}}}\n\nHe credits her with fueling his family's current level of observance and for keeping the \"momentum flowing\" in their lives, as they now observe Jewish holidays, light candles on Friday nights, and give their children [[Bar and Bat Mitzvah]]s.<ref name=Pogrebin />{{rp|26}} \"This [[shiksa]] goddess has made me a better Jew than my own parents.\"<ref name=Pogrebin />{{rp|27}}\n\nProducing ''Schindler's List'' in 1993 also renewed his faith, Spielberg says, but \"it really was the fact that my wife took a profound interest in Judaism.\"<ref name=Pogrebin />{{rp|25}} He waited ten years after being given the story in 1982 to make the film, as he did not yet feel \"mature\" enough.<ref name=Pogrebin />{{rp|32}} He first wanted to have a family, \"to figure out what my place was in the world... . When my first son, [Max] was born, it greatly affected me... . A spirit began to ignite in me, and I became a Jewish dad...\"<ref name=McBride />{{rp|21}}\n\nHe said that making the film became a \"natural experience\" for him, adding, \"I ''had'' to tell the story. I've lived on its outer edges.\"<ref name=McBride /> The film, writes biographer [[Joseph McBride (writer)|Joseph McBride]], thereby became the \"culmination\" of Spielberg's long personal struggle with his Jewish identity.<ref name=McBride2>McBride, Joseph. ''Steven Spielberg: A Biography (3rd edition)</ref>{{rp|18}} Some claim the film has made Spielberg \"the one true heir to the great Jewish moguls who created Hollywood,\" most of whom had actively avoided depicting Jews or the Holocaust in their films.<ref name=Loshitzky />\n\n=== Wealth ===\n''[[Forbes]]'' magazine places Spielberg's personal net worth at $3.7 billion.<ref name=\"forbes1\" /> It was revealed in 2009 during the [[Madoff investment scandal|Madoff Ponzi scheme investigation]] that Spielberg and Capshaw were among the investors [[Ponzi scheme|defrauded]] by [[Bernard Madoff|Bernie Madoff]].\n\n=== Yachting ===\nIn 2013, Spielberg purchased the {{convert|282|ft|m|adj=on}} mega-yacht ''Seven Seas'' for US$182 million. He has since put it up for sale and in the meantime has made it available for charter. At US$1.2 million per month, it is one of the most expensive charters on the market. He has ordered a new {{convert|300|ft|m|adj=on}} yacht costing a reported US$250 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/this-184-million-yacht-isnt-enough-for-steven-spielberg-2015-8|title=Steven Spielberg is selling his $184 million mega-yacht because he needs a bigger boat|website=Businessinsider.com|accessdate=December 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Recognition ===\nIn 2002, Spielberg was one of eight flagbearers who carried the Olympic Flag into [[Rice-Eccles Stadium]] at the Opening Ceremonies of the [[2002 Winter Olympic Games]] in [[Salt Lake City]]. In 2006, ''[[Premiere (magazine)|Premiere]]'' listed him as the most powerful and influential figure in the [[film industry|motion picture industry]]. ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' listed him as one of the [[Time 100: The Most Important People of the Century|100 Most Important People of the Century]]. At the end of the 20th century, ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' named him the most influential person of his generation.<ref>{{cite web| title = The 50 most influential baby boomers: Top 10| work = Life| url = http://www.life.com/Life/boomers/50boomers01.html#05| accessdate =October 21, 2006|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20051223110753/http://www.life.com/Life/boomers/50boomers01.html#05|archivedate = December 23, 2005}}</ref> In 2009, [[Boston University]] presented him an honorary Doctor of Humane Letters degree.<ref>{{cite news|title=Honoring Steven Spielberg: Talking about old-school filmmaking, the virtues of TV, and the scent of film|url=http://www.bu.edu/today/2009/honoring-steven-spielberg/|accessdate=August 2, 2013|newspaper=BU Today|date=May 13, 2009}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''Forbes''{{'}} Most Influential Celebrities 2014 list, Spielberg was listed as the most influential celebrity in America. The annual list is conducted by E-Poll Market Research and it gave more than 6,600 celebrities on 46 different personality attributes a score representing \"how that person is perceived as influencing the public, their peers, or both.\" Spielberg received a score of 47, meaning 47% of the US believes he is influential. Gerry Philpott, president of E-Poll Market Research, supported Spielberg's score by stating, \"If anyone doubts that Steven Spielberg has greatly influenced the public, think about how many will think for a second before going into the water this summer.\"<ref name=\"Independent- Most influential\">{{cite news|last=Selby|first=Jenn|title=Steven Spielberg tops Forbes Most Influential Celebrities of 2014 list|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/news/steven-spielberg-tops-forbes-most-influential-celebrities-of-2014-list-9063685.html|accessdate=January 18, 2014|newspaper=The Independent|date=January 16, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Influential celebrities\">{{cite news|title=Forbes' Most Influential Celebrities 2014 List Led By Steven Spielberg, Naturally|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/16/forbes-most-influential-celebrities-2014_n_4611748.html|accessdate=January 18, 2014|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=January 16, 2014}}</ref><ref name=Pomerantz>{{cite news|last=Pomerantz|first=Dorothy|title=Steven Spielberg Tops Our List of the Most Influential Celebrities|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/dorothypomerantz/2014/01/15/steven-spielberg-tops-our-list-of-the-most-influential-celebrities/|accessdate=January 18, 2014|newspaper=Forbes|date=January 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Politics ===\nSpielberg has usually supported [[Democratic Party (United States)|U.S. Democratic Party]] candidates. He has donated over $800,000 to the Democratic party and its nominees. He has been a close friend of former President [[Bill Clinton]] and worked with the President for the USA Millennium celebrations. He directed an 18-minute film for the project, scored by [[John Williams]] and entitled ''The American Journey''. It was shown at America's Millennium Gala on December 31, 1999, in the [[National Mall]] at the [[Reflecting Pool]] at the base of the [[Lincoln Memorial]] in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{cite news|title = The Clintons' Showbiz Celebration|work=BBC News| date = January 1, 2000| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/586684.stm| accessdate =October 21, 2006}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Steven Spielberg 1999 2.jpg|thumb|right|Secretary of Defense [[William Cohen|William S. Cohen]] escorts Spielberg through a military honor cordon into the Pentagon.]] Spielberg resigned as a member of the national advisory board of the [[Boy Scouts of America]] in 2001 because of his disapproval of the organization's [[Boy Scouts of America membership controversies#Position on homosexuality|anti-homosexuality stance]].<ref>{{cite news|title = Spielberg quits scouts 'over gay ban'|work=BBC News| date = April 17, 2001|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/film/1281309.stm| accessdate =October 30, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywood.com/news/detail/id/386418|work= Hollywood.com|title=Spielberg resigns from Boy Scouts board|accessdate=March 10, 2006|date= April 26, 2001}}</ref> In 2007 the [[Arab League]] voted to boycott Spielberg's movies after he donated $1&nbsp;million for relief efforts in Israel during the [[2006 Lebanon War]].<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/news/international/spielberg-movies-banned-by-arab-league-wikileaks-cable-reveals-1.331251?localLinksEnabled=false \"Spielberg movies banned by Arab League, WikiLeaks cable reveals.\"] ''[[Haaretz]]'', December 18, 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title = Spielberg donates $US1m to Israeli relief|agency = Associated Press|date = August 10, 2006|accessdate =December 18, 2010|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/people/spielberg-directs-aid-to-israel/2006/08/10/1154803000553.html|newspaper=The Age|location=Melbourne}}</ref> On February 20, 2007, Spielberg, [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]], and [[David Geffen]] invited Democrats to a [[fundraiser]] for [[Barack Obama]].<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20070126/ap_en_ot/celebrities_obama_8 Obama excites entertainment community] By JOCELYN NOVECK, AP National Writer {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> In February 2008, Spielberg pulled out of his role as advisor to the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in response to the Chinese government's inaction over the [[War in Darfur]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Spielberg drops out as Beijing Olympics advisor|year=2008|work=Los Angeles Times|author=Rachel Abramowitz|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/movies/la-et-spielberg13feb13,1,7027646.story?ctrack=2&cset=true|accessdate=February 13, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080603215030/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/movies/la-et-spielberg13feb13%2C1%2C7027646.story?ctrack=2&cset=true|archivedate=June 3, 2008}}</ref> Spielberg said in a statement that \"''I find that my conscience will not allow me to continue business as usual''.\" It also said that \"''Sudan's government bears the bulk of the responsibility for these on-going crimes, but the international community, and particularly China, should be doing more.''.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Spielberg in Darfur snub to China|work=BBC News|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7242016.stm\n|accessdate=May 16, 2008|date=February 13, 2008}}</ref> The [[International Olympic Committee]] respected Spielberg's decision, but IOC president [[Jacques Rogge]] admitted in an interview that \"''[Spielberg] certainly would have brought a lot to the opening ceremony in terms of creativity.''\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Rogge respect for Spielberg move|work=BBC News|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympics/7247590.stm\n|accessdate=May 16, 2008|date=February 15, 2008}}</ref> Spielberg's statement drew criticism from Chinese officials and state-run media calling his criticism \"unfair\".<ref>{{cite news|title=China hits back over Olympics row|work=BBC News|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7254479.stm\n|accessdate=May 16, 2008|date=February 20, 2008|first=Michael|last=Bristow}}</ref> In September 2008, Spielberg and his wife offered their support to [[same-sex marriage]] by issuing a statement following their donation of $100,000 to the \"No on [[California Proposition 8 (2008)|Proposition 8]]\" campaign fund, a figure equal to the amount of money [[Brad Pitt]] donated to the same campaign less than a week prior.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.eonline.com/uberblog/b30446_Spielberg_Makes_Like_Pitt__Supports_Same_Sex_Marriage.html|title=Spielberg Makes Like Pitt, Supports Same-Sex Marriage \u2013 E! Online|publisher=Uk.eonline.com|date=September 23, 2008|accessdate=March 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\nSpielberg supported [[Hillary Clinton]] for President of the United States in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 election]]. He donated US$1 million to [[Priorities USA Action|Priorities USA]], a pro-Clinton Super PAC.<ref>{{cite news|date=May 27, 2016|title= The Top Donors Backing Hillary Clinton's Super PAC|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ivonaiacob/2016/05/27/top-donors-hillary-clinton-superpac/#259f3ea42740|newspaper=Forbes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Spielberg and his wife Kate Capshaw donated $500,000 to the [[March for Our Lives]] student demonstration in favor of gun control in the United States.<ref>{{cite news | url= https://edition.cnn.com/2018/02/20/entertainment/oprah-march-for-our-lives-donation/index.html | title= Oprah, Steven Spielberg also donating to March For Our Lives, following George Clooney's pledge | publisher=CNN | first=Sandra | last=Gonzalez | date=February 21, 2018 | accessdate=March 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Hobbies ===\nA collector of film memorabilia, Spielberg purchased a balsa Rosebud sled from ''[[Citizen Kane]]'' (1941) in 1982.<ref>{{cite news|date=June 13, 1982|title=Hidden Treasures: Prop Art|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/06/13/opinion/topics-hidden-treasures-prop-art.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=February 11, 2016}}</ref> He bought [[Orson Welles]]'s own directorial copy of the script for the radio broadcast ''[[The War of the Worlds (radio drama)|The War of the Worlds]]'' (1938) in 1994.<ref>[http://www.christies.com/lotfinder/lot/orson-welles-typescript-radioplay-the-war-of-2396734-details.aspx?from=salesummary&intObjectID=2396734&sid=4f5d0c65-d99a-478c-89aa-3dabd2d59f1a Sale 7565 / Lot 149], Orson Welles. Typescript radioplay ''The War of the Worlds''. [[Christie's]], June 2, 1994</ref> Spielberg has purchased Academy Award statuettes being sold on the open market and donated them to the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]], to prevent their further commercial exploitation. His donations include the Oscars that [[Bette Davis]] received for ''[[Dangerous (film)|Dangerous]]'' (1935) and ''[[Jezebel (1938 film)|Jezebel]]'' (1938), and [[Clark Gable]]'s Oscar for ''[[It Happened One Night]]'' (1934).<ref>{{cite news|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=December 21, 2002|title=Spielberg saves Bette Davis Oscar|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2002/dec/21/entertainment/et-quick21.4|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=February 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\nSpielberg is a major collector of the work of American illustrator and painter [[Norman Rockwell]]. A collection of 57 Rockwell paintings and drawings owned by Spielberg and fellow Rockwell collector and film director [[George Lucas]] were displayed at the [[Smithsonian American Art Museum]] July 2, 2010 \u2013 January 2, 2011, in an exhibition titled ''Telling Stories''.<ref name=\"Rockwell\">{{cite news|url=http://americanart.si.edu/exhibitions/archive/2010/rockwell/|title=Exhibitions: Telling Stories|author=Smithsonian American Art Museum|location=Washington, D.C.|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20130411052418/http://americanart.si.edu/exhibitions/archive/2010/rockwell/|archivedate=April 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\nSpielberg is an avid film buff and, when not shooting a picture, he will watch many films in a single weekend.<ref>{{cite video|title = [[Face to Face (British TV series)|Face to Face]]|publisher = [[BBC Two]]|date = January 31, 1994}}</ref> He sees almost every major summer blockbuster in theaters if not preoccupied and enjoys most of them.<ref>{{cite news|author=Ian Freer|title=Death from Above|work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]|date=August 2005|page=99|authorlink=Ian Freer}}</ref>\n\nSince playing ''[[Pong]]'' while filming ''[[Jaws (film)|Jaws]]'' in 1974, Spielberg has been an avid [[video gamer]]. Spielberg played many of [[LucasArts]] [[adventure game]]s, including the first ''Monkey Island'' games.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q6IYgWh-qnY&t=19m4s GameSpot, \"Storytime with Ron Gilbert \u2013 PAX Australia 2013 Keynote\"], ''Ron Gilbert'', July 7, 2013, accessed March 21, 2015</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qumYnE2wYhA&t=28m16s DoubleFineProd, \"Tim Schafer Plays Day of the Tentacle Part 1\"], ''Tim Schafer'', May 9, 2014, accessed March 22, 2015</ref> He owns a [[Wii]], a [[PlayStation 3]], a [[PlayStation Portable|PSP]], and an [[Xbox 360]], and enjoys playing [[first-person shooter]]s such as the ''[[Medal of Honor (video game series)|Medal of Honor]]'' series and ''[[Call of Duty 4: Modern Warfare]]''. He has also criticized the use of [[cutscene]]s in games, calling them intrusive, and feels making story flow naturally into the gameplay is a challenge for future game developers.<ref>{{cite news|author=Tom Chick|title=A Close Encounter with Steven Spielberg|publisher=Yahoo!|date=December 8, 2008|url=http://videogames.yahoo.com/celebrity-byte/steven-spielberg/1271249|accessdate=December 11, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211191412/http://videogames.yahoo.com/celebrity-byte/steven-spielberg/1271249|archivedate=December 11, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n=== Stalking ===\nIn 2001, Spielberg was [[stalking|stalked]] by [[Conspiracy theory|conspiracy theorist]] and former social worker [[Diana Napolis]]. She accused him, along with actress [[Jennifer Love Hewitt]], of controlling her thoughts through \"cybertronic\" technology and being part of a [[satanic ritual abuse|satanic conspiracy]] against her. Napolis was [[involuntary commitment|committed]] to a mental institution before pleading guilty to stalking, and released on probation with a condition that she have no contact with either Spielberg or Hewitt.<ref>{{cite news|title = Spielberg wins order banning cult stalker|work=The Australian|date = October 23, 2002|page = 12}}</ref><ref name=\"Sauer2002\">{{cite news|newspaper=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|last=Sauer|first=M|date=December 31, 2002|accessdate=October 30, 2008|title=Stalking suspect to undergo more psychological tests|url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/metro/20021231-9999_1m31stalker.html|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080906133859/http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/metro/20021231-9999_1m31stalker.html|archivedate=September 6, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"DeYoung\">{{cite book|author=De Young, Mary|title=The day care ritual abuse moral panic|publisher=McFarland|location=Jefferson, N.C.|year=2004|isbn=978-0-7864-1830-5| pages = [https://books.google.com/books?id=_e8ZkJBtz0EC&pg=PA234 234\u20135]}}</ref>\n\nJonathan Norman was arrested after making two attempts to enter Spielberg's [[Pacific Palisades, Los Angeles|Pacific Palisades]] home in June and July 1997. Norman was jailed for 25 years in California. Spielberg told the court: \"Had Jonathan Norman actually confronted me, I genuinely, in my heart of hearts, believe that I would have been raped or maimed or killed.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/114988.stm|title=Spielberg stalker jailed|date=June 17, 1998|work=BBC News|accessdate=December 11, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/SHOWBIZ/9802/26/spielberg.stalker/|title=Spielberg recounts fears, anguish over alleged stalker|last=Sylvester|first=Sherri|date=February 26, 1998|publisher=CNN|accessdate=December 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{{Main|Steven Spielberg filmography}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Distributor\n|-\n| 1968\n| ''[[Amblin']]'' (short film)\n| [[Filmways]]\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[Duel (1971 film)|Duel]]''\n| [[Universal Pictures]] / [[Cinema International Corporation|CIC]]\n|-\n| 1974\n| ''[[The Sugarland Express]]''\n|rowspan=2| Universal Pictures\n|-\n| 1975\n| ''[[Jaws (film)|Jaws]]''\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[Close Encounters of the Third Kind]]''\n| [[Columbia Pictures]]\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[1941 (film)|1941]]''\n| Universal Pictures / Columbia Pictures\n|-\n| 1981\n| ''[[Raiders of the Lost Ark]]''\n| [[Paramount Pictures]]\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]''\n| Universal Pictures\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[Twilight Zone: The Movie]]'' (one segment)\n| [[Warner Bros.]]\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom]]''\n| Paramount Pictures\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[The Color Purple (film)|The Color Purple]]''\n|rowspan=2| Warner Bros.\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Empire of the Sun (film)|Empire of the Sun]]''\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1989\n| ''[[Always (1989 film)|Always]]''\n| Universal Pictures / [[United Artists]]\n|-\n| ''[[Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade]]''\n| Paramount Pictures\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Hook (film)|Hook]]''\n| [[TriStar Pictures]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1993\n| ''[[Jurassic Park (film)|Jurassic Park]]''\n|rowspan=3| Universal Pictures\n|-\n| ''[[Schindler's List]]''\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1997\n| ''[[The Lost World: Jurassic Park]]''\n|-\n| ''[[Amistad (film)|Amistad]]''\n| [[DreamWorks Pictures]]\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Saving Private Ryan]]''\n| DreamWorks Pictures / Paramount Pictures\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[A.I. Artificial Intelligence]]''\n| Warner Bros. / DreamWorks Pictures\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2002\n| ''[[Minority Report (film)|Minority Report]]''\n| [[20th Century Fox]] / DreamWorks Pictures\n|-\n| ''[[Catch Me If You Can]]''\n|rowspan=2| DreamWorks Pictures\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[The Terminal]]''\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2005\n| ''[[War of the Worlds (2005)|War of the Worlds]]''\n| Paramount Pictures / DreamWorks Pictures\n|-\n| ''[[Munich (film)|Munich]]''\n| Universal Pictures / DreamWorks Pictures\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Indiana Jones and the Kingdom of the Crystal Skull]]''\n| Paramount Pictures\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2011\n| ''[[The Adventures of Tintin (film)|The Adventures of Tintin]]''\n| Paramount Pictures / Columbia Pictures\n|-\n| ''[[War Horse (film)|War Horse]]''\n| [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Walt Disney Studios]]\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Lincoln (film)|Lincoln]]''\n|rowspan=2| Walt Disney Studios / 20th Century Fox\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Bridge of Spies (film)|Bridge of Spies]]''\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[The BFG (2016 film)|The BFG]]''\n| Walt Disney Studios\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[The Post (film)|The Post]]''\n| 20th Century Fox\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Ready Player One (film)|Ready Player One]]''\n| Warner Bros.\n|-\n|2020\n| ''[[West Side Story (2020 film)|West Side Story]]''\n| [[20th Century Studios]]\n|}\n\n== Awards and honors ==\n{{See also|List of awards and nominations received by Steven Spielberg}}\n[[File:Steven Spielberg 1999 4 crop.jpg|thumb|right|Spielberg receiving a public service award presented by United States Secretary of Defense [[William Cohen]], 1999]]\n[[File:Steven Spielberg - Walk of Fame.jpg|thumb|right|Steven Spielberg's star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame]]\n\n[[File:SpielbergGraumansChinese.jpg|thumb|Footprints and handprints of Steven Spielberg in front of the [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre]]]]\n\n[[File:2009libertymedal.JPG|thumb|left|Former President Clinton with Spielberg as he accepts the 2009 Liberty Award in [[Philadelphia]]]]\n\nSpielberg has won three Academy Awards. He has been nominated for seven Academy Awards for the category of [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]], winning two of them (''[[Schindler's List]]'' and ''[[Saving Private Ryan]]''), and ten of the films he directed were up for the [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] Oscar (''Schindler's List'' won). In 1987, he was awarded the [[Irving G. Thalberg Memorial Award]] for his work as a creative producer.\n\nDrawing from his own experiences in [[Scouting]], Spielberg helped the [[Boy Scouts of America]] develop a merit badge in cinematography in order to help promote filmmaking as a marketable skill. The badge was launched at the 1989 [[National Scout jamboree (Boy Scouts of America)|National Scout Jamboree]], which Spielberg attended, and where he personally counseled many boys in their work on requirements.<ref>''Boys' Life, September 1989''</ref>\nThat same year, 1989, saw the release of ''Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade''. The opening scene shows a teenage Indiana Jones in [[Uniform and insignia of the Boy Scouts of America|scout uniform]] bearing the rank of a [[Life Scout]]. Spielberg stated he made Indiana Jones a Boy Scout in honor of his experience in Scouting. For his career accomplishments, service to others, and dedication to a new merit badge Spielberg was awarded the [[Distinguished Eagle Scout Award]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Distinguished Eagle Scout Award|publisher=National Capital Area Council&nbsp;\u2013 Boy Scouts of America|url=http://www.boyscouts-ncac.org/pages/6207_distinguished_eagle_scout_award.cfm|accessdate=October 21, 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061005110513/https://www.boyscouts-ncac.org/pages/6207_distinguished_eagle_scout_award.cfm|archivedate=October 5, 2006}}</ref>\n\nSteven Spielberg received the [[AFI Life Achievement Award]] in 1995.\n\nIn 1998, he was awarded the [[Federal Cross of Merit]] with Ribbon of the Federal Republic of Germany. The Award was presented to him by President [[Roman Herzog]] in recognition of his film ''Schindler's List'' and his Shoa-Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|title = Steven Spielberg erh\u00e4lt das Bundesverdienstkreuz|publisher = Berlin Online|date = September 11, 1998|url = http://www.berlinonline.de/berliner-zeitung/archiv/.bin/dump.fcgi/1998/0911/seite1/0064/index.html|accessdate = December 19, 2008|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20091019070726/http://www.berlinonline.de/berliner-zeitung/archiv/.bin/dump.fcgi/1998/0911/seite1/0064/index.html|archive-date = October 19, 2009|url-status=dead|df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, Spielberg received an honorary degree from [[Brown University]]. Spielberg was also awarded the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] [[Awards and decorations of the United States government#Department of Defense|Medal for Distinguished Public Service]] by Secretary of Defense [[William Cohen]] at [[the Pentagon]] on August 11, 1999; Cohen presented the award in recognition of Spielberg's film ''Saving Private Ryan''.\n\nIn 2001, he was appointed as an [[List of honorary British knights and dames|honorary Knight Commander]] of the [[Order of the British Empire]] (KBE) by [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] for services to the entertainment industry of the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite news|title = Spielberg receives Royal honour|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1142446.stm|work=BBC News|date = January 30, 2001}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, he was admitted as [[knight]] of the [[L\u00e9gion d'honneur]] by president [[Jacques Chirac]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Le Pr\u00e9sident de la R\u00e9publique remet les insignes de chevalier de la L\u00e9gion d'Honneur \u00e0 M. Steven Spielberg|publisher=Palais de l'\u00c9lys\u00e9e|date=September 5, 2004|language=French|url=http://www.elysee.fr/elysee/elysee.fr/francais_archives/actualites/a_l_elysee/2004/septembre/popup/steven_spielberg_legion_d_honneur-photo_1-5.22276.html|accessdate=September 29, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071206131550/https://www.elysee.fr/elysee/elysee.fr/francais_archives/actualites/a_l_elysee/2004/septembre/popup/steven_spielberg_legion_d_honneur-photo_1-5.22276.html|archivedate=December 6, 2007}}</ref> On July 15, 2006, Spielberg was also awarded the [[Chicago International Film Festival#Grand Prize: Gold Hugo|Gold Hugo Lifetime Achievement Award]] at the Summer Gala of the [[Chicago International Film Festival]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Spielberg receives Lifetime Achievement Award|publisher=Chicago Film Festival|date=July 17, 2006|url=http://www.chicagofilmfestival.org/cgi-bin/WebObjects/CIFFSite.woa/wa/pages/SummerGala06|accessdate=October 21, 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061016164659/http://www.chicagofilmfestival.org/cgi-bin/WebObjects/CIFFSite.woa/wa/pages/SummerGala06|archivedate=October 16, 2006 }}</ref> and also was awarded a [[Kennedy Center]] honour on December 3. The tribute to Spielberg featured a short, filmed biography narrated by [[Liam Neeson]] and included thank-yous from World War II veterans for ''Saving Private Ryan'', as well as a performance of the finale to [[Leonard Bernstein]]'s ''Candide'', conducted by [[John Williams]] (Spielberg's frequent composer).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2006-12-26-0612260070-story.html|title=`Kennedy Center Honors' hits mostly high notes|last=Sentinel|first=Hal Boedeker, Tribune newspapers: Orlando|website=chicagotribune.com|language=en-US|access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Science Fiction and Fantasy Hall of Fame|Science Fiction Hall of Fame]] inducted Spielberg in 2005, the first year it considered non-literary contributors.<ref name=sfhof2005>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfhomeworld.org/make_contact/article.asp?articleID=206|archive-url=https://archive.today/20050326222649/http://www.sfhomeworld.org/make_contact/article.asp?articleID=206|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 26, 2005|title=It's Official! Inductees Named for 2005 Hall of Fame Class|accessdate=March 26, 2005 }}. Press release March 24, 2005. Science Fiction Museum (''sfhomeworld.org''). Archived March 26, 2005. Retrieved March 22, 2013.</ref><ref name=sfhof-old>[http://www.midamericon.org/halloffame/ \"Science Fiction and Fantasy Hall of Fame\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130521070009/http://www.midamericon.org/halloffame/|date=May 21, 2013 }}. Mid American Science Fiction and Fantasy Conventions, Inc. Retrieved April 7, 2013. This was the official website of the hall of fame to 2004.</ref> In November 2007, he was chosen for a [[Lifetime Achievement Award]] to be presented at the sixth annual [[Visual Effects Society Awards]] in February 2009. He was set to be honored with the [[Cecil B. DeMille Award]] at the January 2008 [[Golden Globes]]; however, due to the new, watered-down format of the ceremony resulting from conflicts in the [[2007\u20132008 Writers Guild of America strike|2007\u201308 writers strike]], the HFPA postponed his honor to the 2009 ceremony.<ref>{{cite news|title = Spielberg to Receive Cecil B. DeMille Award|publisher = ComingSoon.net|date = November 14, 2007|url = https://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=39311|accessdate=November 14, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7179401.stm|title = Spielberg Globe honour 'deferred'|work=BBC News|date = January 9, 2008}}</ref> In 2008, Spielberg was awarded the [[L\u00e9gion d'honneur]].<ref>{{cite news|title=French honour for Steven Spielberg|publisher=[[Press Association]]|date=May 21, 2008|url=http://ukpress.google.com/article/ALeqM5jS1sYgmE95AtZeoVHxjt38GsqF1A|accessdate=May 22, 2008 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2008, Spielberg received [[Arizona State University]]'s Hugh Downs Award for Communication Excellence.<ref>[http://newswise.com/articles/view/541939/Steven Spielberg Receives Arizona State University Communication Award] Newswise. Retrieved June 22, 2008.</ref>\n\nSpielberg received an honorary degree at [[Boston University]]'s 136th Annual Commencement on May 17, 2009. In October 2009 Steven Spielberg received the [[Philadelphia Liberty Medal]]; presenting him with the medal was former US president and Liberty Medal recipient Bill Clinton. Special guests included [[Whoopi Goldberg]], Pennsylvania Governor [[Ed Rendell]] and Philadelphia Mayor [[Michael Nutter]].\n\nOn October 22, 2011 he was admitted as a Commander of the Belgian [[Order of the Crown (Belgium)|Order of the Crown]]. He was given the badge on a red neck ribbon by the Belgian Federal Minister of Finance [[Didier Reynders]]. The Commander is the third highest rank of the Order of the Crown. He was the president of the jury for the [[2013 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=\"SpielbergCannes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-21612509|title=Steven Spielberg to head up Cannes Film Festival jury|accessdate=February 28, 2013|newspaper=BBC News|date=February 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn November 19, 2013, Spielberg was honored by the [[National Archives and Records Administration]] with its Records of Achievement Award. Spielberg was given two facsimiles of the [[13th Amendment to the United States Constitution]], one passed but not ratified in 1861, as well as a facsimile of the actual 1865 amendment signed into law by President [[Abraham Lincoln]]. The amendment and the process of passing it were the subject of his film ''[[Lincoln (film)|Lincoln]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2013/biz/news/steven-spielberg-honored-by-national-archives-1200861205|title=Spielberg Honored by National Archives \u2013 Variety|author=Ted Johnson|work=Variety|date=November 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn November 24, 2015, Spielberg was awarded the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] from [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] in a ceremony at the [[White House]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2015/11/16/president-obama-names-recipients-presidential-medal-freedom|title=President Obama Names Recipients of the Presidential Medal of Freedom| accessdate=November 16, 2015|date=November 16, 2015|work=The White House}}</ref>\n\nOn May 26, 2016, Spielberg was awarded an Honorary Doctor of Arts by [[Harvard University]].\n\nIn July 2016, Spielberg was awarded a gold [[Blue Peter badge]] on the BBC children's television programme ''[[Blue Peter]]''.<ref>Burns, Catherine (July 22, 2016) [http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/36865145/steven-spielberg-has-just-won-at-life-hes-got-a-gold-blue-peter-badge Steven Spielberg has just won at life. He's got a Gold Blue Peter badge] [[BBC]] [[Newsbeat]] website</ref>\n\n===Awards received by Spielberg films===\n<!--Table is for nominations & wins received only by films directed by Spielberg. DO NOT INCLUDE MOVIES THAT WEREN'T DIRECTED BY HIM-->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Film\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Academy Awards\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| BAFTA Awards\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Golden Globe Awards\n|-\n! Nominations\n! Wins\n! Nominations\n! Wins\n! Nominations\n! Wins\n|-\n| 1975\n| ''[[Jaws (film)|Jaws]]''\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|3\n|align=center|7\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|1\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[Close Encounters of the Third Kind]]''\n|align=center|9\n|align=center|2\n|align=center|9\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|4\n|\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[1941 (film)|1941]]''\n|align=center|3\n|\n|\n|\n|align=center|5\n|\n|-\n| 1981\n| ''[[Raiders of the Lost Ark]]''\n|align=center|9\n|align=center|5\n|align=center|7\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|1\n|\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]''\n|align=center|9\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|12\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|5\n|align=center|2\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom]]''\n|align=center|2\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|1\n|\n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[The Color Purple (film)|The Color Purple]]''\n|align=center|11\n|\n|align=center|1\n|\n|align=center|5\n|align=center|1\n|-\n| 1987\n|''[[Empire of the Sun (film)|Empire of the Sun]]''\n|align=center|6\n|\n|align=center|6\n|align=center|3\n|align=center|2\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade]]''\n|align=center|3\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|3\n|\n|align=center|1\n|\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Hook (film)|Hook]]''\n|align=center|5\n|\n|\n|\n|align=center|1\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1993\n| ''[[Jurassic Park]]''\n|align=center|3\n|align=center|3\n|align=center|3\n|align=center|2\n|\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Schindler's List]]''\n|align=center|12\n|align=center|7\n|align=center|13\n|align=center|7\n|align=center|6\n|align=center|3\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1997\n| ''[[The Lost World: Jurassic Park]]''\n|align=center|1\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|''[[Amistad (film)|Amistad]]''\n|align=center|4\n|\n|\n|\n|align=center|4\n|\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Saving Private Ryan]]''\n|align=center|11\n|align=center|5\n|align=center|10\n|align=center|2\n|align=center|5\n|align=center|2\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[A.I. Artificial Intelligence]]''\n|align=center|2\n|\n|align=center|1\n|\n|align=center|3\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2002\n| ''[[Minority Report (film)|Minority Report]]''\n|align=center|1\n|\n|align=center|1\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Catch Me If You Can]]''\n|align=center|2\n|\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|1\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2005\n| ''[[War of the Worlds (2005 film)|War of the Worlds]]''\n|align=center|3\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Munich (film)|Munich]]''\n|align=center|5\n|\n|\n|\n|align=center|2\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Indiana Jones and the Kingdom of the Crystal Skull]]''\n|\n|\n|align=center|1\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2011\n| ''[[The Adventures of Tintin (film)|The Adventures of Tintin]]''\n|align=center|1\n|\n|align=center|2\n|\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|1\n|-\n| ''[[War Horse (film)|War Horse]]''\n|align=center|6\n|\n|align=center|5\n|\n|align=center|2\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Lincoln (film)|Lincoln]]''\n|align=center|12\n|align=center|2\n|align=center|10\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|7\n|align=center|1\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Bridge of Spies (film)|Bridge of Spies]]''\n|align=center|6\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|9\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|1\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[The BFG (2016 film)|The BFG]]''\n|\n|\n|align=center|1\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[The Post (film)|The Post]]''\n|align=center|2\n|\n|\n|\n|align=center|6\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Ready Player One (film)|Ready Player One]]''\n|align=center|1\n|\n|align=center|1\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|'''Total'''\n!align=center|130\n!align=center|34\n!align=center|110\n!align=center|22\n!align=center|66\n!align=center|11\n|}\n\n===Directed Academy Award Performances===\nSpielberg has directed fourteen Oscar winning and nominated performances.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Performer\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Film\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Result\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''[[Academy Award for Best Actor]]'''\n|-\n| [[66th Academy Awards|1993]]\n| [[Liam Neeson]]\n| ''[[Schindler's List (film)|Schindler's List]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[71st Academy Awards|1998]]\n| [[Tom Hanks]]\n| ''[[Saving Private Ryan]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[85th Academy Awards|2012]]\n| [[Daniel Day-Lewis]]\n| ''[[Lincoln (film)|Lincoln]]''\n| {{win}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''[[Academy Award for Best Actress]]'''\n|-\n| [[58th Academy Awards|1986]]\n| [[Whoopi Goldberg]]\n| ''[[The Color Purple (film)|The Color Purple]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[90th Academy Awards|2017]]\n| [[Meryl Streep]]\n| ''[[The Post (film)|The Post]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''[[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]]'''\n|-\n| [[66th Academy Awards|1993]]\n| [[Ralph Fiennes]]\n| ''[[Schindler's List (film)|Schindler's List]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[70th Academy Awards|1997]]\n| [[Anthony Hopkins]]\n| ''[[Amistad (film)|Amistad]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[75th Academy Awards|2002]]\n| [[Christopher Walken]]\n| ''[[Catch Me If You Can]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[85th Academy Awards|2012]]\n| [[Tommy Lee Jones]]\n| ''[[Lincoln (film)|Lincoln]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[88th Academy Awards|2015]]\n| [[Mark Rylance]]\n| ''[[Bridge of Spies (film)|Bridge of Spies]]''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''[[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]]'''\n|-\n| [[50th Academy Awards|1977]]\n| [[Melinda Dillon]]\n| ''[[Close Encounters of the Third Kind]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| [[58th Academy Awards|1986]]\n| [[Margaret Avery]]\n|rowspan=2| ''[[The Color Purple (film)|The Color Purple]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Oprah Winfrey]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[85th Academy Awards|2012]]\n| [[Sally Field]]\n| ''[[Lincoln (film)|Lincoln]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n== Praise and criticism ==\n*In 2005, Steven Spielberg was rated the greatest film director of all time by [[Empire (magazine)|''Empire'' magazine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmsite.org/directors5.html|title=Film Site-AMC.com|publisher=Filmsite.org|date=April 19, 1996|accessdate=January 31, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140331180201/http://www.filmsite.org/directors5.html|archivedate=March 31, 2014}}</ref> In 1997, a [[Wall Street]] [[sell-side analyst]] said, \"There are only two brand names in the business: [[Disney]] and Spielberg\".<ref name=\"fabrikant19970120\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/01/20/business/despite-a-sluggish-beginning-dreamworks-is-viewed-as-a-potential-hollywood-power.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm| title=Despite a Sluggish Beginning, Dreamworks Is Viewed as a Potential Hollywood Power| work=The New York Times| date=January 20, 1997| accessdate=July 20, 2012| author=Fabrikant, Geraldine}}</ref>\n*After watching the unconventional, off-center camera techniques of ''[[Jaws (film)|Jaws]]'', [[Alfred Hitchcock]] praised \"young Spielberg,\" for thinking outside of the visual dynamics of the theater, saying \"He's the first one of us who doesn't see the [[proscenium]] arch\".<ref name=McBride /><ref>{{cite magazine|first=Owen|last=Gleiberman|url=https://ew.com/article/2007/08/01/bourne-ultimatum-2/|title=''The Bourne Ultimatum''|website=Entertainment Weekly|date=August 1, 2007|accessdate=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n*Some of Spielberg's admirers include [[Robert Aldrich]],<ref>{{cite book| title = Robert Aldrich: interviews| url = https://books.google.com/?id=d2gm0LW617UC&pg=PA172| isbn = 978-1-57806-602-5| author1 = Aldrich, Robert| author2 = Arnold, Edwin T| author3 = Miller, Eugene L| year = 2004}}</ref> [[Ingmar Bergman]],<ref>{{cite web|title=N\u00e4r Bergman g\u00e5r p\u00e5 bio|url=http://sydsvenskan.se/nojen/article255225.ece|accessdate=August 27, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071204010344/http://sydsvenskan.se/nojen/article255225.ece|archivedate=December 4, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Werner Herzog]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/interview_strong_man_on_a_mission_werner_herzog_talks_about_invincible/|title=INTERVIEW: Strong Man on a Mission; Werner Herzog Talks About 'Invincible'|publisher=indieWIRE|date=September 23, 2002|accessdate=January 31, 2011}}</ref> [[Stanley Kubrick]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/janharlaninterview.html|title=On Kubrick \u2013 A Talk With Kubrick Documentarian Jan Harlan|publisher=Dvdtalk.com|accessdate=January 31, 2011}}</ref> [[David Lean]],<ref>{{cite book| title = David Lean Interviews| url = https://books.google.com/?id=kzVEXi4Plw0C&printsec=frontcover| isbn = 978-1-60473-235-1| author1 = Organ, Steven| year = 2009}}</ref> [[Sidney Lumet]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehollywoodinterview.blogspot.com/2008/01/sidney-lumet-hollywood-interview.html|title=The Hollywood Interview: Sidney Lumet|publisher=Thehollywoodinterview.blogspot.com|date=January 7, 2008|accessdate=January 31, 2011}}</ref> [[Roman Polanski]],<ref>{{Cite book| url = https://books.google.com/?id=Pckg8k3g-PkC&pg=PA167&lpg=PA167&dq=%22that+film+challenged+some+of+my+preconceptions%22#v=onepage&q=%22that%20film%20challenged%20some%20of%20my%20preconceptions%22&f=false| title = Roman Polanski: Interviews| isbn = 978-1-57806-799-2| last1 = Polanski| first1 = Roman| last2 = Cronin| first2 = Paul| date = October 2005}}</ref> [[Martin Scorsese]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NV8k4tNCB6k|title=Golden Globes 2009: Steven Spielberg Cecil B. DeMille Award|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=January 31, 2011}}</ref> [[Fran\u00e7ois Truffaut]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Stephen Rowley|url=http://home.mira.net/~satadaca/genre2.htm|title=Genre, Auteurism, and Spielberg|publisher=Home.mira.net|accessdate=January 31, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110504134502/https://home.mira.net/~satadaca/genre2.htm|archivedate=May 4, 2011}}</ref> [[David Lynch]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.davidlynch.de/nmelynch.html|title=David Lynch interview New Musical Express, 21st August, 1982|publisher=Davidlynch.de|date=August 21, 1982|accessdate=May 25, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313210031/http://www.davidlynch.de/nmelynch.html|archivedate=March 13, 2012}}</ref> and [[Zhang Yimou]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.henan.china.cn/english/features/film/165749.htm|title=Zhang Yimou, Spielberg to Join Hands for Olympic Ceremonies|publisher=Henan.china.cn|accessdate=January 31, 2011 }}{{dead link|date=April 2017|bot=Elisfkc|fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*Spielberg's movies have also influenced many directors that followed, including [[Adam Green (filmmaker)|Adam Green]], [[J. J. Abrams]],<ref>[https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/article/five-favourite-films-with-j-j-abrams/ Five Favorite Films with J.J. Abrams]. Rotten Tomatoes. Retrieved June 21, 2011.</ref> [[Paul Thomas Anderson]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=yJn4PKjxIcUC&pg=PA74&lpg=PA74&dq=%22paul+thomas+anderson%22+%22close+encounters%22#v=onepage&q=%22paul%20thomas%20anderson%22%20%22close%20encounters%22&f=false|title=Useless Beauty: Ecclesiastes Through The Lens Of Contemporary Film \u2013 Robert K. Johnston|accessdate=May 25, 2012|isbn=978-0-8010-2785-7|date=November 1, 2004|last1=Johnston|first1=Robert K.}}</ref> [[Neill Blomkamp]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scifimoviepage.com/upcoming/previews/district9-sequel.html|title=District 9 (2009) \u2013 Neill Blomkamp Interview|publisher=Sci-Fi Movie Page|date=August 18, 2009|accessdate=January 31, 2011}}</ref> [[James Cameron]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://marketsaw.blogspot.com/2010/08/exclusive-james-cameron-interview-talks.html|title=James Cameron Interview! Talks AVATAR Re-release, Sequels, 3D Conversions & Working With Del Toro!|publisher=Marketsaw.blogspot.com|date=August 7, 2010|accessdate=January 31, 2011}}</ref> [[Guillermo del Toro]],<ref>http://www.deltorofilms.com/GDT_Favorites.php {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100209181157/http://www.deltorofilms.com/GDT_Favorites.php|date=February 9, 2010 }}</ref> [[Roland Emmerich]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/2012/news/1854593/five-favorite-films-with-roland-emmerich/|title=Five Favorite Films with Roland Emmerich|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=January 31, 2011}}</ref> [[David Fincher]], [[Peter Jackson]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1189344-lovely_bones/news/1861930/five_favorite_films_with_peter_jackson/|title=Five Favorite Films With Peter Jackson|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=January 31, 2011}}</ref> Kal Ng,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.sensesofcinema.com/contents/00/10/ng.html|title=Interview with Kal Ng|publisher=Archive.sensesofcinema.com|accessdate=January 31, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101225150706/https://archive.sensesofcinema.com/contents/00/10/ng.html|archivedate=December 25, 2010}}</ref> [[Robert Rodriguez]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/comic_con_2009/news/1834188/five_favorite_films_with_robert_rodriguez/|title=Five Favorite Films with Robert Rodriguez|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=January 31, 2011}}</ref> [[John Sayles]],<ref>{{cite book| title = John Sayles: interviews| url = https://books.google.com/?id=0cGjdRbHCyYC&printsec=frontcover| isbn = 978-1-57806-138-9| author1 = Sayles, John| author2 = Carson, Diane| year = 1999}}</ref> [[Ridley Scott]],<ref>{{cite book| title = Ridley Scott: interviews|url = https://books.google.com/?id=kpF6yekYJeEC&printsec=frontcover| isbn = 978-1-57806-726-8| author1 = Scott, Ridley| author2 = Knapp, Laurence F| author3 = Kulas, Andrea F| date = February 2005}}</ref> [[John Singleton]],<ref>{{cite book| title = John Singleton: interviews|url = https://books.google.com/?id=nrTB2Uf7kEIC&printsec=frontcover| isbn = 978-1-60473-116-3| author1 = Barboza, Craigh| date = January 2009}}</ref> [[Kevin Smith]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1190296-zack_and_miri_make_a_porno/news/1776943/five_favorite_films_with_kevin_smith/|title=Five Favorite Films with Kevin Smith|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=January 31, 2011}}</ref> [[Steven Soderbergh]], [[Quentin Tarantino]],<ref>{{cite book| title = Quentin Tarantino: interviews|url = https://books.google.com/?id=c5SdiFJmswcC&printsec=frontcover| isbn = 978-1-57806-051-1| author1 = Tarantino, Quentin| author2 = Peary, Gerald| year = 1998}}</ref> and [[Gareth Edwards (director)|Gareth Edwards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/watch-gareth-edwards-names-3-filmmaking-heroes-plus-new-godzilla-featurette-goes-behind-the-scenes-20140501|title=Watch: Gareth Edwards Names His 3 Filmmaking Heroes Plus \u2013 The Playlist|author=Kevin Jagernauth|date=May 1, 2014|work=The Playlist|access-date=May 4, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505070200/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/watch-gareth-edwards-names-3-filmmaking-heroes-plus-new-godzilla-featurette-goes-behind-the-scenes-20140501|archive-date=May 5, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2016, [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]] said of Spielberg: \"You can take James Cameron, [[Christopher Nolan|Chris Nolan]] or Martin Scorsese \u2013 all brilliant and in many ways his peers, but look at quality and consistency, and no one compares.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/steven-spielberg-dreamworks-past-amblins-902544|title=Steven Spielberg on DreamWorks' Past, Amblin's Present and His Own Future|author=Kim Masters|date=June 15, 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n*British film critic [[Tom Shone]] has said of Spielberg, \"If you have to point to any one director of the last twenty-five years in whose work the medium of film was most fully itself \u2013 where we found out what it does best when left to its own devices, it has to be that guy.\"<ref>Shone, Tom. [https://books.google.com/books?id=_HMOHsjIb5cC&pg=PA80 ''Blockbuster: how Hollywood learned to stop worrying and love the summer'']. p. 80. Simon and Schuster, 2004. {{ISBN|0-7432-3568-1}}.</ref> Jess Cagle, the managing editor of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', called Spielberg \"...arguably (well, who would argue?) the greatest filmmaker in history.\"<ref>\"Spielberg and You\" \u2013 Entertainment Weekly. Pg. 6. 12/9/11.</ref>\n*Spielberg's critics complain that his films are overly sentimental and tritely moralistic.<ref>{{cite magazine|title = A.I. Artificial Intelligence|author = Glenn Heath, Jr.|url = https://www.slantmagazine.com/dvd/review/a-i-artificial-intelligence/1985|date = April 14, 2011|magazine=Slant Magazine|accessdate=May 1, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=A.I.: Artificial Intelligence|author=Thorsen, Tor|url=http://www.reel.com/movie.asp?MID=131724&Tab=reviews&CID=13|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080210071037/http://www.reel.com/movie.asp?MID=131724&Tab=reviews&CID=13|archivedate=February 10, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Rowley\">{{cite web|title=Steven Spielberg on Senses of Cinema|author=Rowley, Stephen|url=http://www.sensesofcinema.com/2006/great-directors/spielberg/|accessdate=March 16, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080305063853/http://www.sensesofcinema.com/contents/directors/06/spielberg.html|archivedate=March 5, 2008|url-status=live |date=February 6, 2006}}</ref> In his book ''[[Easy Riders, Raging Bulls]]'', [[Peter Biskind]] summarized the views of Spielberg's detractors, accusing the director of \"infantilizing the audience, reconstituting the spectator as child, then overwhelming him and her with sound and spectacle, obliterating irony, aesthetic self-consciousness, and critical reflection.\"<ref>''[[Easy Riders, Raging Bulls]]: How the Sex 'n' Drugs 'n' Rock 'n' Roll Generation Saved Hollywood'' by [[Peter Biskind]], Bloomsbury, London, 1999, pp. 343\u2013344.</ref>\n*Critics of mainstream film such as [[Ray Carney]] and American artist and actor [[Crispin Glover]] (who starred in the Spielberg-produced ''[[Back to the Future]]'' and who sued Spielberg for using his likeness in ''[[Back to the Future Part II]]'')<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/columnist/popcandy/2002-08-07-candy.htm|title= The amazingly true tales of Crispin Glover|publisher=Pop Candy|author=Whitney Matheson|work=USA Today|date= August 7, 2002|accessdate=March 8, 2011}}</ref> claim that Spielberg's films lack depth and do not take risks.<ref>{{cite web|title = There's no Business like Show Business|author = Carney, Ray|url = http://people.bu.edu/rcarney/carncult/showbiz.shtml|accessdate =March 16, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| last = Glover| first = Crispin| authorlink = Crispin Glover| title = What Is It?| url = http://thecrispincorner.com/essay.html| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060503191918/http://thecrispincorner.com/essay.html| archivedate = May 3, 2006| accessdate =September 1, 2007}}</ref>\n*[[French New Wave]] filmmaker [[Jean-Luc Godard]] stated that he holds Spielberg partly responsible for the lack of artistic merit in mainstream cinema and accused Spielberg of using his film ''[[Schindler's List]]'' to make a profit off tragedy while Schindler's wife, [[Emilie Schindler]], lived in poverty in Argentina.<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Bill|last=Gibron|title=Short Cuts&nbsp;\u2013 Forgotten Gems: In Praise of Love|magazine=Pop Matters|date=April 21, 2007|url=https://www.popmatters.com/pm/blogs/shortends_post/33421/short-cuts-forgotten-gems-in-praise-of-love-2001|accessdate=April 28, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070424103927/http://www.popmatters.com/pm/blogs/shortends_post/33421/short-cuts-forgotten-gems-in-praise-of-love-2001|archivedate=April 24, 2007 }}</ref> In defense of Spielberg, critic [[Roger Ebert]] said \"Has Godard or any other director living or dead done more than Spielberg, with his Holocaust Project, to honor and preserve the memories of the survivors?\"<ref>{{cite news|author = Roger Ebert|title = In Praise of Love|work=Chicago Sun-Times|date = October 18, 2002|url = http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20021018/REVIEWS/210180306/1023|accessdate=April 28, 2007|authorlink = Roger Ebert}}</ref> Author [[Thomas Keneally]] has also disputed claims that Emilie Schindler was never paid for her contributions to the film, \"not least because I had recently sent Emilie a check myself.\"<ref>{{Cite book| url = https://books.google.com/?id=vg1Gw6VSK98C&pg=PA265&lpg=PA265&dq=%22searching+for+schindler%22+%22not+a+penny%22#v=onepage&q&f=false| title = Searching for Schindler: A Memoir| isbn = 978-0-385-52617-3| last1 = Keneally| first1 = Thomas| year = 2007}}</ref>\n*Film critic [[Pauline Kael]], who had championed Spielberg's films in the 1970s, expressed disappointment in his later development, stating that \"he's become, I think, a very bad director.... And I'm a little ashamed for him, because I loved his early work.... [H]e turned to virtuous movies. And he's become so uninteresting now.... I think that he had it in him to become more of a fluid, far-out director. But, instead, he's become a melodramatist.\"<ref>''[[Afterglow: A Last Conversation with Pauline Kael]]'' by [[Francis Davis]], [[Da Capo Press]], 2003, p. 50.</ref>\n*[[Imre Kert\u00e9sz]], Hungarian Jewish author, [[Nazi concentration camps|Nazi concentration camp]] survivor, and winner of the [[Nobel Prize in Literature]], criticized Spielberg's depiction of the Holocaust in ''Schindler's List'' as [[kitsch]], saying \"I regard as kitsch any representation of the Holocaust that is incapable of understanding or unwilling to understand the organic connection between our own deformed mode of life and the very possibility of the Holocaust.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.english.illinois.edu/maps/holocaust/reflections.htm|title=Holocaust Reflections|publisher=English.illinois.edu|accessdate=January 31, 2011}}</ref> Veteran documentary filmmaker and professor [[Claude Lanzmann]] also labeled ''Schindler's List'' \"pernicious in its impact and influence\" and \"very sentimental\".<ref>''[[The New York Times]]'', December 6, 2010 [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/07/movies/07shoah.html?_r=1&pagewanted=all Maker of 'Shoah' Stresses Its Lasting Value]</ref>\n*Stephen Rowley wrote an extensive essay about Spielberg and his career in ''[[Senses of Cinema]]''. In it, he discussed Spielberg's strengths as a filmmaker, saying \"there is a welcome complexity of tone and approach in these later films that defies the lazy stereotypes often bandied about his films\" and that \"Spielberg continues to take risks, with his body of work continuing to grow more impressive and ambitious\", concluding that he has only received \"limited, begrudging recognition\" from critics.<ref name=\"Rowley\" />\n*[[Shia LaBeouf]], who worked with Spielberg on a number of films including ''[[Indiana Jones and the Kingdom of the Crystal Skull]]'' and various [[DreamWorks Pictures|DreamWorks]] productions (such as the [[Transformers (film series)|''Transformers'' film series]]), described his experiences working with the director in a wide-ranging interview with ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' in 2016. He stated, \"I grew up with this idea, [that] if you got to Spielberg, that's where it is \u2013 I'm not talking about fame, and I'm not talking about money. You get there, and you realize you're not meeting the Spielberg you dream of. You're meeting a different Spielberg, who is in a different stage in his career. He's less a director than he is a fucking company.\" He went on to discuss his on-set actor/director relationship with Spielberg, as well as the films they made together, \"Spielberg's sets are very different \u2013 everything has been so meticulously planned. You got to get this line out in 37 seconds. You do that for five years, you start to feel like not knowing what you're doing for a living.\" He concluded his point by stating: \"I don't like the movies that I made with Spielberg. The only movie that I liked that we made together was [the first] ''Transformers'' [film].\" Later in the interview, LaBeouf recited and criticised the advice given to him by Spielberg following the mixed reaction to both ''Kingdom of the Crystal Skull'', and LaBeouf's performance in the film. He claims Spielberg told him not to read about himself in the media, but LaBeouf felt irritated by what he perceived to be non-advice and a lack of understanding, saying \"There's no way to not do that. For me to not read that means I need to not take part in society. The generation previous to mine didn't have the immediate response [of the internet]. If you were Mark Hamill [in ''Star Wars''], you could lie to yourself. You could find the pockets of joy, and turn a blind eye to the shit over there.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Setoodeh|first1=Ramin|title=How Shia LaBeouf Stopped Drinking and Found the Career He Wanted|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/shia-labeouf-drinking-steven-spielberg-american-honey-1201851776/|website=Variety|publisher=Variety Media, LLC|accessdate=December 27, 2016|date=September 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Other===\n*In 1999, Spielberg, then a co-owner of [[DreamWorks Pictures|DreamWorks]], was involved in a heated debate in which the studio proposed building on [[wetland]]s near Los Angeles, though development was later dropped for economic reasons.<ref>{{cite news|title=Entertainment Spielberg Studio Plan axed|publisher=[[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]]|date=July 22, 1999|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/384010.stm|accessdate=October 30, 2006}}</ref>\n*In August 2007, [[Ai Weiwei]], artistic consultant for the [[Beijing National Stadium|Beijing Olympic Stadium]], known as the \"Bird's Nest\", accused those choreographing the Olympic opening ceremony, including Spielberg, of failing to live up to their responsibility as artists by allowing their work to be used by the Chinese government, which has suppressed human rights in China, including those of Ai's family, for the purpose of \"propaganda\". Ai said, \"It's disgusting. I don't like anyone who shamelessly abuses their profession, who makes no moral judgment.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Watts, Jonathan|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/editorials/archives/2007/08/11/2003373696|title=Olympic artist lashes out over PRC propaganda|work=[[Taipei Times]]|date=August 11, 2007|accessdate=July 6, 2008}}</ref>\n*On February 28, 2019, [[Anne Thompson (film journalist)|Anne Thompson]] of ''[[IndieWire]]'' reported that Spielberg is keen on pushing for rule changes at the [[Academy Awards]] (Oscars) regarding films that are distributed theatrically and through streaming, with Thompson sharing an [[Amblin Entertainment|Amblin]] spokesperson's quote: \"Steven feels strongly about the difference between the streaming and theatrical situation. He'll be happy if the others will join [his campaign] when that comes up [at the Academy Board of Governors meeting]. He will see what happens.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Thompson|first=Anne|title=The Spielberg vs. Netflix Battle Could Mean Collateral Damage for Indies at the Oscars|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/02/steven-spielberg-vs-netflix-oscar-academy-wars-1202047846/|accessdate=March 22, 2019|work=[[IndieWire]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation|Penske Business Media, LLC]]|date=February 28, 2019}}</ref> This, in addition to his March 2018 criticism of [[Netflix]]'s distribution strategy,<ref>{{cite news|last=Sims|first=David|title=Steven Spielberg's Netflix Fears|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/03/steven-spielbergs-netflix-fears/556550/|accessdate=March 22, 2019|work=[[The Atlantic]]|publisher=The Atlantic Monthly Group|date=March 27, 2018}}</ref> was then interpreted by others to be Spielberg campaigning against Netflix films being qualified for the Oscars,<ref>{{cite news|last=Hughes|first=William|title=Steven Spielberg is gunning to make sure Netflix never has another Oscars contender like ''Roma''|url=https://news.avclub.com/steven-spielberg-is-gunning-to-make-sure-netflix-never-1833005033|accessdate=March 22, 2019|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[Onion, Inc.]]|date=March 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Logan|first=Elizabeth|title=Hollywood Reacts to Steven Spielberg's Oscars Crusade Against Netflix|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/steven-spielberg-oscars-netflix|accessdate=March 22, 2019|work=[[W (magazine)|W]]|publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]]|date=March 3, 2019}}</ref> prompting reactions from [[Ava DuVernay]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Fuster|first=Jeremy|title=Ava DuVernay Opposes Steven Spielberg's Effort to Keep Netflix Out of the Oscars|url=https://www.thewrap.com/ava-duvernay-steven-spielberg-anti-netflix/|accessdate=March 22, 2019|work=[[TheWrap]]|publisher=TheWrap News Inc.|date=March 2, 2019}}</ref> [[J. C. Chandor]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Ryan|first=Mike|title='Triple Frontier' Director J.C. Chandor Explains Why Spielberg Is Wrong And Streaming Is The Future Of Movies|url=https://uproxx.com/movies/j-c-chandor-interview-triple-frontier-netflix-spielberg/|accessdate=March 22, 2019|work=[[UPROXX]]|publisher=Warner Music Inc.|date=March 14, 2019}}</ref> and [[Joe Berlinger]] among others.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lang|first=Brent|title=Steven Spielberg vs. Netflix: How Oscars Voters Are Reacting|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/awards/steven-spielberg-oscars-netflix-1203155528/|accessdate=March 22, 2019|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=Variety Media, LLC|date=March 5, 2019}}</ref> [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]] stated that Spielberg has \"actually said nothing\" regarding the situation with Netflix, adding that \"What happened is a journalist was onto a story about this and had heard a rumor about Steven. They called a spokesperson to get a comment and honestly, just twisted it around. One, Steven didn't say that, and two, he is not going to the academy in April with some sort of plan. But he has not opined at all, nor has he aligned with some specific thing.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Porter|first1=Rick|title=Jeffrey Katzenberg: Steven Spielberg Isn't Out to Get Netflix|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/jeffrey-katzenberg-steven-spielberg-isnt-get-netflix-1193263|accessdate=March 22, 2019|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=Valence Media|date=March 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[CinemaScore#List of A+ films|Directors with two films rated A+ by CinemaScore]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n284. Spielberg Among the Big Names Allegedly Burned by Madoff https://abcnews.go.com/GMA/story?id=6463587&page=1\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=5E80Tv7F3zIC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Steven Spielberg: interviews|publisher=Univ. Press of Mississippi|year=2000|isbn=978-1-57806-113-6|author1=Steven Spielberg|author2=Lester D. Friedman|author3=Brent Notbohm}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4UJQqBSFm8AC&pg=PP1|title=Steven Spielberg: Director of Blockbuster Films|publisher=Enslow Publishers, Inc.|year=2008|isbn=978-0-7660-2888-3|author=Laura Bufano Edge}}\n*{{c